{"title_page": "Micro", "text_new": "{{wiktionary|micro|micro-}}\n'''[https://www.studypointbihar.com/2020/04/macros-macros-are-most-powerful-tool-of.html Micro]''' may refer to:Macros are the most powerful tool of a software. Quite often while working with a software you need to enter or choose commands to perform a specific task. If this task is to performed repeatedly then it may times seems tiring and boring. In that case, a macro comes to rescue. \n\nA macro is a series of commands, keystrokes or other actions that are recorded under a name. Creating a macro simply involves recording a number of actions. After recording, when you run the macro then those actions are repeated. Behind the scenes, the application you're working in executes VBA code when you run a macro. Using a macro helps to \n\n-Speed up routine editing and formatting tasks. \n\n-Combine multiple commands into one. \n\n-Automate repetitive and complex tasks. \n\nMany application softwares support macros. Macros are supported in MS-Office by MS-Word, MS-Excel, MS-Powerpoint. Besides these many other softwares support them. Some of the application programs even contain the feature of predefined macros that you can use directly. You can also create your own macros to automate tasks you perform frequently. \n\nMacros can be simple containing a few steps or may be complex containing a number of steps. It may even include a macro allowing you to perform multiple tasks at a time. Due to large number of advantages offered with the use of macros these are nowadays used quite often. \n\nSome examples of macros :\n\n\u2022\t A macro created in MS-Word to perform the tasks such a find a word, replace and change its format to Bold and Font Size = 18\n\n\u2022\t A macro created in MS-Excel that selects a row of data, applies a specific format, sorts the data. \n\nIn order to create and run a macro in a PowerPoint presentation, Word document, Excel workbook, or any other file you must display the Developer tab. For this, click File tab >Options . As a result , Options dialog is displayed . Now click Customize Ribbon category and click the Developer check box ( if unchecked ) under Main Tabs heading on the right side of the dialog . Click OK button .\n\nAs a result, a Developer tab is added to the MS - Word, MS - Excel or MS - Powerpoint in which you are working.\n\nAs macros are small programs so it is likely that they may contain viruses . MS - Office provides you the opportunity to decide how you want to handle files that contain macros . For this , it provides Macro Security button . Clicking it , displays a Trust Center dialog that help you choose whether you want to disable all macros , disable Some macros , or enable all macros . When you choose the appropriate radio button , click OK button . \n\nBefore recording a file , you must make sure that the file in which you record them is macro enabled . To make a file macro enabled , open Save As dialog and in the Save As Type : drop down , choose Word Macro Enabled document if working in MSWord.\u00a0 Similarly for MS - Excel and MS - Powerpoint.\u00a0 A files that are macro enabled have the last letter in their extension.\u00a0 MS - Word (. docm), MIS Excel (.xlsm), MS - Powerpoint (. Pptim).\u00a0 Finally, click the Save button. \u00a0\n\nRECORD A MACR0\n\nTo record a macro in MS - Word or MS - Excel performs the following steps: \n\n1.\tClick the Record Macro button on the Developer tab.\u00a0 2. \n\n2.\t A Record dialog pops up.\u00a0 In the Macro name box, enter the name of the macro.\u00a0 You can also assign a keyboard shortcut or a toolbar button to the macro.\u00a0 From the Store Macro In Drop Down.\u00a0 Choose where you would like to store the macro you are just going to record.\u00a0 In the Description box, enter a precise description of what a macro does.\n\n3.\t Click OK button in dialog box . As a result , the Record Macro button in the Developer tab changes to Stop Recording button . In addition , Pause Recording button is also enabled in MS - Word . \n\n4.\t Now carry out the actions you want to record . For example , Select a font type , font size , choose page color or page border etc.\n\n5.\tTo stop , recording your macro , click Stop Recording button on the Developer tab . The macro will be recorded . \n\nThe following points should be remembered while working with macros ,\n\n- Avoid using mouse as you record a macro . The macro recorder may interpret some mouse actions unintentionally.\n\n- Take account of all settings exclusively while recording a macro . For example , if you set font size to 16 points and do not change the font type then it will assume default settings . \n\n-Record macro button is not available if an administrator has not installed VBA component from MS Office . Even if it is installed , administrator can prevent users from accessing macros and VBA . \n\n-Macro names can be 80 characters long and begin with a letter and can include numbers and underscore . However , Blank space , Symbols and punctuation characters are not allowed . \n\n-Store macro in template if you would like to run a macro in all documents you create with your template.\n\nRUN A MACRO \n\nTo run a macro performs the following steps: \n\n1.\u00a0 Click the Macros button from the View tab or the Developer tab or press Alt + F8. \u00a0\n\n2.\u00a0 A Macros dialog pops up.\u00a0 Select the macros you want to run. \n\n3.\u00a0 Click Run button. \n\n\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0If you want to stop a macro that is running, then press Ctrl + Break keys.\n\nIn addition to the Run button, there are buttons to edit a macro.\u00a0 If you click the Edit button, a Visual Basic Editor window is displayed.\u00a0 It displays the code for handling the selected macro.\u00a0 You can modify this code if you are aware of VB.\u00a0 Similarly there are other buttons.\u00a0 We leave it for the readers to understand. \u00a0\n\nIn addition to this technique you can also run a macro when it is made as part of the Quick Access Toolbar.\u00a0 To make a macro as a button in the Quick Access toolbar, click Customize Quick Access Toolbar and choose More Commands.\u00a0 General Chat Chat Lounge\u00a0 General Chat Chat Lounge\u00a0 From the context menu.\u00a0 As a result, the Word Options dialog is displayed.\u00a0 From the Choose Commands from: drop down choose Macros.\u00a0 As a result, the list of already created macros appears in the list (like Normal. New Macros. Macro1).\u00a0 Click the Add button and then the OK button.\u00a0 As a result, the selected macro will be added to the Quick Access Toolbar.<!-- \n\nDo not add a link that merely contains part of the page title, or a link that includes the page title in a longer proper name, where there is no significant risk of confusion or reference. See WP:PTM \n\n-->\n{{toc right}}\n==Measurement==\n* [[micro-]] (\u03bc), a prefix in the SI and other systems of units denoting a factor of 10<sup>\u22126</sup> (one millionth)\n\n==Places==\n* [[Micro, North Carolina]], town in U.S.\n\n==People==\n* [[DJ Micro]], (born Michael Marsicano) an American trance DJ and producer\n*[[Chii Tomiya]] (\u90fd\u5bae \u3061\u3044, born 1991), Japanese female professional wrestler, ring name Micro\n\n==Arts, entertainment, and media==\n* [[Micro (comics)]], often known as Micro, a character in Marvel Comics\n* [[Micro (novel)|''Micro'' (novel)]], techno-thriller by Michael Crichton, published posthumously in 2011 \n* [[Micro (Thai band)]], a Thai rock band formed in 1983\n* ''[[IEEE Micro]]'', a peer-reviewed scientific journal\n\n==Brands and enterprises==\n* [[Micro Cars]], Sri Lankan automobile company, established 1995\n* [[Micro Center]], an American computer department store, established 1979\n* [[Micro ISV]] (mISV or \u03bcISV), a term for a small independent software vendor \n\n==Computing==\n* ''Micro'', a mostly-obsolete term for a [[microcomputer]], e.g.:\n**[[BBC Micro]]\n* BBC [[Micro Bit]], or micro:bit, an ARM-based embedded system for computer education  \n* [[MICRO Relational Database Management System]], an early set-theoretic database management system\n* [[Micro T-Kernel]], \u03bcT-Kernel, a real-time operating system\n\n==Other uses==\n* Micro, type of bus [[transport in Lima]], Peru\n* [[AAA battery]], known as a micro cell\n* [[Micro kart]], a one-passenger mini go-kart\n* [[Game Boy Micro]], a 2005 Nintendo handheld and the final model in the Game Boy line\n\n== See also ==\n* {{look from}}\n* {{in title}}\n* [[Macro (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Micromachinery]]\n* [[Microstate]]\n* [[Mikro (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Mikra (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "text_old": "{{wiktionary|micro|micro-}}\n'''Micro''' may refer to:\n<!-- \n\nDo not add a link that merely contains part of the page title, or a link that includes the page title in a longer proper name, where there is no significant risk of confusion or reference. See WP:PTM \n\n-->\n{{toc right}}\n==Measurement==\n* [[micro-]] (\u03bc), a prefix in the SI and other systems of units denoting a factor of 10<sup>\u22126</sup> (one millionth)\n\n==Places==\n* [[Micro, North Carolina]], town in U.S.\n\n==People==\n* [[DJ Micro]], (born Michael Marsicano) an American trance DJ and producer\n*[[Chii Tomiya]] (\u90fd\u5bae \u3061\u3044, born 1991), Japanese female professional wrestler, ring name Micro\n\n==Arts, entertainment, and media==\n* [[Micro (comics)]], often known as Micro, a character in Marvel Comics\n* [[Micro (novel)|''Micro'' (novel)]], techno-thriller by Michael Crichton, published posthumously in 2011 \n* [[Micro (Thai band)]], a Thai rock band formed in 1983\n* ''[[IEEE Micro]]'', a peer-reviewed scientific journal\n\n==Brands and enterprises==\n* [[Micro Cars]], Sri Lankan automobile company, established 1995\n* [[Micro Center]], an American computer department store, established 1979\n* [[Micro ISV]] (mISV or \u03bcISV), a term for a small independent software vendor \n\n==Computing==\n* ''Micro'', a mostly-obsolete term for a [[microcomputer]], e.g.:\n**[[BBC Micro]]\n* BBC [[Micro Bit]], or micro:bit, an ARM-based embedded system for computer education  \n* [[MICRO Relational Database Management System]], an early set-theoretic database management system\n* [[Micro T-Kernel]], \u03bcT-Kernel, a real-time operating system\n\n==Other uses==\n* Micro, type of bus [[transport in Lima]], Peru\n* [[AAA battery]], known as a micro cell\n* [[Micro kart]], a one-passenger mini go-kart\n* [[Game Boy Micro]], a 2005 Nintendo handheld and the final model in the Game Boy line\n\n== See also ==\n* {{look from}}\n* {{in title}}\n* [[Macro (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Micromachinery]]\n* [[Microstate]]\n* [[Mikro (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Mikra (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "2409:4055:31f:8c28:64e3:f0ff:fe3c:45ea", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(How to record a macro)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micro"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy John Liautaud", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jimmy John Liautaud\n| image              = Jimmy John Liautaud 2018 Headshot.jpg\n| alt                = Jimmy John's Founder Jimmy John Liautaud\n| caption            = Jimmy John Liautaud\n| birth_name         = James John Liautaud\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1964|01|12}}\n| birth_place        = Arlington Heights, Illinois\n| children           = 3\n| mother             = Gina Gudaityte Liautaud\n| father             = [[James P. Liautaud]]\n| spouse             = Leslie Liautaud\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Restaurateur \n| years_active       = 1983\u2013present\n| known_for          = Founding Jimmy John's sandwich chain\n| networth           = [[US dollar|US$]]1.7 billion (October 2018)<ref name=\"ForbesBillionaire\">{{cite web |title=Jimmy John Liautaud |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/jimmy-john-liautaud/ |website=[[Forbes]].com |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n| website            = {{URL|https://jimmyjohnliautaud.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''James John Liautaud''' (born January 12, 1964) is the founder and former chairman of [[Jimmy John's]] sandwich chain.<ref name=\"Bloomberg: Jimmy John's Founder Abandons IPO, Saying He's Not a Wall Street Guy\">{{cite web|last1=Giammona|first1=Craig|title=Jimmy John's Founder Abandons IPO, Saying He's Not a Wall Street Guy|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-12-01/jimmy-john-s-ceo-abandons-ipo-saying-he-s-not-a-wall-street-guy|website=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Liautaud was included in the [[The World's Billionaires|Forbes list of the world's wealthiest people]]. At this time, [[Forbes]] estimated Liautaud's documented wealth at $1.7 billion.<ref name=\"ForbesBillionaire\"/>\n\n==Family and early life==\n[[File:James P. Liautaud with Son, Jimmy John&#039;s Owner Jimmy John Liautaud.jpg|thumb|left|James P. Liautaud with Son, Jimmy John&#039;s Founder Jimmy John Liautaud]]\nLiautaud was born in [[Arlington Heights, Illinois|Arlington Heights]], Illinois on January 12, 1964.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sasvari |first1=Tom |title=200-foot super yacht 'Rock.It' visits Gore Bay |url=https://www.manitoulin.ca/200-foot-super-yacht-rock-it-visits-gore-bay/ |accessdate=5 March 2019 |newspaper=Manitoulin Expositor |date=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Horatio Alger Association\">{{cite web |title=Jimmy John Liautaud - Member Profile |url=https://horatioalger.org/members/member-detail/jimmy-john-liautaud/ |website=[[Horatio Alger Association of Distinguished Americans]] |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> His father is [[James P. Liautaud|James Liautaud]], longtime entrepreneur, and his mother is Gina Gudaityte Liautaud. He was born the second of four siblings, with brothers Greg and Robby Liautaud and a sister Lara Liautaud Berry.<ref name=\"Chicago Business:Father of Jimmy John's owner dies, helped found business\">{{cite news|last1=Kapos|first1=Shia|title=Father of Jimmy John's owner dies, helped found business|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20151031/BLOGS03/151039965/father-of-jimmy-johns-owner-dies-helped-found-business|magazine=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=31 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Horatio Alger Association\" /> He attended high school at [[Elgin Academy (Elgin, Illinois)|Elgin Academy]], a private prep school in Elgin, Illinois, where he became close with and was influenced by the dean, James Lyons.<ref name=\"New York Times: Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian\">{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Dirk|title=Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/31/education/31jimmy.html?_r=0|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=30 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe studied at [[Eastern Illinois University]], but left to grow his up-and-coming restaurant business.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune: Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO\">{{cite web|last1=Bomkamp|first1=Samantha|title=Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-jimmy-johns-1104-biz-20151103-story.html|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Restaurant career==\n[[File:Jimmy John Liautaud and Jimmy John&#039;s Franchise Owner Drew Brees.jpg|thumb|right|Jimmy John Liautaud and Jimmy John&#039;s Franchise Owner Drew Brees]]\n\nAfter Liautaud graduated from high school in 1982, his father offered him a loan of $25,000 to open a business on the condition that when the business failed, he would enlist in the [[United States Army|US Army]].<ref name=\"New York Times: Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian\" /> Although his father wanted him to enlist, he agreed to loan the money in exchange for a 48% stake in the business. Initially Jimmy John wanted to open a hot dog stand, but after visiting numerous such stands throughout the summer of 1982, he realized the $25,000 would not be enough for such a venture.<ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\">{{cite web|last1=Casey|first1=Erin|title=Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud|url=http://www.success.com/article/success-stories-jimmy-john-liautaud|magazine=SUCCESS Magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715011308/http://www.success.com/article/success-stories-jimmy-john-liautaud |archive-date=2018-07-15|date=4 March 2009}}</ref> After a chance encounter at a sandwich shop, Jimmy John realized that he could open a sandwich shop within his available budget by purchasing premium meats at a neighborhood market and baking his own bread. With the help of his family as tasters, he decided to put four sandwiches on his original menu. On January 13, 1983 Jimmy John's Gourmet Sandwiches opened in [[Charleston, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Bloomberg: Jimmy John's Founder Abandons IPO, Saying He's Not a Wall Street Guy\" /><ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\" /> Due to the poor location of his first store, Liautaud decided to include delivery of his sandwiches to boost sales. He began by bringing samples door-to-door to the nearby Eastern Illinois University dorms.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune: Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO\" /> By the end of his first year, the restaurant started making a profit. At the end of his second year, Liautaud was able to purchase his father's share in the business and he became sole owner. The business continued to grow, and he was able to open his second and third shops in 1986 and 1987.\n\nIn 1988, Liautaud met businessman Jamie Coulter. At the time, Coulter was a [[Pizza Hut]] Franchisee, and later founded and ran [[Lone Star Steakhouse & Saloon|Lone Star Steakhouse and Saloon]] and other chains. Coulter helped Liautaud take his business to the next level. In 1994 he sold his first Jimmy John's [[franchising|franchise]], in addition to the 10 stores owned by Liautaud himself.<ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\" /><ref name=\"Advertising Age Interview of Jimmy John Liautaud\">{{cite web|last1=Wohl|first1=Jessica|title=Sub Shop Owner Jimmy John Weighs IPO but Isn't Sure He Has the Stomach for It|url=http://adage.com/article/cmo-strategy/detail-oriented-jimmy-john-a-stadium-signage-auditor/301198/|magazine=[[Ad Age]]|accessdate=8 September 2016|date=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nBy 2002, the company had about 200 stores, 10% of which were corporate stores that Liautaud oversaw himself. Sales at the stores managed by Liautaud were outpacing the franchised stores by a wide margin. Together with his partner, and now President & CEO, James North, he visited 70 of the poorest-performing stores. After 18 months of getting the stores \u201cback to basics\u201d and instilling in them \u201csome of that initial spark\u201d, he was able to help the stores become more profitable.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune: Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO\" />\n\n[[File:Jimmy John Liautaud with Jimmy John&#039;s President James North.jpg|thumb|left|Jimmy John Liautaud with Jimmy John&#039;s President James North]]\nIn January 2007, Liautaud selected [[Weston Presidio]], a private-equity firm, to help acquire better locations for the expanding company. Weston Presidio bought a 33% stake in the company, and during the first year closed on over 100 real estate deals.<ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\" />\n\nIn September 2016, [[Roark Capital Group]] agreed to purchase a majority stake in Liautaud's company, as Weston Presidio sold their minority investment after 10 years. Terms of the transaction were not immediately disclosed, though it was later clarified that Liautaud retained 35% ownership of the company as part of the deal.<ref name=\"Jimmy John Liautaud Talks!\">{{cite web|last1=Frost|first1=Peter|title=Jimmy John Talks|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20170121/ISSUE01/170129971/jimmy-john-talks|magazine=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|accessdate=29 January 2017|date=21 January 2017}}</ref> As part of the agreement, Liautaud, as the company's founder and largest individual shareholder, continued as chairman of the board.<ref name=\"Roark Capital Buys Majority Stake in Jimmy John's\">{{cite web|last1=Hufford|first1=Austen|title=Roark Capital Buys Majority Stake in Jimmy John's|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/roark-capital-buys-majority-stake-in-jimmy-johns-1473341501|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=11 September 2016|date=8 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Arby's owner buys Jimmy John's majority stake\">{{cite web|last1=Frost|first1=Peter|title=Arby's owner buys Jimmy John's majority stake|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20160908/NEWS07/160909882/jimmy-johns-sells-majority-stake-to-arbys-owner|magazine=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|accessdate=15 September 2016|date=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2018 book, Dick Portillo of Portillo's Restaurants called Liautaud his \"good friend\" and relayed that Liautaud tried to buy Portillo's before it was ultimately sold to Berkshire Partners.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Portillo |first1=Dick |title=Out of the Dog House |date=27 November 2018 |publisher=Triumph Books |isbn=9781641252478 |page=239}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Roark's [[Inspire Brands]] announced it was acquiring Jimmy John's for an unspecified amount in a deal unanimously approved by Liautaud and the rest of the Jimmy John's Board of Directors.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inspire Brands to Acquire Jimmy John\u2019s |url=https://inspirebrands.com/inspire-brands-to-acquire-jimmy-johns/ |accessdate=9 October 2019 |publisher=[[Inspire Brands]] |date=25 September 2019}}</ref> At the close of the deal, Liautaud said that he will step down as chairman of the company and transition to become an adviser to the brand.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haddon |first1=Heather |title=Arby\u2019s Parent to Acquire Jimmy John\u2019s |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/inspire-brands-to-add-jimmy-johns-to-its-restaurant-roster-11569408901 |accessdate=9 October 2019 |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=25 September 2019}}</ref> The acquisition was completed on October 18.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruggless |first1=Ron |title=Inspire completes purchase of Jimmy John\u2019s |url=https://www.nrn.com/mergers-acquisitions/inspire-completes-purchase-jimmy-john-s |accessdate=21 October 2019 |work=Nation's Restaurant News |date=18 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2008, Liautaud donated $1 million to his high school, Elgin Academy, on the condition that the building constructed using his donation bear not only his name, but also the name of the man who had been the dean of the school when Liautaud attended: James Lyons.<ref name=\"New York Times: Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian\" />\n[[File:Jimmy John's Owner Jimmy John Liautaud Presents $1 Million Check to Folds of Honor.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Jimmy John Liautaud donating $1 million to Major Dan Rooney and Folds of Honor.]]\nIn 2011, Liautaud and his wife pledged $1 million toward the construction of the new [[Champaign County, Illinois|Champaign County]] YMCA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liautauds pledge $1 million to new Champaign County Y|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2011-06-23/liautauds-pledge-1-million-new-champaign-county-y.html|accessdate=9 November 2017|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign\u2013Urbana)]]|date=23 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Liautaud donated $1 million to the Folds of Honor Foundation, an organization that supports the families of fallen soldiers.<ref name=\"Tulsa World: Jimmy John's to donate $1 million to Owasso-based Folds of Honor\">{{cite web|last1=Staff Reports|title=Jimmy John's to donate $1 million to Owasso-based Folds of Honor|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/communities/owasso/news/jimmy-john-s-to-donate-million-to-owasso-based-folds/article_dba8a6a0-a4ec-510e-9579-35104cec3eb9.html|website=[[Tulsa World]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Liautaud and his wife, Leslie, donated $2 million to help Brewster Academy kick off the fundraising for their new residence hall to house 22 students and 4 faculty residences.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Braiterman|first1=Lisa|title=New Residence Hall Underway|url=http://blogs.brewsteracademy.org/off-and-digging/|accessdate=9 November 2017|website=[[Brewster Academy]]|date=4 August 2017}}</ref> In May 2018, the new residence opened, and is called \"Toad Hall\" after a common mispronunciation of the family's last name.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brewster Academy Opens Toad Hall Following Gift from Leslie and Jimmy John Liautaud |url=http://blogs.brewsteracademy.org/brewster-academy-opens-toad-hall-following-gift-from-leslie-and-jimmy-john-liautaud/ |accessdate=9 January 2019 |website=[[Brewster Academy]] |date=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Camp Southern Ground, a non-profit summer camp founded by musician [[Zac Brown Band|Zac Brown]], announced that the Liautauds had donated over $3.2 million to date to help build the camp's first residential lodge and fund ongoing operations. In non-summer months, the camp's facilities are used to support military veterans and their families transitioning back to civilian life.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zac Brown's Camp Southern Ground Receives $2.2 Million Donation From Jimmy John's Owner, Jimmy John Liautaud |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/zac-browns-camp-southern-ground-receives-2-2-million-donation-from-jimmy-johns-owner-jimmy-john-liautaud-300782407.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=Camp Southern Ground |date=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Liautaud Family Foundation directed $1.291 million to the Horatio Alger Association to support scholarships for underprivileged students in 2019.<ref name=\"IP1\">{{cite news |last1=Adeniji |first1=Ade |title=Sandwich Chain Billionaire Jimmy John Liautaud and His Family Get More Strategic About Their Giving |url=https://www.insidephilanthropy.com/home/2019/12/4/a-sandwich-chain-billionaire-and-his-family-gets-more-strategic-about-their-giving |accessdate=15 January 2020 |publisher=[[Inside Philanthropy]] |date=4 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nLiautaud partnered with his father to create with an endowment gift of $5 million, the Liautaud Graduate School of Business at the University of Illinois-Chicago.<ref name=\"IP1\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Liautaud Family Gives $5 Million to Establish UIC Graduate Business School |url=https://www.newswise.com/articles/liautaud-family-gives-5-million-to-establish-uic-graduate-business-school |accessdate=15 January 2020 |publisher=University of Illinois at Chicago |date=14 November 2003}}</ref>\n\nThe Liautauds donated $1 million to Chicago\u2019s Youth Guidance Becoming a Man program, which helps disadvantaged young men learn how to handle tough life challenges and give them the tools to succeed in the future.<ref name=\"IP1\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Youth Guidance Expands Becoming A Man Program To Reach 4,000 At-Risk Chicago Males |url=https://www.prlog.org/12592584-youth-guidance-expands-becoming-man-program-to-reach-4000-at-risk-chicago-males.html |accessdate=15 January 2020 |publisher=Youth Guidance |date=6 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOther causes supported by the Liautauds include: the Frances Nelson Smile Healthy Dental Clinic,<ref name=\"News-Gazette: Liautaud donates $300,000 to benefit Frances Nelson\">{{cite web|last1=Pressey|first1=Debra|title=Liautaud donates $300,000 to benefit Frances Nelson|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2013-04-08/liautaud-donates-300000-benefit-frances-nelson.html|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign\u2013Urbana)]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=8 April 2013}}</ref> the Kickapoo Rail Trail,<ref name=\"Jimmy John's owner gives $150,000 to Illinois trail project\">{{cite web|title=Jimmy John's owner gives $150,000 to Illinois trail project|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/illinois/jimmy-john-s-owner-gives-to-illinois-trail-project/article_0ba8f685-78de-5704-8e00-8398bc32318c.html|newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|accessdate=8 September 2016|date=3 July 2016}}</ref> Crisis Nursery in Urbana, Illinois,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jimmy John Liautaud & the Liautaud Family Foundation|url=https://crisisnursery.net/jimmy-john-liautaud-family-foundation/|website=Crisis Nursery|accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> Champaign County's Youth Assessment Center,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wickman|first1=Natalie|title=Youth Assessment Center to settle on new site by spring|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2018-01-11/youth-assessment-center-settle-new-site-spring.html|accessdate=14 February 2018|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign-Urbana)]]|date=11 January 2018}}</ref>, [[Champaign Unit 4 School District|Champaign Unit 4]] schools,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Lyndsay|title=Students, staff are 'totally pumped' about planned projects|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2018-01-22/students-staff-are-totally-pumped-about-planned-projects.html|accessdate=14 February 2018|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign-Urbana)]]|date=22 January 2018}}</ref> Christmas layaway purchases,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jensen |first1=Jennifer |title=$80,000 in layaways paid by generous donation |url=https://www.wcia.com/news/local-news/-80-000-in-layaways-paid-off-by-generous-donation/1651895860 |accessdate=12 December 2018 |work=[[WCIA]] |date=10 December 2018}}</ref> the American Heart Association, the Mayo Clinic Center for Individualized Medicine, MD Anderson, the Pancreatic Cancer Action Network, the Lurie Children\u2019s Hospital of Chicago, the Goodman Theater, and the Detroit Symphony.<ref name=\"IP1\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Jimmy John Liautaud and Leslie Liautaud: Donor Grants |url=https://www.insidephilanthropy.com/donors/jimmy-john-and-leslie-liautaud-donor-grants |publisher=[[Inside Philanthropy]] |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nLiautaud is a member of the University of Illinois at Chicago's Chicago Area Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"Institute for Entrepreneurial Studies\">{{cite web|title=2015 Chicago Area Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame Inductees|url=https://ies.uic.edu/entrepreneurship-hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-members/|website=Institute for Entrepreneurial Studies|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he was named to Chicago's \u201c40 Under 40\u201d by Crain's Chicago Business.<ref name=\"CRAIN'S: \tJIMMY JOHN LIAUTAUD | 39Founder, chairman and CEOJimmy John's Gourmet Sandwich Shops\">{{cite news|title=JIMMY JOHN LIAUTAUD, Founder, chairman and CEO Jimmy John's Gourmet Sandwich Shops|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20031029/PAGES/1426/40-under-40-2003|magazine=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he was named the [[Ernst & Young|Ernst & Young Food & Beverage Entrepreneur of the Year]] in Illinois. The winners were selected by an independent panel of judges composed of local community and business leaders.<ref name=\"Illinois Entrepreneurs Named Ernst & Young Entrepreneur Of The Year\u00ae 2004 Award Winners\">{{cite web|title=Illinois Entrepreneurs Named Ernst & Young Entrepreneur Of The Year\u00ae 2004 Award Winners|url=http://www.lakecapital.com/pdfs/hcg1505.pdf|website=Lakecapital.com|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> In the same year, he was given the Lifetime Achievement Award at the National CEO Conference and inducted into the Collegiate Entrepreneurs' Organization Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"QSR Magazine\">{{cite news|title=\"Jimmy John\" in CEO Hall of Fame|url=https://www.qsrmagazine.com/news/jimmy-john-ceo-hall-fame|magazine=QSR Magazine|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n \nIn 2007, Liautaud delivered the commencement speech at his alma mater, now known as the Liautaud-Lyons Upper School, a program of Elgin Academy.<ref name=\"New York Times: Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian\" />\n\nIn 2012, Liautaud was awarded the Nation's Restaurant News Golden Chain award for outstanding accomplishments that have benefited consumers in the food industry.<ref name=\"The Daily Meal: Meet the 2012 Golden Chain Award winners\">{{cite web|last1=[[Nation's Restaurant News]] Staff Writer|title=Meet the 2012 Golden Chain Award winners|url=http://www.thedailymeal.com/meet-2012-golden-chain-award-winners|website=The Daily Meal|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=9 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, he was named Franchise Times' \"Dealmaker of the Year\" for the deal that brought [[Roark Capital Group]] in as the company's new majority owner. Beth Ewen, FT's editor-in-chief called the deal \"one of the best private equity deals of all time in the restaurant business.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lazare|first1=Lewis|title=Jimmy John's founder hailed as king of the dealmakers|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/chicago/news/2017/03/15/jimmy-johns-founder-hailed-as-king-of-the.html|accessdate=22 March 2017|work=[[Chicago Business Journal]]|date=15 March 2017}}</ref> In December of that year, Liautaud was chosen to receive the Horatio Alger Award for 2018. The [[Horatio Alger Association of Distinguished Americans]] recognizes people who have overcome personal challenges to achieve personal and professional success.<ref>{{cite news|title=Owner, Founder & Chairman of Jimmy John's Gourmet Sandwiches, Jimmy John Liautaud, to Receive 2018 Horatio Alger Award|url=https://horatioalger.org/haa_news/owner-founder-chairman-of-jimmy-johns-gourmet-sandwiches-jimmy-john-liautaud-to-receive-2018-horatio-alger-award/|accessdate=24 December 2017|website=[[Horatio Alger Association of Distinguished Americans]]|date=5 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pressey|first1=Debra|title=Jimmy John Liautaud part of Horatio Alger Association's Class of 2018|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2017-12-15/jimmy-john-liautaud-part-horatio-alger-associations-class-2018.html|accessdate=24 December 2017|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign-Urbana)]]|date=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Public speaking ==\nLiautaud speaks at a broad range of venues, including high schools;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apg-wi.com/spooner_advocate/news/regional/sandwich-mogul-jimmy-john-shares-advice-with-northwood-students/article_bd97be08-1951-11e6-bb06-23323557cdd7.html|title=Sandwich mogul 'Jimmy John' shares advice with Northwood students|last=ADMINISTRATOR|first=JEAN SERUM {{!}} NORTHWOOD SCHOOL|website=APG of Wisconsin|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref> colleges and universities;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.kellogg.northwestern.edu/inside/2017/03/17/growth-scaling-and-life-lessons-from-jimmy-johns-founder-ceo/|title=Growth, Scaling, and Life Lessons from Jimmy John Liautaud, Founder, Owner & Chairman of Jimmy John\u2019s {{!}} Inside Kellogg|website=blogs.kellogg.northwestern.edu|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mendoza.nd.edu/news/jimmy-john-brings-his-story-of-sandwich-franchise-success-to-notre-dame/|title=Jimmy John brings his story of sandwich franchise success to Notre Dame - Notre Dame Business|website=Mendoza College of Business|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.kellogg.northwestern.edu/inside/2019/06/18/jimmy-john-liautaud-emba/|title=Jimmy John Liautaud Shares His Story with EMBA Students in Miami|website=blogs.kellogg.northwestern.edu|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref> and community spaces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://champaign.org/event/start-and-grow-your-business-guest-speaker-jimmy-john-liautaud-1287660|title=Start and Grow Your Business: Guest Speaker Jimmy John Liautaud|website=champaign.org|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox-companies.com/about-2/giving-back/|title=Community Involvement|date=2014-07-25|website=Fox Companies|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref>\n\n==Hunting==\nLiautaud is an avid hunter and fisherman. In an interview in 2015 with the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', Liautaud said that the largest misconception about him is that people still connect him to photos of him posing with big game from 10 years ago. According to Liautaud, he used to hunt [[Big five game|big game in Africa]] on legally organized [[safari]]s, but he no longer does.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune: Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO\" /> Starting in 2015, his hunting prompted people to call for a [[boycott]] of his business.<ref name=\"Rizzo\">{{cite news|last1=Rizzo|first1=Lillian|title=Jimmy John's Faces Boycott Call Over Founder's Trophy Hunting|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/privateequity/2015/08/05/jimmy-johns-faces-boycott-call-over-founders-trophy-hunting/|accessdate=28 October 2016|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=5 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLiautaud is married to cum dumpster, dancer, playwright, actress, and choreographer Leslie Liautaud and has three children, Spencer, Lucy, and Fred.<ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\" /><ref name=\"CHAMBANAMOMS.COM Chambana Mom to Know: Leslie Liautaud Chambana Mom to Know: Leslie Liautaud\">{{cite web|last1=Editors|title= Chambana Mom to Know: Leslie Liautaud Chambana Mom to Know: Leslie Liautaud|url=http://www.chambanamoms.com/2011/10/12/chambana-mom-to-know-leslie-liautaud/|website=chambanamoms.com|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=12 October 2011}}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2016|reason=Appears to be a local blog}}</ref> Liautaud is an investor in wines and vineyards, at least one of which has been featured on the cover of ''[[Wine Spectator]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.franchisetimes.com/April-2017/How-Jimmy-Johns-landed-FTs-deal-of-the-year/ |title=How Jimmy John's landed FT's deal of the year |work=[[Franchise Times]] |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=April 2, 2017 |first=Beth |last=Ewen}}</ref> He also owns thousands of acres of farmland in Central Illinois.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McKinstry|first1=Erin|title=As generations age, farm owners less connected to their land|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/state_news/as-generations-age-farm-owners-less-connected-to-their-land/article_19094154-441a-11e8-9f0b-8336aac36649.html|newspaper=[[Columbia Missourian]]|accessdate=30 April 2018|date=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLiautaud also owns a superyacht named [[ROCK.IT (yacht)|ROCK.IT]], a 198-foot ship built with his input by Feadship in 2014. The ship, which can accommodate ten guests with a crew of 13,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Larry |title=Jimmy John's $100 million yacht visits Ogdensburg |url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/news05/jimmy-johns-100-million-yacht-visits-ogdensburg-20161004 |accessdate=20 November 2018 |newspaper=[[Watertown Daily Times]] |date=4 October 2016}}</ref> has been a finalist for a few yacht awards<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bednarova |first1=Zuzana |title=World Superyacht Awards 2015 Finalists |url=http://www.charterworld.com/news/world-superyacht-awards-2015-finalists |website=CharterWorld.com |publisher=[[Boat International Media]] |accessdate=20 November 2018 |date=3 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Finalists announced for the ShowBoats Design Awards 2016 |url=https://www.boatinternational.com/luxury-yacht-events/design-and-innovation-awards/finalists-announced-for-the-showboats-design-awards-2016--28653 |website=[[Boat International Media]] |accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> and been featured in a number of industry publications.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mower |first1=Marilyn |title=Rock.It \u2014 the hip, modern Feadship yacht with a touch of class |url=https://www.boatinternational.com/yachts/editorial-features/rockit-the-hip-modern-feadship-yacht-with-a-touch-of-class--29481 |website=[[Boat International Media]] |accessdate=20 November 2018 |date=25 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=From sandwiches to superyachts: Inside Jimmy John's 197' Feadship |url=https://archive.org/details/ShowBoats_Intl_March_2016 |work=ShowBoats International|publisher=[[Boat International Media]] |pages=104-114 |date=6 March 2016 |accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://jimmyjohnliautaud.com/ Jimmy John Liautaud's official website]\n* [https://www.jimmyjohns.com/about-us/our-story/ Jimmy John's story by founder Jimmy John Liautaud]\n* [https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=39564257&privcapId=36597434 Jimmy John Liautaud's Businessweek bio]\n* {{IMDb name|6908472}}\n* [https://www.crunchbase.com/person/jimmy-john-liautaud Jimmy John Liautaud on CrunchBase]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liautaud, James John}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American people of Lithuanian descent]]\n[[Category:Eastern Illinois University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Arlington Heights, Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jimmy John Liautaud\n| image              = Jimmy John Liautaud 2018 Headshot.jpg\n| alt                = Jimmy John's Founder Jimmy John Liautaud\n| caption            = Jimmy John Liautaud\n| birth_name         = James John Liautaud\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1964|01|12}}\n| birth_place        = Arlington Heights, Illinois\n| children           = 3\n| mother             = Gina Gudaityte Liautaud\n| father             = [[James P. Liautaud]]\n| spouse             = Leslie Liautaud\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Restaurateur \n| years_active       = 1983\u2013present\n| known_for          = Founding Jimmy John's sandwich chain\n| networth           = [[US dollar|US$]]1.7 billion (October 2018)<ref name=\"ForbesBillionaire\">{{cite web |title=Jimmy John Liautaud |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/jimmy-john-liautaud/ |website=[[Forbes]].com |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n| website            = {{URL|https://jimmyjohnliautaud.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''James John Liautaud''' (born January 12, 1964) is the founder and former chairman of [[Jimmy John's]] sandwich chain.<ref name=\"Bloomberg: Jimmy John's Founder Abandons IPO, Saying He's Not a Wall Street Guy\">{{cite web|last1=Giammona|first1=Craig|title=Jimmy John's Founder Abandons IPO, Saying He's Not a Wall Street Guy|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-12-01/jimmy-john-s-ceo-abandons-ipo-saying-he-s-not-a-wall-street-guy|website=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Liautaud was included in the [[The World's Billionaires|Forbes list of the world's wealthiest people]]. At this time, [[Forbes]] estimated Liautaud's documented wealth at $1.7 billion.<ref name=\"ForbesBillionaire\"/>\n\n==Family and early life==\n[[File:James P. Liautaud with Son, Jimmy John&#039;s Owner Jimmy John Liautaud.jpg|thumb|left|James P. Liautaud with Son, Jimmy John&#039;s Founder Jimmy John Liautaud]]\nLiautaud was born in [[Arlington Heights, Illinois|Arlington Heights]], Illinois on January 12, 1964.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sasvari |first1=Tom |title=200-foot super yacht 'Rock.It' visits Gore Bay |url=https://www.manitoulin.ca/200-foot-super-yacht-rock-it-visits-gore-bay/ |accessdate=5 March 2019 |newspaper=Manitoulin Expositor |date=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Horatio Alger Association\">{{cite web |title=Jimmy John Liautaud - Member Profile |url=https://horatioalger.org/members/member-detail/jimmy-john-liautaud/ |website=[[Horatio Alger Association of Distinguished Americans]] |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> His father is [[James P. Liautaud|James Liautaud]], longtime entrepreneur, and his mother is Gina Gudaityte Liautaud. He was born the second of four siblings, with brothers Greg and Robby Liautaud and a sister Lara Liautaud Berry.<ref name=\"Chicago Business:Father of Jimmy John's owner dies, helped found business\">{{cite news|last1=Kapos|first1=Shia|title=Father of Jimmy John's owner dies, helped found business|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20151031/BLOGS03/151039965/father-of-jimmy-johns-owner-dies-helped-found-business|magazine=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=31 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Horatio Alger Association\" /> He attended high school at [[Elgin Academy (Elgin, Illinois)|Elgin Academy]], a private prep school in Elgin, Illinois, where he became close with and was influenced by the dean, James Lyons.<ref name=\"New York Times: Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian\">{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Dirk|title=Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/31/education/31jimmy.html?_r=0|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=30 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe studied at [[Eastern Illinois University]], but left to grow his up-and-coming restaurant business.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune: Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO\">{{cite web|last1=Bomkamp|first1=Samantha|title=Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-jimmy-johns-1104-biz-20151103-story.html|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Restaurant career==\n[[File:Jimmy John Liautaud and Jimmy John&#039;s Franchise Owner Drew Brees.jpg|thumb|right|Jimmy John Liautaud and Jimmy John&#039;s Franchise Owner Drew Brees]]\n\nAfter Liautaud graduated from high school in 1982, his father offered him a loan of $25,000 to open a business on the condition that when the business failed, he would enlist in the [[United States Army|US Army]].<ref name=\"New York Times: Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian\" /> Although his father wanted him to enlist, he agreed to loan the money in exchange for a 48% stake in the business. Initially Jimmy John wanted to open a hot dog stand, but after visiting numerous such stands throughout the summer of 1982, he realized the $25,000 would not be enough for such a venture.<ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\">{{cite web|last1=Casey|first1=Erin|title=Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud|url=http://www.success.com/article/success-stories-jimmy-john-liautaud|magazine=SUCCESS Magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715011308/http://www.success.com/article/success-stories-jimmy-john-liautaud |archive-date=2018-07-15|date=4 March 2009}}</ref> After a chance encounter at a sandwich shop, Jimmy John realized that he could open a sandwich shop within his available budget by purchasing premium meats at a neighborhood market and baking his own bread. With the help of his family as tasters, he decided to put four sandwiches on his original menu. On January 13, 1983 Jimmy John's Gourmet Sandwiches opened in [[Charleston, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Bloomberg: Jimmy John's Founder Abandons IPO, Saying He's Not a Wall Street Guy\" /><ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\" /> Due to the poor location of his first store, Liautaud decided to include delivery of his sandwiches to boost sales. He began by bringing samples door-to-door to the nearby Eastern Illinois University dorms.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune: Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO\" /> By the end of his first year, the restaurant started making a profit. At the end of his second year, Liautaud was able to purchase his father's share in the business and he became sole owner. The business continued to grow, and he was able to open his second and third shops in 1986 and 1987.\n\nIn 1988, Liautaud met businessman Jamie Coulter. At the time, Coulter was a [[Pizza Hut]] Franchisee, and later founded and ran [[Lone Star Steakhouse & Saloon|Lone Star Steakhouse and Saloon]] and other chains. Coulter helped Liautaud take his business to the next level. In 1994 he sold his first Jimmy John's [[franchising|franchise]], in addition to the 10 stores owned by Liautaud himself.<ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\" /><ref name=\"Advertising Age Interview of Jimmy John Liautaud\">{{cite web|last1=Wohl|first1=Jessica|title=Sub Shop Owner Jimmy John Weighs IPO but Isn't Sure He Has the Stomach for It|url=http://adage.com/article/cmo-strategy/detail-oriented-jimmy-john-a-stadium-signage-auditor/301198/|magazine=[[Ad Age]]|accessdate=8 September 2016|date=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nBy 2002, the company had about 200 stores, 10% of which were corporate stores that Liautaud oversaw himself. Sales at the stores managed by Liautaud were outpacing the franchised stores by a wide margin. Together with his partner, and now President & CEO, James North, he visited 70 of the poorest-performing stores. After 18 months of getting the stores \u201cback to basics\u201d and instilling in them \u201csome of that initial spark\u201d, he was able to help the stores become more profitable.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune: Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO\" />\n\n[[File:Jimmy John Liautaud with Jimmy John&#039;s President James North.jpg|thumb|left|Jimmy John Liautaud with Jimmy John&#039;s President James North]]\nIn January 2007, Liautaud selected [[Weston Presidio]], a private-equity firm, to help acquire better locations for the expanding company. Weston Presidio bought a 33% stake in the company, and during the first year closed on over 100 real estate deals.<ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\" />\n\nIn September 2016, [[Roark Capital Group]] agreed to purchase a majority stake in Liautaud's company, as Weston Presidio sold their minority investment after 10 years. Terms of the transaction were not immediately disclosed, though it was later clarified that Liautaud retained 35% ownership of the company as part of the deal.<ref name=\"Jimmy John Liautaud Talks!\">{{cite web|last1=Frost|first1=Peter|title=Jimmy John Talks|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20170121/ISSUE01/170129971/jimmy-john-talks|magazine=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|accessdate=29 January 2017|date=21 January 2017}}</ref> As part of the agreement, Liautaud, as the company's founder and largest individual shareholder, continued as chairman of the board.<ref name=\"Roark Capital Buys Majority Stake in Jimmy John's\">{{cite web|last1=Hufford|first1=Austen|title=Roark Capital Buys Majority Stake in Jimmy John's|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/roark-capital-buys-majority-stake-in-jimmy-johns-1473341501|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=11 September 2016|date=8 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Arby's owner buys Jimmy John's majority stake\">{{cite web|last1=Frost|first1=Peter|title=Arby's owner buys Jimmy John's majority stake|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20160908/NEWS07/160909882/jimmy-johns-sells-majority-stake-to-arbys-owner|magazine=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|accessdate=15 September 2016|date=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2018 book, Dick Portillo of Portillo's Restaurants called Liautaud his \"good friend\" and relayed that Liautaud tried to buy Portillo's before it was ultimately sold to Berkshire Partners.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Portillo |first1=Dick |title=Out of the Dog House |date=27 November 2018 |publisher=Triumph Books |isbn=9781641252478 |page=239}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Roark's [[Inspire Brands]] announced it was acquiring Jimmy John's for an unspecified amount in a deal unanimously approved by Liautaud and the rest of the Jimmy John's Board of Directors.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inspire Brands to Acquire Jimmy John\u2019s |url=https://inspirebrands.com/inspire-brands-to-acquire-jimmy-johns/ |accessdate=9 October 2019 |publisher=[[Inspire Brands]] |date=25 September 2019}}</ref> At the close of the deal, Liautaud said that he will step down as chairman of the company and transition to become an adviser to the brand.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haddon |first1=Heather |title=Arby\u2019s Parent to Acquire Jimmy John\u2019s |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/inspire-brands-to-add-jimmy-johns-to-its-restaurant-roster-11569408901 |accessdate=9 October 2019 |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=25 September 2019}}</ref> The acquisition was completed on October 18.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruggless |first1=Ron |title=Inspire completes purchase of Jimmy John\u2019s |url=https://www.nrn.com/mergers-acquisitions/inspire-completes-purchase-jimmy-john-s |accessdate=21 October 2019 |work=Nation's Restaurant News |date=18 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2008, Liautaud donated $1 million to his high school, Elgin Academy, on the condition that the building constructed using his donation bear not only his name, but also the name of the man who had been the dean of the school when Liautaud attended: James Lyons.<ref name=\"New York Times: Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian\" />\n[[File:Jimmy John's Owner Jimmy John Liautaud Presents $1 Million Check to Folds of Honor.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Jimmy John Liautaud donating $1 million to Major Dan Rooney and Folds of Honor.]]\nIn 2011, Liautaud and his wife pledged $1 million toward the construction of the new [[Champaign County, Illinois|Champaign County]] YMCA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liautauds pledge $1 million to new Champaign County Y|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2011-06-23/liautauds-pledge-1-million-new-champaign-county-y.html|accessdate=9 November 2017|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign\u2013Urbana)]]|date=23 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Liautaud donated $1 million to the Folds of Honor Foundation, an organization that supports the families of fallen soldiers.<ref name=\"Tulsa World: Jimmy John's to donate $1 million to Owasso-based Folds of Honor\">{{cite web|last1=Staff Reports|title=Jimmy John's to donate $1 million to Owasso-based Folds of Honor|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/communities/owasso/news/jimmy-john-s-to-donate-million-to-owasso-based-folds/article_dba8a6a0-a4ec-510e-9579-35104cec3eb9.html|website=[[Tulsa World]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Liautaud and his wife, Leslie, donated $2 million to help Brewster Academy kick off the fundraising for their new residence hall to house 22 students and 4 faculty residences.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Braiterman|first1=Lisa|title=New Residence Hall Underway|url=http://blogs.brewsteracademy.org/off-and-digging/|accessdate=9 November 2017|website=[[Brewster Academy]]|date=4 August 2017}}</ref> In May 2018, the new residence opened, and is called \"Toad Hall\" after a common mispronunciation of the family's last name.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brewster Academy Opens Toad Hall Following Gift from Leslie and Jimmy John Liautaud |url=http://blogs.brewsteracademy.org/brewster-academy-opens-toad-hall-following-gift-from-leslie-and-jimmy-john-liautaud/ |accessdate=9 January 2019 |website=[[Brewster Academy]] |date=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Camp Southern Ground, a non-profit summer camp founded by musician [[Zac Brown Band|Zac Brown]], announced that the Liautauds had donated over $3.2 million to date to help build the camp's first residential lodge and fund ongoing operations. In non-summer months, the camp's facilities are used to support military veterans and their families transitioning back to civilian life.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zac Brown's Camp Southern Ground Receives $2.2 Million Donation From Jimmy John's Owner, Jimmy John Liautaud |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/zac-browns-camp-southern-ground-receives-2-2-million-donation-from-jimmy-johns-owner-jimmy-john-liautaud-300782407.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=Camp Southern Ground |date=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Liautaud Family Foundation directed $1.291 million to the Horatio Alger Association to support scholarships for underprivileged students in 2019.<ref name=\"IP1\">{{cite news |last1=Adeniji |first1=Ade |title=Sandwich Chain Billionaire Jimmy John Liautaud and His Family Get More Strategic About Their Giving |url=https://www.insidephilanthropy.com/home/2019/12/4/a-sandwich-chain-billionaire-and-his-family-gets-more-strategic-about-their-giving |accessdate=15 January 2020 |publisher=[[Inside Philanthropy]] |date=4 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nLiautaud partnered with his father to create with an endowment gift of $5 million, the Liautaud Graduate School of Business at the University of Illinois-Chicago.<ref name=\"IP1\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Liautaud Family Gives $5 Million to Establish UIC Graduate Business School |url=https://www.newswise.com/articles/liautaud-family-gives-5-million-to-establish-uic-graduate-business-school |accessdate=15 January 2020 |publisher=University of Illinois at Chicago |date=14 November 2003}}</ref>\n\nThe Liautauds donated $1 million to Chicago\u2019s Youth Guidance Becoming a Man program, which helps disadvantaged young men learn how to handle tough life challenges and give them the tools to succeed in the future.<ref name=\"IP1\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Youth Guidance Expands Becoming A Man Program To Reach 4,000 At-Risk Chicago Males |url=https://www.prlog.org/12592584-youth-guidance-expands-becoming-man-program-to-reach-4000-at-risk-chicago-males.html |accessdate=15 January 2020 |publisher=Youth Guidance |date=6 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOther causes supported by the Liautauds include: the Frances Nelson Smile Healthy Dental Clinic,<ref name=\"News-Gazette: Liautaud donates $300,000 to benefit Frances Nelson\">{{cite web|last1=Pressey|first1=Debra|title=Liautaud donates $300,000 to benefit Frances Nelson|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2013-04-08/liautaud-donates-300000-benefit-frances-nelson.html|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign\u2013Urbana)]]|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=8 April 2013}}</ref> the Kickapoo Rail Trail,<ref name=\"Jimmy John's owner gives $150,000 to Illinois trail project\">{{cite web|title=Jimmy John's owner gives $150,000 to Illinois trail project|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/illinois/jimmy-john-s-owner-gives-to-illinois-trail-project/article_0ba8f685-78de-5704-8e00-8398bc32318c.html|newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|accessdate=8 September 2016|date=3 July 2016}}</ref> Crisis Nursery in Urbana, Illinois,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jimmy John Liautaud & the Liautaud Family Foundation|url=https://crisisnursery.net/jimmy-john-liautaud-family-foundation/|website=Crisis Nursery|accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> Champaign County's Youth Assessment Center,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wickman|first1=Natalie|title=Youth Assessment Center to settle on new site by spring|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2018-01-11/youth-assessment-center-settle-new-site-spring.html|accessdate=14 February 2018|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign-Urbana)]]|date=11 January 2018}}</ref>, [[Champaign Unit 4 School District|Champaign Unit 4]] schools,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Lyndsay|title=Students, staff are 'totally pumped' about planned projects|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2018-01-22/students-staff-are-totally-pumped-about-planned-projects.html|accessdate=14 February 2018|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign-Urbana)]]|date=22 January 2018}}</ref> Christmas layaway purchases,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jensen |first1=Jennifer |title=$80,000 in layaways paid by generous donation |url=https://www.wcia.com/news/local-news/-80-000-in-layaways-paid-off-by-generous-donation/1651895860 |accessdate=12 December 2018 |work=[[WCIA]] |date=10 December 2018}}</ref> the American Heart Association, the Mayo Clinic Center for Individualized Medicine, MD Anderson, the Pancreatic Cancer Action Network, the Lurie Children\u2019s Hospital of Chicago, the Goodman Theater, and the Detroit Symphony.<ref name=\"IP1\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Jimmy John Liautaud and Leslie Liautaud: Donor Grants |url=https://www.insidephilanthropy.com/donors/jimmy-john-and-leslie-liautaud-donor-grants |publisher=[[Inside Philanthropy]] |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nLiautaud is a member of the University of Illinois at Chicago's Chicago Area Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"Institute for Entrepreneurial Studies\">{{cite web|title=2015 Chicago Area Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame Inductees|url=https://ies.uic.edu/entrepreneurship-hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-members/|website=Institute for Entrepreneurial Studies|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he was named to Chicago's \u201c40 Under 40\u201d by Crain's Chicago Business.<ref name=\"CRAIN'S: \tJIMMY JOHN LIAUTAUD | 39Founder, chairman and CEOJimmy John's Gourmet Sandwich Shops\">{{cite news|title=JIMMY JOHN LIAUTAUD, Founder, chairman and CEO Jimmy John's Gourmet Sandwich Shops|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20031029/PAGES/1426/40-under-40-2003|magazine=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he was named the [[Ernst & Young|Ernst & Young Food & Beverage Entrepreneur of the Year]] in Illinois. The winners were selected by an independent panel of judges composed of local community and business leaders.<ref name=\"Illinois Entrepreneurs Named Ernst & Young Entrepreneur Of The Year\u00ae 2004 Award Winners\">{{cite web|title=Illinois Entrepreneurs Named Ernst & Young Entrepreneur Of The Year\u00ae 2004 Award Winners|url=http://www.lakecapital.com/pdfs/hcg1505.pdf|website=Lakecapital.com|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> In the same year, he was given the Lifetime Achievement Award at the National CEO Conference and inducted into the Collegiate Entrepreneurs' Organization Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"QSR Magazine\">{{cite news|title=\"Jimmy John\" in CEO Hall of Fame|url=https://www.qsrmagazine.com/news/jimmy-john-ceo-hall-fame|magazine=QSR Magazine|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n \nIn 2007, Liautaud delivered the commencement speech at his alma mater, now known as the Liautaud-Lyons Upper School, a program of Elgin Academy.<ref name=\"New York Times: Troublesome Student Makes Good, and Honors Disciplinarian\" />\n\nIn 2012, Liautaud was awarded the Nation's Restaurant News Golden Chain award for outstanding accomplishments that have benefited consumers in the food industry.<ref name=\"The Daily Meal: Meet the 2012 Golden Chain Award winners\">{{cite web|last1=[[Nation's Restaurant News]] Staff Writer|title=Meet the 2012 Golden Chain Award winners|url=http://www.thedailymeal.com/meet-2012-golden-chain-award-winners|website=The Daily Meal|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=9 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, he was named Franchise Times' \"Dealmaker of the Year\" for the deal that brought [[Roark Capital Group]] in as the company's new majority owner. Beth Ewen, FT's editor-in-chief called the deal \"one of the best private equity deals of all time in the restaurant business.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lazare|first1=Lewis|title=Jimmy John's founder hailed as king of the dealmakers|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/chicago/news/2017/03/15/jimmy-johns-founder-hailed-as-king-of-the.html|accessdate=22 March 2017|work=[[Chicago Business Journal]]|date=15 March 2017}}</ref> In December of that year, Liautaud was chosen to receive the Horatio Alger Award for 2018. The [[Horatio Alger Association of Distinguished Americans]] recognizes people who have overcome personal challenges to achieve personal and professional success.<ref>{{cite news|title=Owner, Founder & Chairman of Jimmy John's Gourmet Sandwiches, Jimmy John Liautaud, to Receive 2018 Horatio Alger Award|url=https://horatioalger.org/haa_news/owner-founder-chairman-of-jimmy-johns-gourmet-sandwiches-jimmy-john-liautaud-to-receive-2018-horatio-alger-award/|accessdate=24 December 2017|website=[[Horatio Alger Association of Distinguished Americans]]|date=5 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pressey|first1=Debra|title=Jimmy John Liautaud part of Horatio Alger Association's Class of 2018|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2017-12-15/jimmy-john-liautaud-part-horatio-alger-associations-class-2018.html|accessdate=24 December 2017|newspaper=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign-Urbana)]]|date=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Public speaking ==\nLiautaud speaks at a broad range of venues, including high schools;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apg-wi.com/spooner_advocate/news/regional/sandwich-mogul-jimmy-john-shares-advice-with-northwood-students/article_bd97be08-1951-11e6-bb06-23323557cdd7.html|title=Sandwich mogul 'Jimmy John' shares advice with Northwood students|last=ADMINISTRATOR|first=JEAN SERUM {{!}} NORTHWOOD SCHOOL|website=APG of Wisconsin|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref> colleges and universities;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.kellogg.northwestern.edu/inside/2017/03/17/growth-scaling-and-life-lessons-from-jimmy-johns-founder-ceo/|title=Growth, Scaling, and Life Lessons from Jimmy John Liautaud, Founder, Owner & Chairman of Jimmy John\u2019s {{!}} Inside Kellogg|website=blogs.kellogg.northwestern.edu|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mendoza.nd.edu/news/jimmy-john-brings-his-story-of-sandwich-franchise-success-to-notre-dame/|title=Jimmy John brings his story of sandwich franchise success to Notre Dame - Notre Dame Business|website=Mendoza College of Business|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.kellogg.northwestern.edu/inside/2019/06/18/jimmy-john-liautaud-emba/|title=Jimmy John Liautaud Shares His Story with EMBA Students in Miami|website=blogs.kellogg.northwestern.edu|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref> and community spaces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://champaign.org/event/start-and-grow-your-business-guest-speaker-jimmy-john-liautaud-1287660|title=Start and Grow Your Business: Guest Speaker Jimmy John Liautaud|website=champaign.org|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox-companies.com/about-2/giving-back/|title=Community Involvement|date=2014-07-25|website=Fox Companies|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref>\n\n==Hunting==\nLiautaud is an avid hunter and fisherman. In an interview in 2015 with the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', Liautaud said that the largest misconception about him is that people still connect him to photos of him posing with big game from 10 years ago. According to Liautaud, he used to hunt [[Big five game|big game in Africa]] on legally organized [[safari]]s, but he no longer does.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune: Jimmy John's founder opens up on expansion, big game hunting, possible IPO\" /> Starting in 2015, his hunting prompted people to call for a [[boycott]] of his business.<ref name=\"Rizzo\">{{cite news|last1=Rizzo|first1=Lillian|title=Jimmy John's Faces Boycott Call Over Founder's Trophy Hunting|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/privateequity/2015/08/05/jimmy-johns-faces-boycott-call-over-founders-trophy-hunting/|accessdate=28 October 2016|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=5 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLiautaud is married to dancer, playwright, actress, and choreographer Leslie Liautaud and has three children, Spencer, Lucy, and Fred.<ref name=\"Success: Success Stories: Jimmy John Liautaud\" /><ref name=\"CHAMBANAMOMS.COM Chambana Mom to Know: Leslie Liautaud Chambana Mom to Know: Leslie Liautaud\">{{cite web|last1=Editors|title= Chambana Mom to Know: Leslie Liautaud Chambana Mom to Know: Leslie Liautaud|url=http://www.chambanamoms.com/2011/10/12/chambana-mom-to-know-leslie-liautaud/|website=chambanamoms.com|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=12 October 2011}}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2016|reason=Appears to be a local blog}}</ref> Liautaud is an investor in wines and vineyards, at least one of which has been featured on the cover of ''[[Wine Spectator]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.franchisetimes.com/April-2017/How-Jimmy-Johns-landed-FTs-deal-of-the-year/ |title=How Jimmy John's landed FT's deal of the year |work=[[Franchise Times]] |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=April 2, 2017 |first=Beth |last=Ewen}}</ref> He also owns thousands of acres of farmland in Central Illinois.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McKinstry|first1=Erin|title=As generations age, farm owners less connected to their land|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/state_news/as-generations-age-farm-owners-less-connected-to-their-land/article_19094154-441a-11e8-9f0b-8336aac36649.html|newspaper=[[Columbia Missourian]]|accessdate=30 April 2018|date=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLiautaud also owns a superyacht named [[ROCK.IT (yacht)|ROCK.IT]], a 198-foot ship built with his input by Feadship in 2014. The ship, which can accommodate ten guests with a crew of 13,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Larry |title=Jimmy John's $100 million yacht visits Ogdensburg |url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/news05/jimmy-johns-100-million-yacht-visits-ogdensburg-20161004 |accessdate=20 November 2018 |newspaper=[[Watertown Daily Times]] |date=4 October 2016}}</ref> has been a finalist for a few yacht awards<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bednarova |first1=Zuzana |title=World Superyacht Awards 2015 Finalists |url=http://www.charterworld.com/news/world-superyacht-awards-2015-finalists |website=CharterWorld.com |publisher=[[Boat International Media]] |accessdate=20 November 2018 |date=3 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Finalists announced for the ShowBoats Design Awards 2016 |url=https://www.boatinternational.com/luxury-yacht-events/design-and-innovation-awards/finalists-announced-for-the-showboats-design-awards-2016--28653 |website=[[Boat International Media]] |accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref> and been featured in a number of industry publications.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mower |first1=Marilyn |title=Rock.It \u2014 the hip, modern Feadship yacht with a touch of class |url=https://www.boatinternational.com/yachts/editorial-features/rockit-the-hip-modern-feadship-yacht-with-a-touch-of-class--29481 |website=[[Boat International Media]] |accessdate=20 November 2018 |date=25 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=From sandwiches to superyachts: Inside Jimmy John's 197' Feadship |url=https://archive.org/details/ShowBoats_Intl_March_2016 |work=ShowBoats International|publisher=[[Boat International Media]] |pages=104-114 |date=6 March 2016 |accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://jimmyjohnliautaud.com/ Jimmy John Liautaud's official website]\n* [https://www.jimmyjohns.com/about-us/our-story/ Jimmy John's story by founder Jimmy John Liautaud]\n* [https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=39564257&privcapId=36597434 Jimmy John Liautaud's Businessweek bio]\n* {{IMDb name|6908472}}\n* [https://www.crunchbase.com/person/jimmy-john-liautaud Jimmy John Liautaud on CrunchBase]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liautaud, James John}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American people of Lithuanian descent]]\n[[Category:Eastern Illinois University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Arlington Heights, Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:e3e0:fcd0::63c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_John_Liautaud"}
{"title_page": "Himba people", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Himba\n| native_name      = OvaHimba\n| native_name_lang = her\n| image            = [[File:Namibie Himba 0717a.jpg|none|150px]]\n| image_caption    = Himba (OmuHimba) woman\n| population       = about 50,000<ref name=\"METNG\" />\n| regions          =\n| region1          = {{flag|Namibia}}\n| pop1             = -\n| region2          = {{flag|Angola}}\n| pop2             = -\n| languages        = OtjiHimba (a variety of [[Herero language|Herero]])\n| religions        = [[Monotheism|Monotheistic]] ([[Mukuru]] and [[Veneration of the dead|Ancestor Reverence]])\n| related          = [[Herero people]], [[Bantu peoples]]\n}}\nThe '''Himba''' (singular: '''OmuHimba''', plural: '''OvaHimba''') are [[indigenous peoples]] with an estimated population of about 50,000 people<ref name=\"METNG\">{{Cite book|title=Strategies That Integrate Environmental Sustainability Into National Development Planning Process to Address Livelihood Concerns of the OvaHimba Tribe in Namibia - A Summary|volume=|first=|last=Kamaku Consultancy Services cc., Commissioned by: Country Pilot Partnership (CPP) Programme Namibia|authorlink=|url=http://www.met.gov.na/CPP/Resources/Himba%20research%20Study%20Report.pdf|publisher=The Ministry of Environment and Tourism, Republic of Namibia.|location=Windhoek, Namibia|year=2011|language=|chapter=|pages=|isbn=|access-date=2014-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031219/http://www.met.gov.na/CPP/Resources/Himba%20research%20Study%20Report.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> living in northern [[Namibia]], in the [[Kunene Region]] (formerly [[Kaokoland]]) and on the other side of the Kunene River in southern [[Angola]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> There are also a few groups left of the '''OvaTwa''', who are also OvaHimba, but are [[hunter-gatherer]]s. However, the OvaHimba do not like to be associated with OvaTwa.{{cn|date=January 2010}} Culturally distinguishable from the [[Herero people]], the OvaHimba are a semi-[[nomad]]ic, [[pastoralism|pastoralist]] people and speak OtjiHimba, a variety of [[Herero language|Herero]], which belongs to the [[Bantu languages|Bantu family]] within [[Niger\u2013Congo languages|Niger\u2013Congo]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> The OvaHimba are semi-nomadic as they have base homesteads where crops are cultivated, but may have to move within the year depending on rainfall and where there is access to water.  \n\nThe OvaHimba are considered the last (semi-) nomadic people of Namibia.\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Himba-Hirten.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Himba [[herder]]s in Kaokoland]]\n\n===Subsistence economy===\n{{Details|Subsistence economy}}\nThe OvaHimba are predominantly [[livestock]] farmers who breed [[fat-tailed sheep]] and [[goat]]s, but count their [[wealth]] in the number of their [[cattle]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> They also grow and farm rain-fed [[crops]] such as [[maize]] and [[millet]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> Livestock are the major source of [[milk]] and [[meat]] for the OvaHimba. Their main diet is sour milk and maize porridge ( oruhere ruomaere) and sometimes plain hard porridge only, due to milk and meat scarcity. Their diet is also supplemented by [[cornmeal]], [[chicken]] eggs, wild [[herb]]s and [[honey]]. Only occasionally, and opportunistically, are the livestock sold for [[cash]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> Non-farming businesses, wages and salaries, pensions, and other cash remittances make up a very small portion of the OvaHimba livelihood, which is gained chiefly from their work in [[conservation area|conservancies]], old-age [[pension]]s, and [[drought]] relief aid from the [[government of Namibia]].<ref name=\"METNG\" />\n\n===Daily life===\nWomen and girls tend to perform more labor-intensive work than men and boys do, such as carrying water to the village, [[earthen plaster]]ing the [[Mopane#Uses|mopane]] wood homes with a traditional mixture of [[ultisol|red clay soil]] and cow [[manure]] [[Binder (material)|binding agent]], collecting firewood, attending to the [[calabash]] vines used for producing and ensuring a secure supply of [[soured milk]], cooking and serving meals, as well as [[artisan]]s making [[handicraft]]s, [[clothing]] and [[jewelry]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> The responsibility for milking the cows and goats also lies with the women and girls.<ref name=\"METNG\" /> Women and girls take care of the children, and one woman or girl will take care of another woman's children. The men's main tasks are tending to the [[livestock]] farming, [[herding]] where the men will often be away from the family home for extended periods, [[animal slaughter]]ing, [[construction]], and holding [[council]] with village [[tribal chief]]s.<ref name=\"METNG\" /> \n\nMembers of a single extended family typically dwell in a [[Homestead (small African settlement)|homestead]] (''onganda''), a small family-village, consisting of a circular hamlet of huts and work shelters that surround an ''okuruwo'' ([[fire worship|sacred ancestral fire]]) and a [[kraal]] for the [[sacred]] livestock. Both the fire and the livestock are closely tied to their [[veneration of the dead]], the sacred fire representing ancestral protection and the sacred livestock allowing \"proper relations between human and ancestor\".{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=18}}\n\nThe OvaHimba use a heterogeneous pasture system that includes both rainy-season pastures and dry-season pastures. Dry-season pastures are rested during the rainy season which results in higher biomass production in the soil compared to constantly grazing all pastures. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=M\u00fcller|first=Birgit|last2=Linst\u00e4dter|first2=Anja|last3=Frank|first3=Karin|last4=Bollig|first4=Michael|last5=Wissel|first5=Christian|date=2007|title=Learning from Local Knowledge: Modeling the Pastoral-Nomadic Range Management of the Himba, Namibia|url=https://esajournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1890/06-1193.1|journal=Ecological Applications|language=en|volume=17|issue=7|pages=1857\u20131875|doi=10.1890/06-1193.1|issn=1939-5582}}</ref>\n\n===Clothing and hair style===\n[[File:Himba Girls Photo by Sascha Grabow.JPG|thumb|150px|Young Himba girls. The ''Erembe'' headdress indicates both are married.]]\n[[Image:Himba lady preparing deodorant.jpg|thumb|150px|Himba woman preparing [[incense]], the smoke is used as an [[antimicrobial]] body cleansing agent, [[deodorant]] and fragrant, made by burning aromatic herbs and resins.]]\nBoth the Himba men and women are accustomed to wearing traditional clothing that benefits their living environment in the [[Kaokoland]] and the hot [[semi-arid climate]] of their area, in most occurrences this consists simply of [[skirt]]-like [[clothing]] made from [[calfskin]]s and sheep skin or increasingly from more modern textiles, and occasionally [[sandal]]s for footwear. Women's sandals are made from cows' skin; while men's are made from old car tires.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} Women who have given birth wear a small backpack of skin attached to their traditional outfit. Himba people, especially women, are remarkably famous for covering themselves with ''[[otjize]]'' paste, a [[cosmetics|cosmetic]] mixture of [[butterfat]] and [[ochre]] pigment, to cleanse the skin over long periods due to [[water scarcity]] and protect themselves from the extremely hot and dry climate of the [[Kaokoland]] as well as insect bites. The cosmetic mixture, often perfumed with the aromatic resin of the ''omuzumba'' [[shrub]], gives their skin and hair [[Braid|plait]]s a distinctive orange or red-tinge characteristic, as well as texture and style.<ref name=\"METNG\" /> Otjize is considered foremost a highly desirable [[Aesthetics|aesthetic]] beauty cosmetic, symbolizing earth's rich red color and blood the essence of life, and is consistent with the OvaHimba ideal of [[beauty]].<ref name=\"DMHT\" />\n\nHairstyle and jewelry play a significant role among the OvaHimba, indicating age and social status within their community.<ref name=\"DMHT\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2607647/Incredible-photos-reveal-elaborate-hairdos-Himba-tribe-created-using-goat-hair-MUD.html|title=That's an unusual look! Namibia's Himba tribeswomen...|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=2014-04-18|accessdate=2014-09-01}}</ref> Both men and women wear adornments around their necks, arms, and feet. An infant or child will generally have his or her head kept shaven of hair, or with just a small crop of hair on the crown of the head. This soon is sculptured, for young boys, into one braided plait extending to the rear of the head. Young girls have two braided plaits extending forward towards the face, often parallel to their eyes, the form of wear being determined by the ''oruzo'' membership (patrilineal descent group). The style remains during [[preadolescence]] until [[puberty]].<ref name=\"DMHT\" /> Some young girls may also have one braided plait extending forwards, which means they are one of a pair of [[twin]]s.<ref name=\"DMHT\" />\n\nFrom pubescence, boys continue to have one braided plait, while girls will have many ''otjize''-textured hair plaits, some arranged to [[veil]] the girl's face. In daily practice the plaits are often tied together and held parted back from the face.<ref name=\"DMHT\" /> Women who have been married for about a year, or have had a child, wear an ornate headpiece called the ''Erembe'', sculptured from [[sheepskin]], with many streams of braided hair, coloured and put in shape with otjize paste.<ref name=\"DMHT\" /> Unmarried young men continue to wear one braided plait extending to the rear of the head, while married men wear a [[cap]] or head-wrap and un-braided hair beneath.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newlynatural.com/blog/2011/01/himba-hair-styling/|title=Himba Hair Styling|last=Kcurly|date=4 January 2011|website=Newly Natural|accessdate=2012-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://goafrica.about.com/library/bl.himba.htm|title=Tribes of Africa. The Himba|website=Africa Travel|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=2012-08-04}}</ref> [[Widow]]ed men will remove their cap or head-wrap and expose un-braided hair. The OvaHimba are also accustomed to use [[wood ash]] for hair cleansing due to [[water scarcity]].<ref name=\"DMHT\" />\n\n===Customary practices===\nThe OvaHimba are [[Polygamy|polygamous]], with the average Himba man being husband to two wives at the same time. They also practice early [[arranged marriage]]s. Young Himba girls are married to male partners chosen by their fathers. This happens from the onset of puberty,<ref name=\"METNG\" /> which may mean that girls aged 10 or below are married off. This practice is illegal in Namibia, and even some OvaHimba contest it, but it is nevertheless widespread.<ref>{{cite news | title=Opuwo's lonely voice against child marriages | last=Kangootui | first=Nomhle |newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=26 May 2016 | page=1 | url= http://www.namibian.com.na/Opuwo\u2019s-lonely-voice-against-child-marriages/40932/read}}</ref>\nAmong the Himba people, it is customary as a [[rite of passage]] to [[circumcision|circumcise]] boys before puberty. Upon marriage, a Himba boy is considered a man, unlike a Himba girl who is not considered a fully-fledged woman until she bears a child. \n[[File:Namibie Himba 0720a.jpg|thumb|Young Himba woman and child, the woman wearing a headpiece and beaded anklets or omohanga]]\n\n\nMarriage among the OvaHimba involves transactions of cattle, which are the source of their economy. Bridewealth is involved in these transactions; this can be negotiable between the groom's family and the bride's father, depending on the relative poverty of the families involved.<ref>Crandall, D. (1998). The Role of Time in Himba Valuations of Cattle. The Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute, 4(1), 101-114. doi:10.2307/3034430</ref> In order for the bride's family to accept the bridewealth, the cattle must appear of high quality. It is standard practice to offer an ox, but more cattle will be offered if the groom's father is wealthy and is capable of offering more.\n<br />\n\n===Societal participation===\n[[File:Himba village, Namibia (2014).jpg|thumb|left|Typical Himba village near [[Uis]] in [[Namibia]] (2014)]]\nDespite the fact a majority of OvaHimba live a distinct cultural [[Lifestyle (sociology)|lifestyle]] in their remote rural environment and homesteads, they are [[Social dynamics|socially dynamic]], and not all are isolated from the trends of local [[urban culture]]s. The OvaHimba coexist and interact with members of their country's other ethnic groups and the social trends of urban townsfolk. This is especially true of those in proximity to the Kunene Region capital of [[Opuwo]], who travel frequently to shop at the local town [[supermarket]]s for the convenience of commercial consumer products, market food produce and to acquire [[health care]].<ref name=\"METNG\" />\n\n===Links with Western culture===\nSome Himba children attend Western schools and some young people leave the homelands to live in towns.<ref>BBC article https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-40247310</ref>\n\n==Tribal structure==\n[[File:Headman Kapika und sein Enkel.jpg|left|thumb|200px|A traditional regional [[Leaders of Hereroland|Leader]] or Headman of the OvaHimba - Chief Kapuka Thom (\u2020 2009) of the Vita (Thom) Royal House<ref name=\"PASEAN\">{{Cite book|title=Imagining The Post-Apartheid State: An Ethnographic Account of Namibia|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dV2mAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA204&lpg=PA204&dq=Kapuka+Thom&source=bl&ots=ZCTJhx0th3&sig=UB1fh-6VnC0Mnh8s567ITlktwJk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Hha_U6-yHMbC0QXLx4GYAw&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Kapuka%20Thom&f=false|volume=|first=John|last=Friedman|publisher=Berghahn Books|location=Oxford, New York|year=2011|language=|page=204|isbn=9781782383239}}</ref> with his grandson]]\nBecause of the harsh desert climate in the region where they live and their seclusion from outside influences, the OvaHimba have managed to maintain and preserve much of their traditional lifestyle. Members live under a tribal structure based on [[bilateral descent]] that helps them live in one of the most extreme environments on earth.\n\n[[File:Himba-Arbeit.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Himba girl at work]]\nUnder bilateral descent, every tribe member belongs to two clans: one through the father (a patriclan, called ''oruzo'') and another through the mother (a matriclan, called ''eanda'').{{sfn|Crandall|2000}} Himba clans are led by the eldest male in the clan.  Sons live with their father's clan, and when daughters marry, they go to live with the clan of their husband.  However, inheritance of wealth does not follow the patriclan but is determined by the matriclan, that is, a son does not inherit his father's cattle but his maternal uncle's instead. Along with the inheritance of wealth, moral obligations are also important within the tribal structure. When a person dies, the OvaHimba evaluate the care of those who are left behind, such as orphans and widows. Access to water-points and pastures are another part of the OvaHimba inheritance structure.\n\nBilateral descent is found among only a few groups in West Africa, India, Australia, Melanesia and Polynesia, and anthropologists consider the system advantageous for groups that live in extreme environments because it allows individuals to rely on two sets of kin dispersed over a wide area.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?chanID=sa006&articleID=0005596A-DE68-1C6F-84A9809EC588EF21|title=The Himba and the Dam|first=Carol|last=Ezzell|date=17 June 2001|magazine=[[Scientific American]]|url-access=subscription|journal=|access-date=20 July 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012142329/http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?chanID=sa006&articleID=0005596A-DE68-1C6F-84A9809EC588EF21|archive-date=12 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe OvaHimba history is fraught with disasters, including severe droughts and guerrilla warfare, especially during Namibia's war of independence and as a result of the civil war in neighboring [[Angola]]. Between 1904\u20131908, they suffered from the same attempt at genocide during the [[Herero Wars]] conducted by the [[German Empire]] colonist government in [[German South-West Africa]] under [[Lothar von Trotha]] that decimated notably the [[Herero people]] and the [[Nama people]] during the [[Herero and Namaqua Genocide]].{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\nIn the 1980s it appeared the OvaHimba way of life was coming to a close due to a climax in adverse climatic conditions and political conflicts.<ref name=\"RMHE\">{{Cite book|title=Risk Management in a Hazardous Environment: A Comparative Study of two Pastoral Societies|volume=|first=Michael|last=Bollig|authorlink=|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SsPO7wYv1VkC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=Springer Science+Business Media, Inc.|location=New York|year=2006|language=|chapter=|pages=167\u2013168|isbn=9780387275819}}</ref> A severe drought killed 90% of their livestock, and many gave up their herds and became refugees in the town of [[Opuwo]] living in [[slum]]s on international [[humanitarian aid]] or joined [[Koevoet]] paramilitary units to cope with the [[livestock]] losses and widespread [[famine]].<ref name=\"RMHE\" /> OvaHimba living over the border in Angola, were occasionally victims of [[kidnapping]] during the South African Border war, either taken as hostages or abducted to join the Angolan branch of the [[People's Liberation Army of Namibia]] (PLAN, army of [[SWAPO]]).<ref name=\"RMHE\" />\n\n===Religion===\nThe OvaHimba are a [[monotheism|monotheistic]] people who worship the god [[Mukuru]], as well as their clan's ancestors ([[Veneration of the dead|ancestor reverence]]). Mukuru only blesses, while the ancestors can bless and curse.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=188}} Each family has its own [[Fire worship|sacred ancestral fire]], which is kept by the fire-keeper. The fire-keeper approaches the [[sacred]] ancestral fire every seven to eight days in order to communicate with Mukuru and the ancestors on behalf of his family.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=47}} Often, because Mukuru is busy in a distant realm, the ancestors act as Mukuru's representatives.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=47}}\n\nThe OvaHimba traditionally believe in ''omiti'', which some translate to mean [[witchcraft]] but which others call \"[[black magic]]\" or \"bad medicine\".{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=33}} Some OvaHimba believe that death is caused by ''omiti'', or rather, by someone using ''omiti'' for malicious purposes.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|pp=38\u201339}} Additionally, some believe that evil people who use ''omiti'' have the power to place bad thoughts into another's mind{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=102}} or cause extraordinary events to happen (such as when a common illness becomes life-threatening).{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=66}} But users of ''omiti'' do not always attack their victim directly; sometimes they target a relative or loved one.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=67}} Some OvaHimba will consult a [[traditional healers of South Africa|traditional African diviner-healer]] to reveal the reason behind an extraordinary event, or the source of the ''omiti''.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=66}}\n\n===Since Namibian independence===\n[[File:Himba Mobile School.JPG|thumb|Himba mobile school]]\nThe OvaHimba have been successful in maintaining their culture and traditional way of life.\n\nAs such, the OvaHimba have worked with international activists to block a proposed hydroelectric dam along the [[Kunene River#The Epupa dam|Kunene River]] that would have flooded their ancestral lands,<ref name=\"UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs\">{{cite news |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report/76311/NAMIBIA-Dam-will-mean-our-destruction-warn-Himba=eng |title=Namibia: Dam will mean our destruction, warn Himba |work=[[IRIN]] |publisher=[[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] |date=18 January 2008}}</ref> 2011, Namibia announced its new plan to build a dam in Orokawe, in the Baynes Mountains. The OvaHimba submitted in February 2012 their protest Declaration against the hydroelectric dam to the United Nations, the African Union and to the Government of Namibia.<ref name=\"ep1061\" />\n\nThe government of Norway and Iceland funded mobile schools for Himba children, but since Namibia took them over in 2010, they have been converted to permanent schools and are no longer mobile. The Himba leaders complain in their declaration about the culturally inappropriate school system, that they say would threaten their culture, identity and way of life as a people.\n\n===Human rights===\nGroups of the last remaining hunters and gatherers Ovatwa are held in secured camps in the northern part of Namibia's Kunene region, despite complaints by the traditional Himba chiefs that the Ovatwa are held there without their consent and against their wishes.<ref name=\"osi\">{{cite web |title=Indigenous coalition opposed to new dam |url=http://www.osisa.org/indigenous-peoples/namibia/indigenous-coalition-opposed-new-dam |website=[[OSISA]] |first=Delme |last=Cupido |date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-02-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304071437/http://www.osisa.org/indigenous-peoples/namibia/indigenous-coalition-opposed-new-dam |archive-date=4 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, [[traditional]] Himba chiefs<ref name=\"Galdu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.galdu.org/web/index.php?odas=5638&giella1=eng |title=Indigenous Himba Appeal to UN to Fight Namibian Dam |website=Galdu |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |accessdate=2012-04-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017232022/http://www.galdu.org/web/index.php?odas=5638&giella1=eng |archivedate=2013-10-17 }}</ref> issued two separate Declarations<ref name=\"ep1070\" /><ref name=\"newsodrome\">{{cite web|url=http://newsodrome.com/native_american_news/namibian-minority-groups-demand-their-rights-29917361 |title=Namibian Minority Groups Demand Their Rights |website=Newsodrome |accessdate=2012-04-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017135555/http://newsodrome.com/native_american_news/namibian-minority-groups-demand-their-rights-29917361 |archivedate=October 17, 2013 }}</ref> to the [[African Union]] and to the [[OHCHR]] of the [[United Nations]].\n\nThe first, titled \"Declaration of the most affected Ovahimba, Ovatwa, Ovatjimba and Ovazemba against the Orokawe Dam in the Baynes Mountains\"<ref name=\"ep1061\">{{cite web |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=1061 |title=Declaration of the most affected Ovahimba, Ovatwa, Ovatjimba and Ovazemba against the Orokawe Dam in the Baynes Mountains |website=Earth Peoples |date=7 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-04-06}}</ref> outlines the objections from regional Himba chiefs and communities that reside near the Kunene River.\n\nThe second, titled \"Declaration by the traditional Himba leaders of [[Kaokoland]] in [[Namibia]]\"<ref name=\"ep1070\">{{cite web |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=1070 |title=Declaration by the traditional Himba leaders of Kaokoland in Namibia |website=Earth Peoples |date=20 January 2012 |accessdate=2012-04-06}}</ref> lists violations of civil, cultural, economic, environmental, social and political rights perpetrated by the government of [[Namibia]] (GoN).\n\nSeptember 2012, the [[United Nations]] [[United Nations special rapporteur|Special Rapporteur]] on the Rights of [[Indigenous Peoples]] visited the OvaHimba and heard their concerns that they do not have recognized traditional authorities and that they are placed under the jurisdictions of chiefs of neighboring dominant tribes, who make decisions on behalf of the minority communities. In his view, the lack of recognition of traditional chiefs, in accordance with Namibian law, relates to a lack of recognition of the minority indigenous tribes' communal lands.<ref name=\"OHCHR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=12603&LangID=E=eng |title=Statement of the Special Rapporteur on the rights of indigenous peoples, James Anaya, upon concluding his visit to Namibia from 20-28 September 2012 |date=28 September 2012 |website=[[OHCHR]] |accessdate=2012-11-28}}</ref>\n\nNovember 23, 2012, hundreds of OvaHimba and Zemba from Omuhonga and Epupa region protested in Okanguati against Namibia's plans to construct a dam in the Kunene River in the Baynes Mountains, against increasing mining operations on their traditional land and human rights violations against them.<ref name=\"Earth Peoples1\">{{cite web |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=2910=eng |title=Namibia: Indigenous semi-nomadic Himba and Zemba march in protest against dam, mining and human rights violations |first=Rebecca |last=Sommer |authorlink=Rebecca Sommer|date=23 November 2012 |website=Earth Peoples |accessdate=2012-11-24}}</ref>\n\nMarch 25, 2013, over 1,000 Himba people marched in protest again, this time in Opuwo, against the ongoing human rights violations that they endure in Namibia. They expressed their frustration over the lack of recognition of their traditional chiefs as \"Traditional Authorities\" by the government;<ref name=\"Earth Peoples2\">{{cite web |title=German GIZ directly engaged with dispossessing indigenous peoples of their lands and territories in Namibia|publisher=earthpeoples.org|url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=4151 |accessdate=2013-03-30}}</ref> Namibia's plans to build the Orokawe dam in the Baynes Mountains at the Kunene River without consulting with the OvaHimba, who do not consent to the construction plans; culturally inappropriate education; the illegal fencing of parts of their traditional land; and their lack of property rights to the territory that they have lived upon for centuries. They also protested against the implementation of the Communal Land Reform Act of 2002.<ref name=\"Allafrica\">{{cite news |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201303260714.html |title=Himba, Zemba reiterate 'no' to Baynes dam |first=Catherine |last=Sasman |newspaper=[[Allafrica]] |date= |accessdate=2014-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn October 14, 2013, Himba chief Kaipka, on behalf of his region Epupa and the community which was featured in German RTL reality TV show ''Wild Girls'' condemned the misuse of Himba people, individuals and villagers in the show, and demanded the halt of broadcasting any further episodes as they would mock the culture and way of being of the Himba people.<ref name=\"Earth Peoples3\">{{cite web |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=5395=eng |title=Indigenous peoples Himba community condemn RTL TV series Wild Girls, asking Earth Peoples co-founder Rebecca Sommer for help to intervene on their behalf and stop it |website=Earth Peoples |accessdate=2013-10-16}}</ref>\n\nMarch 29, 2014, OvaHimba from both countries, Angola and Namibia, march again in protest against the dam's construction plans as well as against the government attempt to bribe their regional Himba chief. In the signed letter of the Himba community from Epupa, the region that would be directly affected by the dam, the traditional leaders explain that any consent form signed by a former chief as a result of bribery wasn't valid as they remain opposed to the dam.<ref name=\"Earth People4\">{{cite news |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=5669 |title=NAMIBIA Semi-nomadic HIMBA march again in protest against dam construction and government attempt to bribe Himba chief\u2019s consent |first=Rebecca |last=Sommer |website=earthpeoples.org |date= |accessdate=2014-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Anthropological investigations==\n\n===Color perception===\n{{see also|Linguistic relativity and the color naming debate}}\nSeveral researchers have studied the OvaHimba perception of colours.<ref name=\"himba colour\">\n{{cite web|last=Roberson|first=Debi|last2=Davidoff|first2=Jules|last3=Davies|first3=Ian R.L.|last4=Shapiro|first4=Laura R.|title=Colour Categories and Category Acquisition in Himba and English|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/43627151_Colour_categories_and_category_acquisition_in_Himba_and_English|format=pdf|website=The Department of Psychology|publisher=[[University of Essex]]|accessdate=2012-05-28}}</ref> The OvaHimba use four colour names: ''zuzu'' stands for dark shades of blue, red, green and purple; ''vapa'' is white and some shades of yellow; ''buru'' is some shades of green and blue; and ''dambu'' is some other shades of green, red and brown.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Reiger |first=Terry |first2=Paul |last2=Kay |title=Language, thought, and color: Whorf was half right |journal=[[Trends (journals)|Trends in Cognitive Sciences]] |date=28 August 2009 |doi=10.1016/j.tics.2009.07.001 |url=http://www1.icsi.berkeley.edu/~kay/tics2.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=2012-08-29 |volume=13 |pages=439\u2013446 |pmid=19716754}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Ovahimba==\n* [[Vipuakuje Muharukua]], member of Namibia's Parliament\n\n==See also==\n* [[Herero people]]\n* [[Nama people]]\n* [[Oorlam people]]\n* [[Ovambo people]]\n* [[Zemba people]]\n\n<gallery widths=\"154px\" heights=\"200px\" class=\"center\" caption=\"\">\nFile:Himba village.jpg|Himba village about 15&nbsp;km north of [[Opuwo]], Namibia.\nFile:Himba Woman and Family.JPG|Himba woman and some of her family standing in her father's homestead in Otutati, [[Kunene Region]], Namibia.\nFile:Namibie Himba 0721a.jpg|Himba woman working, Namibia.\nFile:Namibie Himba 0705a.jpg|Pubescent Himba girl with hair headdress styled to [[veil]] her face.\nFile:Himba-Hirten-02.jpg|Male Himba herders.\nFile:Namibie Himba 0713a.jpg|Himba woman prepares a fire. Himba huts in the background.\nFile:Namibie Himba 0716a.jpg|As is customary in Himba culture and climate, a Himba girl of northern Namibia wears a traditional skirt made from calfskin leather, headdress and jewelry which signify her social status.\nFile:Himba women 2008.jpg|Himba woman working\n</gallery>\n\n==Literature==\n*{{Cite book|title=Strategies That Integrate Environmental Sustainability Into National Development Planning Process to Address Livelihood Concerns of the OvaHimba Tribe in Namibia - A Summary|volume=|first=|last=Kamaku Consultancy Services cc., Commissioned by: Country Pilot Partnership (CPP) Programme Namibia|authorlink=|url=http://www.met.gov.na/CPP/Resources/Himba%20research%20Study%20Report.pdf|publisher=The Ministry of Environment and Tourism, Republic of Namibia.|location=Windhoek, Namibia|year=2011|language=|chapter=|pages=|isbn=|access-date=2014-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031219/http://www.met.gov.na/CPP/Resources/Himba%20research%20Study%20Report.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Nomads at the Crossroads|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3ZhhY-oaalIC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|volume=|first=O.P|last=Goyal|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|location=New Delhi|year=2005|language=|pages=9&ndash;11|isbn=9788182051492}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Risk Management in a Hazardous Environment: A Comparative Study of two Pastoral Societies|volume=|first=Michael|last=Bollig|authorlink=|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SsPO7wYv1VkC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=Springer Science+Business Media, Inc.|location=New York|year=2006|language=|chapter=|pages=|isbn=9780387275819}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Ma vie avec les Ovahimba|volume=|first=Rina|last=Sherman|authorlink=|url=http://www.rinasherman.com/Writing/publicationslivres.html#vie}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Pieds nus sur la terre rouge|volume=|first=Solenn|last=Bardet|authorlink=|url=https://www.association-kovahimba.net/fr/boutique-27/81-non-categorise/81-livre}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Rouge Himba|volume=|first=Solenn|last=Bardet|authorlink=|url=https://www.association-kovahimba.net/fr/boutique-27/81-non-categorise/83-bande-dessinee}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Crandall|first=David P.|year=2000|title=The Place of Stunted Ironwood Trees: A Year in the Lives of the Cattle-Herding Himba of Namibia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC|location=New York|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group Inc.|isbn=0-8264-1270-X|ref=harv|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA18 18], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA33 33], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA38 38\u201339], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA47 47], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA48 48], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA66 66], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA67 67], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA102 102], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA188 188]}}\n* Peter Pickford, Beverly Pickford, Margaret Jacobsohn: ''Himba''; ed. New Holland Publishers (UK) Ltd, 1990; {{ISBN|978-1-85368-084-7}}\n* Klaus G. F\u00f6rg, Gerhard Burkl: ''Himba. Namibias ockerrotes Volk''; Rosenheim: Rosenheimer Verlagshaus, 2004; {{ISBN|3-475-53572-6}} (''in German'')\n* Rina Sherman: ''Ma vie avec les Ovahimba''; Paris: Hugo et Cie, 2009; {{ISBN|978-2-7556-0261-6}} (''in French'')\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|Himba}}\n*[https://vimeo.com/205791464 Himbas, struggle for survive; a long term documentary by photojournalist and filmmaker Delmi Alvarez]\n*[http://www.ovahimba.rinasherman.com The Ovahimba Years I Les ann\u00e9es Ovahimba]\n*[http://www.der.org/films/keep-the-dance-alive.html Keep the Dance Alive I Que la danse continue]\n*[http://semioweb.msh-paris.fr/corpus/pci/EN/video.asp?id=939&ress=3005&video=65367&format=47 Sept ann\u00e9es chez les Ovahimba]\n*[http://peacecorpsonline.org/messages/messages/467/2064131.html A Peace Corps volunteer works among the Himba]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UB6gD5q6950 HIMBA CUSTOMS from Namibia. Extract from ''Last Free Men'' by Jos\u00e9 Manuel Novoa]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pOXpRS5y8qM HIMBA DANCE in Omuhonga, Kaokoland, Namibia, video by Rebecca Sommer]\n*[http://www.kovahimba.org Association Kovahimba], created by Solenn Bardet\n\n===Photographs===\n*[http://www.matthieurivart.com/hearts-of-sand Hearts of sand] \u2013 Photography by Matthieu Rivart\n*[http://www.rinasherman.com/indexphot.html The Ovahimba Years] \u2013 Photography by Rina Sherman.\n*[https://www.klaustiedge.com/product-category/tribe-prints/himba/ The Himba Tribe] \u2013 Photography by Klaus Tiedge.\n*[http://www.benjaminrennicke.de/portfolio/Ovahimba Photos of the Himba People in Okangwati] \u2013 Photography by Benjamin Rennicke.\n*[http://www.pgoimages.com/gallery.php?gall=g_namibia_himba Photographs of the Himba in Namibia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080613152141/http://blog.lukaesenko.com/2008/06/10/himba-the-beautiful-people/ Photos from Himba village near Opuwo, Namibia] \u2013 Photographs and information.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060318183106/http://www.on-the-matrix.com/africa/himba.asp Africa on the Matrix: Himba People of Namibia] \u2013 Photographs and information.\n\n===Movies===\n*[https://www.association-kovahimba.net/fr/boutique-27/50-bande-annonce/bande-annonce/70-les-himbas-font-leur-cinema-6 The Himba are shooting] \u2013 movie by Solenn Bardet (French and English).\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Angola}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Namibia}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Namibia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Angola]]\n[[Category:Herero people]]\n[[Category:Pastoralists]]\n[[Category:African nomads]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Himba\n| native_name      = OvaHimba\n| native_name_lang = her\n| image            = [[File:Namibie Himba 0717a.jpg|none|150px]]\n| image_caption    = Himba (OmuHimba) woman\n| population       = about 50,000<ref name=\"METNG\" />\n| regions          =\n| region1          = {{flag|Namibia}}\n| pop1             = -\n| region2          = {{flag|Angola}}\n| pop2             = -\n| languages        = OtjiHimba (a variety of [[Herero language|Herero]])\n| religions        = [[Monotheism|Monotheistic]] ([[Mukuru]] and [[Veneration of the dead|Ancestor Reverence]])\n| related          = [[Herero people]], [[Bantu peoples]]\n}}\nThe '''Himba''' (singular: '''OmuHimba''', plural: '''OvaHimba''') are [[indigenous peoples]] with an estimated population of about 50,000 people<ref name=\"METNG\">{{Cite book|title=Strategies That Integrate Environmental Sustainability Into National Development Planning Process to Address Livelihood Concerns of the OvaHimba Tribe in Namibia - A Summary|volume=|first=|last=Kamaku Consultancy Services cc., Commissioned by: Country Pilot Partnership (CPP) Programme Namibia|authorlink=|url=http://www.met.gov.na/CPP/Resources/Himba%20research%20Study%20Report.pdf|publisher=The Ministry of Environment and Tourism, Republic of Namibia.|location=Windhoek, Namibia|year=2011|language=|chapter=|pages=|isbn=|access-date=2014-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031219/http://www.met.gov.na/CPP/Resources/Himba%20research%20Study%20Report.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> living in northern [[Namibia]], in the [[Kunene Region]] (formerly [[Kaokoland]]) and on the other side of the Kunene River in southern [[Angola]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> There are also a few groups left of the '''OvaTwa''', who are also OvaHimba, but are [[hunter-gatherer]]s. However, the OvaHimba do not like to be associated with OvaTwa.{{cn|date=January 2010}} Culturally distinguishable from the [[Herero people]], the OvaHimba are a semi-[[nomad]]ic, [[pastoralism|pastoralist]] people and speak OtjiHimba, a variety of [[Herero language|Herero]], which belongs to the [[Bantu languages|Bantu family]] within [[Niger\u2013Congo languages|Niger\u2013Congo]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> The OvaHimba are semi-nomadic as they have base homesteads where crops are cultivated, but may have to move within the year depending on rainfall and where there is access to water.  \n\nThe OvaHimba are considered the last (semi-) nomadic people of Namibia.\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Himba-Hirten.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Himba [[herder]]s in Kaokoland]]\n\n===Subsistence economy===\n{{Details|Subsistence economy}}\nThe OvaHimba are predominantly [[livestock]] farmers who breed [[fat-tailed sheep]] and [[goat]]s, but count their [[wealth]] in the number of their [[cattle]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> They also grow and farm rain-fed [[crops]] such as [[maize]] and [[millet]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> Livestock are the major source of [[milk]] and [[meat]] for the OvaHimba. Their main diet is sour milk and maize porridge ( oruhere ruomaere) and sometimes plain hard porridge only, due to milk and meat scarcity. Their diet is also supplemented by [[cornmeal]], [[chicken]] eggs, wild [[herb]]s and [[honey]]. Only occasionally, and opportunistically, are the livestock sold for [[cash]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> Non-farming businesses, wages and salaries, pensions, and other cash remittances make up a very small portion of the OvaHimba livelihood, which is gained chiefly from their work in [[conservation area|conservancies]], old-age [[pension]]s, and [[drought]] relief aid from the [[government of Namibia]].<ref name=\"METNG\" />\n\n===Daily life===\nWomen and girls tend to perform more labor-intensive work than men and boys do, such as carrying water to the village, [[earthen plaster]]ing the [[Mopane#Uses|mopane]] wood homes with a traditional mixture of [[ultisol|red clay soil]] and cow [[manure]] [[Binder (material)|binding agent]], collecting firewood, attending to the [[calabash]] vines used for producing and ensuring a secure supply of [[soured milk]], cooking and serving meals, as well as [[artisan]]s making [[handicraft]]s, [[clothing]] and [[jewelry]].<ref name=\"METNG\" /> The responsibility for milking the cows and goats also lies with the women and girls.<ref name=\"METNG\" /> Women and girls take care of the children, and one woman or girl will take care of another woman's children. The men's main tasks are tending to the [[livestock]] farming, [[herding]] where the men will often be away from the family home for extended periods, [[animal slaughter]]ing, [[construction]], and holding [[council]] with village [[tribal chief]]s.<ref name=\"METNG\" /> \n\nMembers of a single extended family typically dwell in a [[Homestead (small African settlement)|homestead]] (''onganda''), a small family-village, consisting of a circular hamlet of huts and work shelters that surround an ''okuruwo'' ([[fire worship|sacred ancestral fire]]) and a [[kraal]] for the [[sacred]] livestock. Both the fire and the livestock are closely tied to their [[veneration of the dead]], the sacred fire representing ancestral protection and the sacred livestock allowing \"proper relations between human and ancestor\".{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=18}}\n\nThe OvaHimba use a heterogeneous pasture system that includes both rainy-season pastures and dry-season pastures. Dry-season pastures are rested during the rainy season which results in higher biomass production in the soil compared to constantly grazing all pastures. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=M\u00fcller|first=Birgit|last2=Linst\u00e4dter|first2=Anja|last3=Frank|first3=Karin|last4=Bollig|first4=Michael|last5=Wissel|first5=Christian|date=2007|title=Learning from Local Knowledge: Modeling the Pastoral-Nomadic Range Management of the Himba, Namibia|url=https://esajournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1890/06-1193.1|journal=Ecological Applications|language=en|volume=17|issue=7|pages=1857\u20131875|doi=10.1890/06-1193.1|issn=1939-5582}}</ref>\n\n===Clothing and hair style===\n[[File:Himba Girls Photo by Sascha Grabow.JPG|thumb|150px|Young Himba girls. The ''Erembe'' headdress indicates both are married.]]\n[[Image:Himba lady preparing deodorant.jpg|thumb|150px|Himba woman preparing [[incense]], the smoke is used as an [[antimicrobial]] body cleansing agent, [[deodorant]] and fragrant, made by burning aromatic herbs and resins.]]\nBoth the Himba men and women are accustomed to wearing traditional clothing that benefits their living environment in the [[Kaokoland]] and the hot [[semi-arid climate]] of their area, in most occurrences this consists simply of [[skirt]]-like [[clothing]] made from [[calfskin]]s and sheep skin or increasingly from more modern textiles, and occasionally [[sandal]]s for footwear. Women's sandals are made from cows' skin; while men's are made from old car tires.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} Women who have given birth wear a small backpack of skin attached to their traditional outfit. Himba people, especially women, are remarkably famous for covering themselves with ''[[otjize]]'' paste, a [[cosmetics|cosmetic]] mixture of [[butterfat]] and [[ochre]] pigment, to cleanse the skin over long periods due to [[water scarcity]] and protect themselves from the extremely hot and dry climate of the [[Kaokoland]] as well as insect bites. The cosmetic mixture, often perfumed with the aromatic resin of the ''omuzumba'' [[shrub]], gives their skin and hair [[Braid|plait]]s a distinctive orange or red-tinge characteristic, as well as texture and style.<ref name=\"METNG\" /> Otjize is considered foremost a highly desirable [[Aesthetics|aesthetic]] beauty cosmetic, symbolizing earth's rich red color and blood the essence of life, and is consistent with the OvaHimba ideal of [[beauty]].<ref name=\"DMHT\" />\n\nHairstyle and jewelry play a significant role among the OvaHimba, indicating age and social status within their community.<ref name=\"DMHT\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2607647/Incredible-photos-reveal-elaborate-hairdos-Himba-tribe-created-using-goat-hair-MUD.html|title=That's an unusual look! Namibia's Himba tribeswomen...|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=2014-04-18|accessdate=2014-09-01}}</ref> Both men and women wear adornments around their necks, arms, and feet. An infant or child will generally have his or her head kept shaven of hair, or with just a small crop of hair on the crown of the head. This soon is sculptured, for young boys, into one braided plait extending to the rear of the head. Young girls have two braided plaits extending forward towards the face, often parallel to their eyes, the form of wear being determined by the ''oruzo'' membership (patrilineal descent group). The style remains during [[preadolescence]] until [[puberty]].<ref name=\"DMHT\" /> Some young girls may also have one braided plait extending forwards, which means they are one of a pair of [[twin]]s.<ref name=\"DMHT\" />\n\nFrom pubescence, boys continue to have one braided plait, while girls will have many ''otjize''-textured hair plaits, some arranged to [[veil]] the girl's face. In daily practice the plaits are often tied together and held parted back from the face.<ref name=\"DMHT\" /> Women who have been married for about a year, or have had a child, wear an ornate headpiece called the ''Erembe'', sculptured from [[sheepskin]], with many streams of braided hair, coloured and put in shape with otjize paste.<ref name=\"DMHT\" /> Unmarried young men continue to wear one braided plait extending to the rear of the head, while married men wear a [[cap]] or head-wrap and un-braided hair beneath.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newlynatural.com/blog/2011/01/himba-hair-styling/|title=Himba Hair Styling|last=Kcurly|date=4 January 2011|website=Newly Natural|accessdate=2012-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://goafrica.about.com/library/bl.himba.htm|title=Tribes of Africa. The Himba|website=Africa Travel|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=2012-08-04}}</ref> [[Widow]]ed men will remove their cap or head-wrap and expose un-braided hair. The OvaHimba are also accustomed to use [[wood ash]] for hair cleansing due to [[water scarcity]].<ref name=\"DMHT\" />\n\n===Customary practices===\nThe OvaHimba are [[Polygamy|polygamous]], with the average Himba man being husband to two wives at the same time. They also practice early [[arranged marriage]]s. Young Himba girls are married to male partners chosen by their fathers. This happens from the onset of puberty,<ref name=\"METNG\" /> which may mean that girls aged 10 or below are married off. This practice is illegal in Namibia, and even some OvaHimba contest it, but it is nevertheless widespread.<ref>{{cite news | title=Opuwo's lonely voice against child marriages | last=Kangootui | first=Nomhle |newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=26 May 2016 | page=1 | url= http://www.namibian.com.na/Opuwo\u2019s-lonely-voice-against-child-marriages/40932/read}}</ref>\nAmong the Himba people, it is customary as a [[rite of passage]] to [[circumcision|circumcise]] boys before puberty. Upon marriage, a Himba boy is considered a man, unlike a Himba girl who is not considered a fully-fledged woman until she bears a child. \n[[File:Namibie Himba 0720a.jpg|thumb|Young Himba woman and child, the woman wearing a headpiece and beaded anklets or omohanga]]\n\n\nMarriage among the OvaHimba involves transactions of cattle, which are the source of their economy. Bridewealth is involved in these transactions; this can be negotiable between the groom's family and the bride's father, depending on the relative poverty of the families involved.<ref>Crandall, D. (1998). The Role of Time in Himba Valuations of Cattle. The Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute, 4(1), 101-114. doi:10.2307/3034430</ref> In order for the bride's family to accept the bridewealth, the cattle must appear of high quality. It is standard practice to offer an ox, but more cattle will be offered if the groom's father is wealthy and is capable of offering more.\n<br />\n\n===Societal participation===\n[[File:Himba village, Namibia (2014).jpg|thumb|left|Typical Himba village near [[Uis]] in [[Namibia]] (2014)]]\nDespite the fact a majority of OvaHimba live a distinct cultural [[Lifestyle (sociology)|lifestyle]] in their remote rural environment and homesteads, they are [[Social dynamics|socially dynamic]], and not all are isolated from the trends of local [[urban culture]]s. The OvaHimba coexist and interact with members of their country's other ethnic groups and the social trends of urban townsfolk. This is especially true of those in proximity to the Kunene Region capital of [[Opuwo]], who travel frequently to shop at the local town [[supermarket]]s for the convenience of commercial consumer products, market food produce and to acquire [[health care]].<ref name=\"METNG\" />\n\n===Links with Western culture===\nSome Himba children attend Western schools and some young people leave the homelands to live in towns.<ref>BBC article https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-40247310</ref>\n\n==Tribal structure==\n[[File:Headman Kapika und sein Enkel.jpg|left|thumb|200px|A traditional regional [[Leaders of Hereroland|Leader]] or Headman of the OvaHimba - Chief Kapuka Thom (\u2020 2009) of the Vita (Thom) Royal House<ref name=\"PASEAN\">{{Cite book|title=Imagining The Post-Apartheid State: An Ethnographic Account of Namibia|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dV2mAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA204&lpg=PA204&dq=Kapuka+Thom&source=bl&ots=ZCTJhx0th3&sig=UB1fh-6VnC0Mnh8s567ITlktwJk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Hha_U6-yHMbC0QXLx4GYAw&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Kapuka%20Thom&f=false|volume=|first=John|last=Friedman|publisher=Berghahn Books|location=Oxford, New York|year=2011|language=|page=204|isbn=9781782383239}}</ref> with his grandson]]\nBecause of the harsh desert climate in the region where they live and their seclusion from outside influences, the OvaHimba have managed to maintain and preserve much of their traditional lifestyle. Members live under a tribal structure based on [[bilateral descent]] that helps them live in one of the most extreme environments on earth.\n\n[[File:Himba-Arbeit.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Himba girl at work]]\nUnder bilateral descent, every tribe member belongs to two clans: one through the father (a patriclan, called ''oruzo'') and another through the mother (a matriclan, called ''eanda'').{{sfn|Crandall|2000}} Himba clans are led by the eldest male in the clan.  Sons live with their father's clan, and when daughters marry, they go to live with the clan of their husband.  However, inheritance of wealth does not follow the patriclan but is determined by the matriclan, that is, a son does not inherit his father's cattle but his maternal uncle's instead. Along with the inheritance of wealth, moral obligations are also important within the tribal structure. When a person dies, the OvaHimba evaluate the care of those who are left behind, such as orphans and widows. Access to water-points and pastures are another part of the OvaHimba inheritance structure.\n\nBilateral descent is found among only a few groups in West Africa, India, Australia, Melanesia and Polynesia, and anthropologists consider the system advantageous for groups that live in extreme environments because it allows individuals to rely on two sets of kin dispersed over a wide area.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?chanID=sa006&articleID=0005596A-DE68-1C6F-84A9809EC588EF21|title=The Himba and the Dam|first=Carol|last=Ezzell|date=17 June 2001|magazine=[[Scientific American]]|url-access=subscription|journal=|access-date=20 July 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012142329/http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?chanID=sa006&articleID=0005596A-DE68-1C6F-84A9809EC588EF21|archive-date=12 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe OvaHimba history is fraught with disasters, including severe droughts and guerrilla warfare, especially during Namibia's war of independence and as a result of the civil war in neighboring [[Angola]]. Between 1904\u20131908, they suffered from the same attempt at genocide during the [[Herero Wars]] conducted by the [[German Empire]] colonist government in [[German South-West Africa]] under [[Lothar von Trotha]] that decimated notably the [[Herero people]] and the [[Nama people]] during the [[Herero and Namaqua Genocide]].{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\nIn the 1980s it appeared the OvaHimba way of life was coming to a close due to a climax in adverse climatic conditions and political conflicts.<ref name=\"RMHE\">{{Cite book|title=Risk Management in a Hazardous Environment: A Comparative Study of two Pastoral Societies|volume=|first=Michael|last=Bollig|authorlink=|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SsPO7wYv1VkC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=Springer Science+Business Media, Inc.|location=New York|year=2006|language=|chapter=|pages=167\u2013168|isbn=9780387275819}}</ref> A severe drought killed 90% of their livestock, and many gave up their herds and became refugees in the town of [[Opuwo]] living in [[slum]]s on international [[humanitarian aid]] or joined [[Koevoet]] paramilitary units to cope with the [[livestock]] losses and widespread [[famine]].<ref name=\"RMHE\" /> OvaHimba living over the border in Angola, were occasionally victims of [[kidnapping]] during the South African Border war, either taken as hostages or abducted to join the Angolan branch of the [[People's Liberation Army of Namibia]] (PLAN, army of [[SWAPO]]).<ref name=\"RMHE\" />\n\n===Religion===\nThe OvaHimba are a [[monotheism|monotheistic]] people who worship the god [[Mukuru]], as well as their clan's ancestors ([[Veneration of the dead|ancestor reverence]]). Mukuru only blesses, while the ancestors can bless and curse.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=188}} Each family has its own [[Fire worship|sacred ancestral fire]], which is kept by the fire-keeper. The fire-keeper approaches the [[sacred]] ancestral fire every seven to eight days in order to communicate with Mukuru and the ancestors on behalf of his family.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=47}} Often, because Mukuru is busy in a distant realm, the ancestors act as Mukuru's representatives.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=47}}\n\nThe OvaHimba traditionally believe in ''omiti'', which some translate to mean [[witchcraft]] but which others call \"[[black magic]]\" or \"bad medicine\".{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=33}} Some OvaHimba believe that death is caused by ''omiti'', or rather, by someone using ''omiti'' for malicious purposes.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|pp=38\u201339}} Additionally, some believe that evil people who use ''omiti'' have the power to place bad thoughts into another's mind{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=102}} or cause extraordinary events to happen (such as when a common illness becomes life-threatening).{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=66}} But users of ''omiti'' do not always attack their victim directly; sometimes they target a relative or loved one.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=67}} Some OvaHimba will consult a [[traditional healers of South Africa|traditional African diviner-healer]] to reveal the reason behind an extraordinary event, or the source of the ''omiti''.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=66}}\n\n===Since Namibian independence===\n[[File:Himba Mobile School.JPG|thumb|Himba mobile school]]\nThe OvaHimba have been successful in maintaining their culture and traditional way of life.\n\nAs such, the OvaHimba have worked with international activists to block a proposed hydroelectric dam along the [[Kunene River#The Epupa dam|Kunene River]] that would have flooded their ancestral lands,<ref name=\"UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs\">{{cite news |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report/76311/NAMIBIA-Dam-will-mean-our-destruction-warn-Himba=eng |title=Namibia: Dam will mean our destruction, warn Himba |work=[[IRIN]] |publisher=[[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] |date=18 January 2008}}</ref> 2011, Namibia announced its new plan to build a dam in Orokawe, in the Baynes Mountains. The OvaHimba submitted in February 2012 their protest Declaration against the hydroelectric dam to the United Nations, the African Union and to the Government of Namibia.<ref name=\"ep1061\" />\n\nThe government of Norway and Iceland funded mobile schools for Himba children, but since Namibia took them over in 2010, they have been converted to permanent schools and are no longer mobile. The Himba leaders complain in their declaration about the culturally inappropriate school system, that they say would threaten their culture, identity and way of life as a people.\n\n===Human rights===\nGroups of the last remaining hunters and gatherers Ovatwa are held in secured camps in the northern part of Namibia's Kunene region, despite complaints by the traditional Himba chiefs that the Ovatwa are held there without their consent and against their wishes.<ref name=\"osi\">{{cite web |title=Indigenous coalition opposed to new dam |url=http://www.osisa.org/indigenous-peoples/namibia/indigenous-coalition-opposed-new-dam |website=[[OSISA]] |first=Delme |last=Cupido |date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-02-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304071437/http://www.osisa.org/indigenous-peoples/namibia/indigenous-coalition-opposed-new-dam |archive-date=4 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, [[traditional]] Himba chiefs<ref name=\"Galdu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.galdu.org/web/index.php?odas=5638&giella1=eng |title=Indigenous Himba Appeal to UN to Fight Namibian Dam |website=Galdu |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |accessdate=2012-04-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017232022/http://www.galdu.org/web/index.php?odas=5638&giella1=eng |archivedate=2013-10-17 }}</ref> issued two separate Declarations<ref name=\"ep1070\" /><ref name=\"newsodrome\">{{cite web|url=http://newsodrome.com/native_american_news/namibian-minority-groups-demand-their-rights-29917361 |title=Namibian Minority Groups Demand Their Rights |website=Newsodrome |accessdate=2012-04-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017135555/http://newsodrome.com/native_american_news/namibian-minority-groups-demand-their-rights-29917361 |archivedate=October 17, 2013 }}</ref> to the [[African Union]] and to the [[OHCHR]] of the [[United Nations]].\n\nThe first, titled \"Declaration of the most affected Ovahimba, Ovatwa, Ovatjimba and Ovazemba against the Orokawe Dam in the Baynes Mountains\"<ref name=\"ep1061\">{{cite web |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=1061 |title=Declaration of the most affected Ovahimba, Ovatwa, Ovatjimba and Ovazemba against the Orokawe Dam in the Baynes Mountains |website=Earth Peoples |date=7 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-04-06}}</ref> outlines the objections from regional Himba chiefs and communities that reside near the Kunene River.\n\nThe second, titled \"Declaration by the traditional Himba leaders of [[Kaokoland]] in [[Namibia]]\"<ref name=\"ep1070\">{{cite web |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=1070 |title=Declaration by the traditional Himba leaders of Kaokoland in Namibia |website=Earth Peoples |date=20 January 2012 |accessdate=2012-04-06}}</ref> lists violations of civil, cultural, economic, environmental, social and political rights perpetrated by the government of [[Namibia]] (GoN).\n\nSeptember 2012, the [[United Nations]] [[United Nations special rapporteur|Special Rapporteur]] on the Rights of [[Indigenous Peoples]] visited the OvaHimba and heard their concerns that they do not have recognized traditional authorities and that they are placed under the jurisdictions of chiefs of neighboring dominant tribes, who make decisions on behalf of the minority communities. In his view, the lack of recognition of traditional chiefs, in accordance with Namibian law, relates to a lack of recognition of the minority indigenous tribes' communal lands.<ref name=\"OHCHR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=12603&LangID=E=eng |title=Statement of the Special Rapporteur on the rights of indigenous peoples, James Anaya, upon concluding his visit to Namibia from 20-28 September 2012 |date=28 September 2012 |website=[[OHCHR]] |accessdate=2012-11-28}}</ref>\n\nNovember 23, 2012, hundreds of OvaHimba and Zemba from Omuhonga and Epupa region protested in Okanguati against Namibia's plans to construct a dam in the Kunene River in the Baynes Mountains, against increasing mining operations on their traditional land and human rights violations against them.<ref name=\"Earth Peoples1\">{{cite web |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=2910=eng |title=Namibia: Indigenous semi-nomadic Himba and Zemba march in protest against dam, mining and human rights violations |first=Rebecca |last=Sommer |authorlink=Rebecca Sommer|date=23 November 2012 |website=Earth Peoples |accessdate=2012-11-24}}</ref>\n\nMarch 25, 2013, over 1,000 Himba people marched in protest again, this time in Opuwo, against the ongoing human rights violations that they endure in Namibia. They expressed their frustration over the lack of recognition of their traditional chiefs as \"Traditional Authorities\" by the government;<ref name=\"Earth Peoples2\">{{cite web |title=German GIZ directly engaged with dispossessing indigenous peoples of their lands and territories in Namibia|publisher=earthpeoples.org|url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=4151 |accessdate=2013-03-30}}</ref> Namibia's plans to build the Orokawe dam in the Baynes Mountains at the Kunene River without consulting with the OvaHimba, who do not consent to the construction plans; culturally inappropriate education; the illegal fencing of parts of their traditional land; and their lack of property rights to the territory that they have lived upon for centuries. They also protested against the implementation of the Communal Land Reform Act of 2002.<ref name=\"Allafrica\">{{cite news |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201303260714.html |title=Himba, Zemba reiterate 'no' to Baynes dam |first=Catherine |last=Sasman |newspaper=[[Allafrica]] |date= |accessdate=2014-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn October 14, 2013, Himba chief Kaipka, on behalf of his region Epupa and the community which was featured in German RTL reality TV show ''Wild Girls'' condemned the misuse of Himba people, individuals and villagers in the show, and demanded the halt of broadcasting any further episodes as they would mock the culture and way of being of the Himba people.<ref name=\"Earth Peoples3\">{{cite web |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=5395=eng |title=Indigenous peoples Himba community condemn RTL TV series Wild Girls, asking Earth Peoples co-founder Rebecca Sommer for help to intervene on their behalf and stop it |website=Earth Peoples |accessdate=2013-10-16}}</ref>\n\nMarch 29, 2014, OvaHimba from both countries, Angola and Namibia, march again in protest against the dam's construction plans as well as against the government attempt to bribe their regional Himba chief. In the signed letter of the Himba community from Epupa, the region that would be directly affected by the dam, the traditional leaders explain that any consent form signed by a former chief as a result of bribery wasn't valid as they remain opposed to the dam.<ref name=\"Earth People4\">{{cite news |url=http://earthpeoples.org/blog/?p=5669 |title=NAMIBIA Semi-nomadic HIMBA march again in protest against dam construction and government attempt to bribe Himba chief\u2019s consent |first=Rebecca |last=Sommer |website=earthpeoples.org |date= |accessdate=2014-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Anthropological investigations==\n\n===Color perception===\n{{see also|Linguistic relativity and the color naming debate}}\nSeveral researchers have studied the OvaHimba perception of colours.<ref name=\"himba colour\">\n{{cite web|last=Roberson|first=Debi|last2=Davidoff|first2=Jules|last3=Davies|first3=Ian R.L.|last4=Shapiro|first4=Laura R.|title=Colour Categories and Category Acquisition in Himba and English|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/43627151_Colour_categories_and_category_acquisition_in_Himba_and_English|format=pdf|website=The Department of Psychology|publisher=[[University of Essex]]|accessdate=2012-05-28}}</ref> The OvaHimba use four colour names: ''zuzu'' stands for dark shades of blue, red, green and purple; ''vapa'' is white and some shades of yellow; ''buru'' is some shades of green and blue; and ''dambu'' is some other shades of green, red and brown.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Reiger |first=Terry |first2=Paul |last2=Kay |title=Language, thought, and color: Whorf was half right |journal=[[Trends (journals)|Trends in Cognitive Sciences]] |date=28 August 2009 |doi=10.1016/j.tics.2009.07.001 |url=http://www1.icsi.berkeley.edu/~kay/tics2.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=2012-08-29 |volume=13 |pages=439\u2013446 |pmid=19716754}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Ovahimba==\n* [[Vipuakuje Muharukua]], member of Namibia's Parliament\n\n==See also==\n* [[Herero people]]\n* [[Nama people]]\n* [[Oorlam people]]\n* [[Ovambo people]]\n* [[Zemba people]]\n\n<gallery widths=\"154px\" heights=\"200px\" class=\"center\" caption=\"\">\nFile:Himba village.jpg|Himba village about 15&nbsp;km north of [[Opuwo]], Namibia.\nFile:Himba Woman and Family.JPG|Himba woman and some of her family standing in her father's homestead in Otutati, [[Kunene Region]], Namibia.\nFile:Namibie Himba 0721a.jpg|Himba woman working, Namibia.\nFile:Namibie Himba 0705a.jpg|Pubescent Himba girl with hair headdress styled to [[veil]] her face.\nFile:Himba-Hirten-02.jpg|Male Himba herders.\nFile:Namibie Himba 0713a.jpg|Himba woman prepares a fire. Himba huts in the background.\nFile:Namibie Himba 0716a.jpg|As is customary in Himba culture and climate, a Himba girl of northern Namibia wears a traditional skirt made from calfskin leather, headdress and jewelry which signify her social status.\nFile:Himba women 2008.jpg|Himba woman working\n</gallery>\n\n==Literature==\n*{{Cite book|title=Strategies That Integrate Environmental Sustainability Into National Development Planning Process to Address Livelihood Concerns of the OvaHimba Tribe in Namibia - A Summary|volume=|first=|last=Kamaku Consultancy Services cc., Commissioned by: Country Pilot Partnership (CPP) Programme Namibia|authorlink=|url=http://www.met.gov.na/CPP/Resources/Himba%20research%20Study%20Report.pdf|publisher=The Ministry of Environment and Tourism, Republic of Namibia.|location=Windhoek, Namibia|year=2011|language=|chapter=|pages=|isbn=|access-date=2014-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031219/http://www.met.gov.na/CPP/Resources/Himba%20research%20Study%20Report.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Nomads at the Crossroads|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3ZhhY-oaalIC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|volume=|first=O.P|last=Goyal|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|location=New Delhi|year=2005|language=|pages=9&ndash;11|isbn=9788182051492}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Risk Management in a Hazardous Environment: A Comparative Study of two Pastoral Societies|volume=|first=Michael|last=Bollig|authorlink=|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SsPO7wYv1VkC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=Springer Science+Business Media, Inc.|location=New York|year=2006|language=|chapter=|pages=|isbn=9780387275819}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Ma vie avec les Ovahimba|volume=|first=Rina|last=Sherman|authorlink=|url=http://www.rinasherman.com/Writing/publicationslivres.html#vie}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Pieds nus sur la terre rouge|volume=|first=Solenn|last=Bardet|authorlink=|url=https://www.association-kovahimba.net/fr/boutique-27/81-non-categorise/81-livre}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Rouge Himba|volume=|first=Solenn|last=Bardet|authorlink=|url=https://www.association-kovahimba.net/fr/boutique-27/81-non-categorise/83-bande-dessinee}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Crandall|first=David P.|year=2000|title=The Place of Stunted Ironwood Trees: A Year in the Lives of the Cattle-Herding Himba of Namibia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC|location=New York|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group Inc.|isbn=0-8264-1270-X|ref=harv|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA18 18], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA33 33], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA38 38\u201339], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA47 47], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA48 48], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA66 66], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA67 67], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA102 102], [https://books.google.com/books?id=z-aow7Sb0JgC&pg=PA188 188]}}\n* Peter Pickford, Beverly Pickford, Margaret Jacobsohn: ''Himba''; ed. New Holland Publishers (UK) Ltd, 1990; {{ISBN|978-1-85368-084-7}}\n* Klaus G. F\u00f6rg, Gerhard Burkl: ''Himba. Namibias ockerrotes Volk''; Rosenheim: Rosenheimer Verlagshaus, 2004; {{ISBN|3-475-53572-6}} (''in German'')\n* Rina Sherman: ''Ma vie avec les Ovahimba''; Paris: Hugo et Cie, 2009; {{ISBN|978-2-7556-0261-6}} (''in French'')\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|Himba}}\n*[https://vimeo.com/205791464 Himbas, struggle for survive; a long term documentary by photojournalist and filmmaker Delmi Alvarez]\n*[http://www.ovahimba.rinasherman.com The Ovahimba Years I Les ann\u00e9es Ovahimba]\n*[http://www.der.org/films/keep-the-dance-alive.html Keep the Dance Alive I Que la danse continue]\n*[http://semioweb.msh-paris.fr/corpus/pci/EN/video.asp?id=939&ress=3005&video=65367&format=47 Sept ann\u00e9es chez les Ovahimba]\n*[http://peacecorpsonline.org/messages/messages/467/2064131.html A Peace Corps volunteer works among the Himba]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UB6gD5q6950 HIMBA CUSTOMS from Namibia. Extract from ''Last Free Men'' by Jos\u00e9 Manuel Novoa]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pOXpRS5y8qM HIMBA DANCE in Omuhonga, Kaokoland, Namibia, video by Rebecca Sommer]\n*[http://www.kovahimba.org Association Kovahimba], created by Solenn Bardet\n\n===Photographs===\n*[http://www.matthieurivart.com/hearts-of-sand Hearts of sand] \u2013 Photography by Matthieu Rivart\n*[http://www.rinasherman.com/indexphot.html The Ovahimba Years] \u2013 Photography by Rina Sherman.\n*[https://www.klaustiedge.com/product-category/tribe-prints/himba/ The Himba Tribe] \u2013 Photography by Klaus Tiedge.\n*[http://www.benjaminrennicke.de/portfolio/Ovahimba Photos of the Himba People in Okangwati] \u2013 Photography by Benjamin Rennicke.\n*[http://www.pgoimages.com/gallery.php?gall=g_namibia_himba Photographs of the Himba in Namibia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080613152141/http://blog.lukaesenko.com/2008/06/10/himba-the-beautiful-people/ Photos from Himba village near Opuwo, Namibia] \u2013 Photographs and information.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060318183106/http://www.on-the-matrix.com/africa/himba.asp Africa on the Matrix: Himba People of Namibia] \u2013 Photographs and information.\n\n===Movies===\n*[https://www.association-kovahimba.net/fr/boutique-27/50-bande-annonce/bande-annonce/70-les-himbas-font-leur-cinema-6 The Himba are shooting] \u2013 movie by Solenn Bardet (French and English).\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Angola}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Namibia}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Namibia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Angola]]\n[[Category:Herero people]]\n[[Category:Pastoralists]]\n[[Category:African nomads]]\n", "name_user": "MathXplore", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMovies", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Himba_people"}
{"title_page": "Carl Dahlstr\u00f6m", "text_new": "{{about||the American ice hockey centre who played with the Chicago Black Hawks from 1937 to 1945|Cully Dahlstrom|the Finnish merchant|Carl Magnus Dahlstr\u00f6m}}\n{{short description|Swedish ice hockey defenceman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Carl Dahlstr\u00f6m\n| image = Carl Dahlstr\u00f6m 2014.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption = Dahlstr\u00f6m with [[Link\u00f6ping HC]] in 2014\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1995|01|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 231\n| position = [[Defenceman|Defence]]\n| shoots = Left\n| league = [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| team = [[Winnipeg Jets]]\n| prospect_team = <!--[[Manitoba Moose]]-->\n| prospect_league = [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| former_teams = [[Link\u00f6ping HC]]<br>[[Chicago Blackhawks]]\n| draft = 51st overall\n| draft_year = 2013\n| draft_team = [[Chicago Blackhawks]]\n| career_start = 2013\n| career_end = \n}}\n'''Carl Dahlstr\u00f6m''' (born 28 January 1995) is a [[Swedes|Swedish]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[defenceman]] for the <!--[[Winnipeg Jets]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) as a prospect to the--> [[Winnipeg Jets]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). He was selected by the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] in the second round (51st overall) of the [[2013 NHL Entry Draft]].\n\n==Playing career==\nDahlstr\u00f6m made his professional debut in Sweden with youth club, [[Link\u00f6ping HC]] during the [[2013 European Trophy]].<ref>{{citeweb| url = http://www.eliteprospects.com/team.php?team=6&status=stats | title = Link\u00f6pings HC 2013\u201314 player statistics | publisher = eliteprospects.com | date = 6 May 2014 | accessdate = 6 May 2014}}</ref> On 14 April 2016, Dahlstr\u00f6m agreed to a three-year entry-level contract with the Chicago Blackhawks. He was immediately assigned to complete the [[2015\u201316 AHL season|2015\u201316 season]] with [[American Hockey League|AHL]] affiliate, the [[Rockford IceHogs]].<ref>{{citeweb| url = http://blackhawks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=878817 | title = Blackhawks agree to terms with Dahlstrom | publisher = [[Chicago Blackhawks]] | date = 14 April 2016 | accessdate = 14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2017\u201318 AHL season|2017\u201318 season]], Dahlstr\u00f6m, along with teammate [[Matthew Highmore]], were the only players from Rockford named to the 2018 AHL All-Star Classic.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Filomeno|first1=Joshua|title=Dahlstrom, Highmore Named AHL All-Stars|url=http://www.mystateline.com/sports/dahlstrom-highmore-named-ahl-all-stars/924844001|website=mystateline.com|accessdate=24 January 2018|date=18 January 2018}}</ref> Dahlstr\u00f6m made his NHL debut against the [[Minnesota Wild]] on 10 February 2018 where he had one shot on net.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pierce|first1=Jessi|title=Dubnyk, Wild shut out Blackhawks in fifth straight loss|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/chicago-blackhawks-minnesota-wild-game-recap/c-295837404|website=NHL.com|accessdate=19 March 2018|date=10 February 2018}}</ref> He recorded his first NHL point in a 7\u20131 win over the [[Washington Capitals]] on 17 February 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roumeliotis|first1=Charlie|title=Blackhawks end eight-game losing streak with win against Capitals|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/washington-capitals-chicago-blackhawks-game-recap/c-296089476|website=NHL.com|accessdate=19 March 2018|date=18 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2019, Dahlstr\u00f6m signed a two-year contract extension with the Blackhawks.<ref>{{cite web |title=RELEASE: Blackhawks agree to extension with Dahlstrom |url=https://www.nhl.com/blackhawks/news/release-blackhawks-agree-to-extension-with-dahlstrom/c-306177702 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=27 March 2019 |date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 1, 2019, Dahlstr\u00f6m was claimed off of waivers by the Winnipeg Jets.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| border=\"0\" cell