ory:Swedish ice hockey defencemen]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Jets players]]\n\n{{Sweden-icehockey-defenceman-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Dahlstr%C3%B6m"}
{"title_page": "KOVR", "text_new": "{{short description|CBS TV station in Stockton, California}}\n{{About|the Sacramento television station||CBS 13 (disambiguation){{!}}CBS 13}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2008}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = KOVR\n| city                     = [[Stockton, California]]\n| station_logo             = [[File:KOVR logo.svg|180px]]\n| station_branding         = CBS 13 ''(general)''<br/>''CBS 13 News'' ''(newscasts)''\n| station_slogan           = ''Getting Answers''\n| digital                  = 25 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 13 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = {{ubl|'''13.1:''' [[CBS]] ('''[[owned-and-operated station|O&O]]''')|'''13.2:''' [[Start TV]]|'''13.3:''' [[Dabl]]}}\n| owner                    = [[CBS Television Stations]]<br>''(a subsidiary of [[ViacomCBS]])''\n| licensee                 = Sacramento Television Stations, Inc.\n| location                 = [[Stockton, California|Stockton]]\u2013[[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]]\u2013[[Modesto, California]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1954|9|6|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''KOVR''' = '''covering''' all of [[Northern California]]\n| sister_stations          = [[KMAX-TV]]\n| former_callsigns         = \n| former_channel_numbers   = {{ubl|'''Analog:'''|13 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]], 1954\u20132009)}}\n| former_affiliations      = {{ubl|[[Independent station (North America)|Independent]] (1954\u20131957)|[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (1957\u20131995)}}\n| effective_radiated_power = 1,000 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|593|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 56550\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|38|14|24|N|121|30|7|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://sacramento.cbslocal.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''KOVR''', [[virtual channel]] 13 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 25), is a [[CBS]] [[owned-and-operated station|owned-and-operated]] [[television station]] serving [[Sacramento, California]], United States that is [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Stockton, California|Stockton]]. The station is owned by the [[CBS Television Stations]] subsidiary of [[ViacomCBS]], as part of a [[duopoly (broadcasting)|duopoly]] with Sacramento-licensed [[The CW|CW]] owned-and-operated station [[KMAX-TV]] (channel 31). The two stations share studios on KOVR Drive in [[West Sacramento, California|West Sacramento]] and [[KXTV/KOVR tower|transmitter facilities]] in [[Walnut Grove, California|Walnut Grove]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\nThe station first signed on the air on September 6, 1954, with its first broadcast originating from the [[California State Fair]]. KOVR is the oldest continuously operating television station in the Sacramento market. Originally serving as an [[Independent station (North America)|independent station]] with its transmitter located on [[Mount Diablo]], its signal reached the [[San Francisco Bay Area]], lending to the KOVR call letters (\"covering\" all of [[Northern California]]). The station originally operated from studio facilities located on Miner Avenue in Stockton. [[Art Finley]] hosted an afternoon [[children's television series|children's program]], ''Toonytown'', on the station for several years, before moving to [[San Francisco]]'s [[KRON-TV]].\n\n===As an ABC affiliate===\nIn May 1957, KOVR merged its operations with Sacramento's original [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate, KCCC-TV (channel 40, which signed on eleven months before KOVR in September 1953). KCCC shut down, with KOVR acquiring the ABC affiliation. At the network's request, the station moved its transmitter facilities to a temporary site near [[Jackson, California|Jackson]] to avoid competition with [[KGO-TV]] in San Francisco. By this time, it was obvious that Sacramento, Stockton and [[Modesto, California|Modesto]] were going to be a single television market. In 1960, KOVR teamed up with [[KCRA-TV]] (channel 3) and [[KXTV]] (channel 10) to build a new [[KXTV/KOVR/KCRA Tower|{{convert|1,549|ft|m|sing=on}} tower]] in Walnut Grove. In 1985, KOVR and KXTV moved to their current {{convert|2049|ft|m|sing=on}} tower while KCRA moved to [[Hearst-Argyle Tower|its own {{convert|2000|ft|m|sing=on}} tower]]; KCRA still uses the old tower as an auxiliary facility.\n\nIn 1958, the [[Gannett|Gannett Company]] (whose successor company, [[Tegna Inc.|Tegna]], now owns rival KXTV) bought KOVR from its original owners, then sold it the following year to [[John Kluge]]'s Metropolitan Broadcasting (which later became [[Metromedia]]). In 1960, the station moved its business offices and news department to a new studio facility on Arden Way in Sacramento. In 1987, KOVR consolidated its operations into its current facility in West Sacramento.\n\n[[Image:651211-KOVR News 1965.png|thumb|250px|A 1965 advertisement for then ABC affiliate KOVR touting [[Peter Jennings]] as anchor of ''[[ABC World News Tonight|Peter Jennings with the News]]''.]]\nMetromedia sold KOVR to [[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy Newspapers]] in 1964. McClatchy ran the station alongside ''[[The Sacramento Bee]]'' and ''[[Modesto Bee]]'' newspapers, as well as radio stations [[KWG (AM)|KWG]] (1230 AM) in Stockton, [[KESP|KBEE]] (970 AM) in Modesto and [[KFBK (AM)|KFBK]] (1530 AM) in Sacramento. McClatchy was able to own KOVR, KWG, KBEE and KFBK because Sacramento, Stockton and Modesto, then as now, were separate radio markets. McClatchy had established a trio of bee mascots (originally designed by [[Walt Disney]], whose [[The Walt Disney Company|namesake company]] would eventually acquire ABC in 1996) for its properties. Teevee the Bee was KOVR's official mascot during the years that McClatchy owned the station \u2013 short cartoons of the bee bookended KOVR's broadcast day, either ushering in or concluding the day's programming.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RNgecUK3SJA|title=KOVR \"McClatchy Bee\" Sign-Off|first=|last=KLXT77|date=April 6, 2008|publisher=|access-date=February 22, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nAfter McClatchy sold the station to [[The Outlet Company|Outlet Communications]] in 1978, KOVR went into a gradual decline in terms of both ratings and programming quality (even as ABC became the country's highest-rated network), and has been in third place in the Sacramento ratings for most of the time since then. The station was then sold to Narragansett Television [[Limited partnership|LP]] in 1986, then to Anchor Media in 1988. Anchor Media was merged into [[River City Broadcasting]] in 1993, and River City was purchased by the [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] three years later. KOVR has made some firsts in local broadcasting: it was the first station in Northern California to use [[videotape]] (rather than film) for its newscasts, and was the first station in the Sacramento/Stockton area to broadcast in [[stereophonic sound|stereo]].\n\nAs an ABC affiliate, KOVR preempted a moderate amount of programming, even the 30-minute soap opera ''[[Loving (TV series)|Loving]]''. It also aired some ABC programming out of pattern: ''[[All My Children]]'' in the early years was aired at 11 a.m. (half of ABC's affiliates aired the soap at 11 a.m. to follow it with their noon newscasts; until the series was cancelled in 2011, the network recommended that the program run in the noon timeslot). In the mid-1990s, KOVR moved the soap opera to 3 p.m., a practice continued by KXTV following its affiliation switch with KOVR until the early 2000s.\n\n===Switching to CBS===\nOn March 6, 1995, KOVR [[1994-96 United States broadcast TV realignment|swapped networks]] with longtime [[CBS]] affiliate KXTV; KOVR is the third station in Sacramento to have been affiliated with CBS: before moving to KXTV, KCCC carried the network secondarily to its primary ABC affiliation. Despite joining CBS, KOVR chose not to air ''[[Guiding Light]]'', a practice originated by KXTV during its CBS days (due to the show's below-average ratings in the area). When the program ended its run on September 18, 2009, it was one of only two CBS affiliates that did not carry the show; the other, [[WNEM-TV]] in [[Bay City, Michigan]], aired it on a [[MyNetworkTV]]-affiliated [[digital subchannel]]. During ''Guiding Light''{{'}}s last 16 seasons, Sacramento viewers had to view it on cable via future sister station [[KPIX]].\n\n[[Image:KOVR.jpg|thumb|KOVR's previous logo, under Sinclair ownership. This logo is similar to a former logo of another Sinclair-owned station, [[Portland, Maine|Portland]], [[Maine]]'s [[WGME]].]]\nA more notable oddity with KOVR's affiliation with CBS is that the station runs the network's prime time lineup one hour earlier than the standard 8 (7 on Sundays) to 11 p.m. scheduling for the [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific]] as well as the [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]] time zones, opting to run it from 7 to 10 p.m. (the standard scheduling used by stations in the [[Central Time Zone|Central]] and [[Mountain Time Zone|Mountain]] time zones). When KOVR was an ABC affiliate, the station had an 11 p.m. newscast like most stations on the coastal time zones. Upon the network switch, the station followed the then-practice of now-sister station KPIX in having an hour-long prime time newscast at 10 p.m. (KPIX later moved its late evening newscast back to the 11 p.m. slot in 1998). In recent ratings periods, KOVR has battled [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[KTXL]] (channel 40) for the lead among the newscasts in the 10 p.m. timeslot, with KOVR leading in total households and KTXL leading in the key demographics.\n\nIn 2001, KOVR gained attention when it landed a \"local exclusive\" interview with Congressman [[Gary Condit]] regarding the [[Chandra Levy]] murder case (Condit appeared the same evening on ABC, in an interview with [[Connie Chung]]). The station televised an interview on August 30 in which Condit claimed that he did not kill Levy after a visit with the slain intern. Despite numerous KOVR reports filed by reporter Gloria Gomez, the Condit interview was granted to another KOVR reporter, Jodi Hernandez. Much of the national interest in the case was lost days later, in the aftermath of the [[September 11 attacks]].\n\nIn December 2004, Sinclair sold KOVR to [[Viacom (1971\u20132005)|Viacom]] Television Stations Group (now part of [[ViacomCBS]] as [[CBS Television Stations]]), creating the third duopoly in the Sacramento market with [[KMAX-TV]] (channel 31, then a [[UPN]] owned-and-operated station, now a [[The CW|CW]] O&O) and CBS' third television duopoly in California (after [[KCBS-TV]] and [[KCAL-TV]] in [[Los Angeles]]; and KPIX and [[KBCW (TV)|KBCW]] in San Francisco). Viacom was forced to sell [[KFRC (defunct)|KFRC radio]] in San Francisco as a condition of the sale, as the station's city-grade signal reaches Sacramento; the purchase was finalized on April 29, 2005. The station then changed its on-air branding from \"KOVR 13\" to \"CBS 13\".\n\n==Digital television==\n\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=KOVR|title=RabbitEars.Info|author=|date=|website=www.rabbitears.info|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 13.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=3|[[16:9]] || KOVR-DT || Main KOVR programming / [[CBS]]\n|-\n| 13.2 || rowspan=2|[[480i]] || startTV || [[Start TV]]\n|-\n| 13.3 || DABL || [[Dabl]]\n|}\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nKOVR shut down its analog signal, over [[Very high frequency|VHF]], on June 12, 2009, as part of the [[Digital television transition in the United States|federally mandated transition from analog to digital television]].<ref>[http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf List of Digital Full-Power Stations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |date=2013-08-29 }}</ref> The station's digital signal remained on its pre-transition [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 25,<ref name=\"FCCForm387\">{{cite web|url=https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101233298&formid=387&fac_num=56550|title=CDBS Print|author=|date=|website=licensing.FCC.gov|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref> using [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]] to display KOVR's [[virtual channel]] as 13 on digital television receivers.\n\n==Programming==\nKOVR is the only CBS station in the [[Pacific Time Zone]] that runs its prime time lineup out of pattern from the network's recommended scheduling ([[MyNetworkTV]] affiliate [[KQCA]], channel 58, similarly began carrying that service's schedule one hour behind from 7 to 9 p.m. on September 5, 2006; in 2009, KQCA moved MyNetworkTV programming back to the 8 to 10 p.m. timeslot until 2014). After CBS purchased channel 13, some, including station management, had speculated that KOVR would move the CBS prime time lineup back to its standard 8\u201311 p.m. slot and add ''Guiding Light'' to the schedule, as well as drop ''[[The Jerry Springer Show|Jerry Springer]]''. It was assumed that as an O&O, KOVR would have to carry ''Guiding Light'' (most network-owned stations run the entire network programming schedule, with exceptions only for breaking news coverage or special programming). However, on May 3, 2005, CBS announced that it would make no immediate programming changes, including any addition of ''Guiding Light'' (which remained off the station through its final episode in September 2009).\n\nOn August 11, 2005, CBS announced that KOVR's 7\u201310 p.m. scheduling of the prime time lineup, the 10 p.m. newscast and the 11 p.m. airing of the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' would remain in place due to the success of the early prime schedule. At that point, it also stated that ''Guiding Light'' would not join the KOVR schedule; it is believed that this was based on the logic that a show that had not been available in the market for over 14 years would not receive good ratings, and that there were few requests to run the program. On July 31, 2006, KOVR received approval from CBS to move the weekend prime time lineup back an hour in order to maintain an hour-long 10 p.m. newscast seven days a week, to take effect August 27. ''[[The Late Late Show (CBS TV series)|The Late Late Show]]'' (which had been airing at 1 a.m.) was also pushed one hour earlier, while ''Jerry Springer'' (which aired at 3 p.m. until September 8, 2006) was bumped to a later timeslot before moving to [[KMAX-TV]] in September 2006 (the program moved to [[KQCA]] one year later). KOVR began clearing the entire CBS network schedule in September 2009, after ''Guiding Light'' ended and was temporarily replaced by a secondary run of ''[[The Price Is Right (American game show)|The Price Is Right]]''; ''[[Let's Make a Deal]]'' began airing the following month at 9 a.m. (outside of the show's more common 2 p.m. slot for stations in the Pacific Time Zone).\n\nOn July 30, 2018, KOVR began airing a newscast at 11 p.m., relocating the program from sister station KMAX-TV where it has aired for six years. ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' moved to 11:35 p.m. and ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' moved to 12:37 a.m. The scheduling changes marked the first time KOVR will air an 11 p.m. weeknight newscast since its affiliation switch from ABC to CBS in 1995. It also marked the first time since 1995 the CBS late night lineup on KOVR will be in pattern with the rest of the CBS stations in the Pacific Time Zone.\n\n==News operation==\n{{Refimprove section|date=November 2010}}\nKOVR presently broadcasts 37 hours of locally produced newscasts each week (with 6\u00bd hours each weekday, two hours on Saturdays and 2\u00bd hours on Sundays). KOVR debuted its noon newscast in 1965 as a 15-minute broadcast, which was followed by ''People, Places & Things'' at 12:15&nbsp;p.m. In the 1980s, KOVR aired the ABC soap opera ''[[All My Children]]'' at 11 a.m. (on a day-behind [[broadcast delay|tape delay]]) in order to free the noon slot for the newscast.\n\nWhile under Sinclair ownership, KOVR had worked with a small to medium-sized news staff, unusual considering Sacramento's dramatic growth during the 1980s had made it a top-20 market. It was one of several Sinclair-owned stations that did not participate in Sinclair's controversial ''[[News Central]]'' hybrid news format; this [[Centralcasting|centralized]] operation incorporated national news segments, local [[weather forecasting|weather forecast]] segments, and some sports coverage based out of studios at Sinclair's corporate headquarters on Beaver Dam Road in [[Hunt Valley, Maryland|Hunt Valley]], [[Maryland]] that was supplemented by local content at most of Sinclair's in-house news departments. After CBS purchased KOVR, both it and KMAX-TV's news departments were consolidated at KOVR's West Sacramento facility. On-air staff from both stations periodically appear on their respective newscasts.\n\nMost of KOVR's on-air staffers that were with the station under Sinclair ownership have either been fired or have resigned. Dismissals of former lead anchors Paul Joncich and Jennifer Whitney were sudden and unannounced whereas Marcy Valenzuela and Jennifer Krier were allowed to say farewell to viewers on air. Remaining on-air staff include chief meteorologist [[Dave Bender]] and investigative reporter Kurtis Ming. On February 1, 2006, Pallas Hup\u00e9 and former KCRA anchor Sam Shane became the station's new main anchor team; the evening newscast also instituted a three-anchor format, which began with Shane and Hup\u00e9 anchoring the day's major news stories, deferring to anchor/reporter Christina Anderson (now Janes) for national and international headlines. The unique three-anchor setup remained during the weekend 10 p.m. newscasts with rotating anchors. In July 2006, KOVR debuted an hour-long 4 p.m. newscast on weekdays. In January 2018, KOVR reinstated a sports department, which has been without one since the departure of John Henk in the late 1990s.\n\nIn October 2008, KOVR began broadcasting its local newscasts in [[high-definition television|high-definition]]. Only the in-studio segments are presented in HD; however, for over a year-and-a-half after KTXL upgraded its newscasts to HD, KOVR was the only station in the Sacramento market that still presented its remote field reports in [[pillarbox]]ed [[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|standard-definition]]. Atypical for a duopoly, sister station KMAX-TV did not upgrade its newscasts to HD until summer 2009. KOVR has since begun using HD cameras for its field reports; however, much of the field footage is still downconverted to 16:9 widescreen standard definition in the control room. The station's 10 p.m. newscast won a 2010 Emmy Award for \"Best Evening Newscast\" and was the #1 rated late newscast in Sacramento during the May 2010 ratings period.\n\nKOVR also produces a newscast for sister station KMAX, which air weekdays at 6:30 p.m.. In addition, KOVR provides news updates during [[KMAX-TV|KMAX]]'s morning news program ''Good Day''. The weekend afternoon, evening, and late newscasts are translated into [[Spanish language in the United States|Spanish]] via the station's [[Second audio program|SAP]] feed.\n\n===CBS13.com Rush Limbaugh controversy===\nIn May 2007, KOVR revamped its morning news program with an emphasis on its website. The 5\u20136&nbsp;a.m. hour of the newscast, titled ''CBS13.com'', centered around viewer feedback through the web, viral videos and news found on the Internet. On May 7, 2007, the program reported on a song that conservative radio broadcaster [[Rush Limbaugh]] played heavily on his nationally syndicated program called \"Barack the [[Magic Negro]]\" (to the tune of \"[[Puff the Magic Dragon]]\") that spoofed the then-upcoming [[2008 United States presidential election|election]] of [[Barack Obama]]. The song was a satire of an article called \"Magic Negro Returns\"<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2007/mar/19/opinion/oe-ehrenstein19 `Magic Negro' returns], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', March 19, 2007.</ref> that had appeared in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' claiming that Mr. Obama was \u2013 in many people's minds \u2013 fulfilling a Hollywood film archetype the author called the \"Magic Negro\", who has only positive attributes and exists to improve the lives of the main protagonists, who are white.\n\nThe program ran an online poll asking people whether they thought the song was [[Racism in the United States|racist]]. Limbaugh blasted KOVR, claiming it was a part of the \"liberal media\", and called the anchor team of Chris Burrous, Lisa Gonzales and weather anchor Jeff James \"morons\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509041608/http://www.rushlimbaugh.com/home/daily/site_050707/content/01125108.guest.html|title=KOVR in Sacramento Misreports \"Barack, the Magic Negro\"|author=|date=May 9, 2007|website=web.Archive.org|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref> Throughout that day's newscasts, KOVR covered Limbaugh's remarks against the station, adding with a disclaimer after every story that KOVR never intended to couple Limbaugh with the parody song<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n6WXGWMdAs4|title=YouTube|author=|date=|website=www.youtube.com|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref> and admitting that the station found the song on [[YouTube]].\n\n===Notable current on-air staff===\n* [[Kristine Hanson]] \u2013 meteorologist (since 2016; previously at KOVR from 2004 to 2005)\n* [[Christina Anderson (journalist)|Christina Janes]] \u2013 anchor\n\n===Notable former on-air staff===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Stan Atkinson]] \u2013 anchor (1994\u20131999; previously with [[KCRA-TV]], now retired running local ads)\n* [[Claudia Cowan]] \u2013 anchor/reporter (later moved to [[KRON-TV]] in [[San Francisco]]; now reporter for [[Fox News]] in [[New York City]])\n* [[Jonathan Elias]] \u2013 investigative reporter (1991\u20131993, now anchor/reporter at [[WJLA-TV]] in [[Washington, D.C.]])\n* [[Lois Hart]] \u2013 anchor (later at KCRA-TV, now retired)\n* [[Bob Hilton]] \u2013 anchor\n* [[Kinsey Schofield]] \u2013 anchor/reporter (2017)\n* [[Steve Somers]] (now at [[sports radio]] station [[WFAN]] in New York City)\n* [[Jim Wieder]] \u2013 reporter/anchor (1989\u20132005; retired from anchoring in 2006)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Out-of-market cable coverage==\n{{Expand section|date = June 2010}}\nKOVR is available on [[cable television|cable]] in the northern parts of the Bay Area, mostly in northern [[Solano County, California|Solano County]] communities that are part of the Sacramento-Stockton-Modesto media market as defined by Nielsen. KOVR can also be seen in most of the [[Chico, California|Chico]] area.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://sacramento.cbslocal.com/}}\n*{{TVQ|KOVR}}\n*{{BIA|KOVR|TV|TV}}\n\n{{Sacramento TV}}\n{{CBS California}}\n{{CBSTVS}}\n{{Major U.S. TV O-O Stations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kovr}}\n[[Category:CBS Television Stations]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Sacramento, California|OVR]]\n[[Category:CBS network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Metromedia]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1954]]\n[[Category:West Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Start TV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Dabl affiliates]]\n[[Category:Former Gannett subsidiaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|CBS TV station in Stockton, California}}\n{{About|the Sacramento television station||CBS 13 (disambiguation){{!}}CBS 13}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2008}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = KOVR\n| city                     = [[Stockton, California]]\n| station_logo             = [[File:KOVR logo.svg|180px]]\n| station_branding         = CBS 13 ''(general)''<br/>''CBS 13 News'' ''(newscasts)''\n| station_slogan           = ''Getting Answers''\n| digital                  = 25 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 13 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = {{ubl|'''13.1:''' [[CBS]] ('''[[owned-and-operated station|O&O]]''')|'''13.2:''' [[Start TV]]|'''13.3:''' [[Dabl]]}}\n| owner                    = [[CBS Television Stations]]<br>''(a subsidiary of [[ViacomCBS]])''\n| licensee                 = Sacramento Television Stations, Inc.\n| location                 = [[Stockton, California|Stockton]]\u2013[[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]]\u2013[[Modesto, California]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1954|9|6|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''KOVR''' = '''covering''' all of [[Northern California]]\n| sister_stations          = [[KMAX-TV]]\n| former_callsigns         = \n| former_channel_numbers   = {{ubl|'''Analog:'''|13 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]], 1954\u20132009)}}\n| former_affiliations      = {{ubl|[[Independent station (North America)|Independent]] (1954\u20131957)|[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (1957\u20131995)}}\n| effective_radiated_power = 1,000 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|593|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 56550\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|38|14|24|N|121|30|7|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://sacramento.cbslocal.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''KOVR''', [[virtual channel]] 13 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 25), is a [[CBS]] [[owned-and-operated station|owned-and-operated]] [[television station]] serving [[Sacramento, California]], United States that is [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Stockton, California|Stockton]]. The station is owned by the [[CBS Television Stations]] subsidiary of [[ViacomCBS]], as part of a [[duopoly (broadcasting)|duopoly]] with Sacramento-licensed [[The CW|CW]] owned-and-operated station [[KMAX-TV]] (channel 31). The two stations share studios on KOVR Drive in [[West Sacramento, California|West Sacramento]] and [[KXTV/KOVR tower|transmitter facilities]] in [[Walnut Grove, California|Walnut Grove]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\nThe station first signed on the air on September 6, 1954, with its first broadcast originating from the [[California State Fair]]. KOVR is the oldest continuously operating television station in the Sacramento market. Originally serving as an [[Independent station (North America)|independent station]] with its transmitter located on [[Mount Diablo]], its signal reached the [[San Francisco Bay Area]], lending to the KOVR call letters (\"covering\" all of [[Northern California]]). The station originally operated from studio facilities located on Miner Avenue in Stockton. [[Art Finley]] hosted an afternoon [[children's television series|children's program]], ''Toonytown'', on the station for several years, before moving to [[San Francisco]]'s [[KRON-TV]].\n\n===As an ABC affiliate===\nIn May 1957, KOVR merged its operations with Sacramento's original [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate, KCCC-TV (channel 40, which signed on eleven months before KOVR in September 1953). KCCC shut down, with KOVR acquiring the ABC affiliation. At the network's request, the station moved its transmitter facilities to a temporary site near [[Jackson, California|Jackson]] to avoid competition with [[KGO-TV]] in San Francisco. By this time, it was obvious that Sacramento, Stockton and [[Modesto, California|Modesto]] were going to be a single television market. In 1960, KOVR teamed up with [[KCRA-TV]] (channel 3) and [[KXTV]] (channel 10) to build a new [[KXTV/KOVR/KCRA Tower|{{convert|1,549|ft|m|sing=on}} tower]] in Walnut Grove. In 1985, KOVR and KXTV moved to their current {{convert|2049|ft|m|sing=on}} tower while KCRA moved to [[Hearst-Argyle Tower|its own {{convert|2000|ft|m|sing=on}} tower]]; KCRA still uses the old tower as an auxiliary facility.\n\nIn 1958, the [[Gannett|Gannett Company]] (whose successor company, [[Tegna Inc.|Tegna]], now owns rival KXTV) bought KOVR from its original owners, then sold it the following year to [[John Kluge]]'s Metropolitan Broadcasting (which later became [[Metromedia]]). In 1960, the station moved its business offices and news department to a new studio facility on Arden Way in Sacramento. In 1987, KOVR consolidated its operations into its current facility in West Sacramento.\n\n[[Image:651211-KOVR News 1965.png|thumb|250px|A 1965 advertisement for then ABC affiliate KOVR touting [[Peter Jennings]] as anchor of ''[[ABC World News Tonight|Peter Jennings with the News]]''.]]\nMetromedia sold KOVR to [[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy Newspapers]] in 1964. McClatchy ran the station alongside ''[[The Sacramento Bee]]'' and ''[[Modesto Bee]]'' newspapers, as well as radio stations [[KWG (AM)|KWG]] (1230 AM) in Stockton, [[KESP|KBEE]] (970 AM) in Modesto and [[KFBK (AM)|KFBK]] (1530 AM) in Sacramento. McClatchy was able to own KOVR, KWG, KBEE and KFBK because Sacramento, Stockton and Modesto, then as now, were separate radio markets. McClatchy had established a trio of bee mascots (originally designed by [[Walt Disney]], whose [[The Walt Disney Company|namesake company]] would eventually acquire ABC in 1996) for its properties. Teevee the Bee was KOVR's official mascot during the years that McClatchy owned the station \u2013 short cartoons of the bee bookended KOVR's broadcast day, either ushering in or concluding the day's programming.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RNgecUK3SJA|title=KOVR \"McClatchy Bee\" Sign-Off|first=|last=KLXT77|date=April 6, 2008|publisher=|access-date=February 22, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nAfter McClatchy sold the station to [[The Outlet Company|Outlet Communications]] in 1978, KOVR went into a gradual decline in terms of both ratings and programming quality (even as ABC became the country's highest-rated network), and has been in third place in the Sacramento ratings for most of the time since then. The station was then sold to Narragansett Television [[Limited partnership|LP]] in 1986, then to Anchor Media in 1988. Anchor Media was merged into [[River City Broadcasting]] in 1993, and River City was purchased by the [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] three years later. KOVR has made some firsts in local broadcasting: it was the first station in Northern California to use [[videotape]] (rather than film) for its newscasts, and was the first station in the Sacramento/Stockton area to broadcast in [[stereophonic sound|stereo]].\n\nAs an ABC affiliate, KOVR preempted a moderate amount of programming, even the 30-minute soap opera ''[[Loving (TV series)|Loving]]''. It also aired some ABC programming out of pattern: ''[[All My Children]]'' in the early years was aired at 11 a.m. (half of ABC's affiliates aired the soap at 11 a.m. to follow it with their noon newscasts; until the series was cancelled in 2011, the network recommended that the program run in the noon timeslot). In the mid-1990s, KOVR moved the soap opera to 3 p.m., a practice continued by KXTV following its affiliation switch with KOVR until the early 2000s.\n\n===Switching to CBS===\nOn March 6, 1995, KOVR [[1994-96 United States broadcast TV realignment|swapped networks]] with longtime [[CBS]] affiliate KXTV; KOVR is the third station in Sacramento to have been affiliated with CBS: before moving to KXTV, KCCC carried the network secondarily to its primary ABC affiliation. Despite joining CBS, KOVR chose not to air ''[[Guiding Light]]'', a practice originated by KXTV during its CBS days (due to the show's below-average ratings in the area). When the program ended its run on September 18, 2009, it was one of only two CBS affiliates that did not carry the show; the other, [[WNEM-TV]] in [[Bay City, Michigan]], aired it on a [[MyNetworkTV]]-affiliated [[digital subchannel]]. During ''Guiding Light''{{'}}s last 16 seasons, Sacramento viewers had to view it on cable via future sister station [[KPIX]].\n\n[[Image:KOVR.jpg|thumb|KOVR's previous logo, under Sinclair ownership. This logo is similar to a former logo of another Sinclair-owned station, [[Portland, Maine|Portland]], [[Maine]]'s [[WGME]].]]\nA more notable oddity with KOVR's affiliation with CBS is that the station runs the network's prime time lineup one hour earlier than the standard 8 (7 on Sundays) to 11 p.m. scheduling for the [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific]] as well as the [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]] time zones, opting to run it from 7 to 10 p.m. (the standard scheduling used by stations in the [[Central Time Zone|Central]] and [[Mountain Time Zone|Mountain]] time zones). When KOVR was an ABC affiliate, the station had an 11 p.m. newscast like most stations on the coastal time zones. Upon the network switch, the station followed the then-practice of now-sister station KPIX in having an hour-long prime time newscast at 10 p.m. (KPIX later moved its late evening newscast back to the 11 p.m. slot in 1998). In recent ratings periods, KOVR has battled [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[KTXL]] (channel 40) for the lead among the newscasts in the 10 p.m. timeslot, with KOVR leading in total households and KTXL leading in the key demographics.\n\nIn 2001, KOVR gained attention when it landed a \"local exclusive\" interview with Congressman [[Gary Condit]] regarding the [[Chandra Levy]] murder case (Condit appeared the same evening on ABC, in an interview with [[Connie Chung]]). The station televised an interview on August 30 in which Condit claimed that he did not kill Levy after a visit with the slain intern. Despite numerous KOVR reports filed by reporter Gloria Gomez, the Condit interview was granted to another KOVR reporter, Jodi Hernandez. Much of the national interest in the case was lost days later, in the aftermath of the [[September 11 attacks]].\n\nIn December 2004, Sinclair sold KOVR to [[Viacom (1971\u20132005)|Viacom]] Television Stations Group (now part of [[ViacomCBS]] as [[CBS Television Stations]]), creating the third duopoly in the Sacramento market with [[KMAX-TV]] (channel 31, then a [[UPN]] owned-and-operated station, now a [[The CW|CW]] O&O) and CBS' third television duopoly in California (after [[KCBS-TV]] and [[KCAL-TV]] in [[Los Angeles]]; and KPIX and [[KBCW (TV)|KBCW]] in San Francisco). Viacom was forced to sell [[KFRC (defunct)|KFRC radio]] in San Francisco as a condition of the sale, as the station's city-grade signal reaches Sacramento; the purchase was finalized on April 29, 2005. The station then changed its on-air branding from \"KOVR 13\" to \"CBS 13\".\n\n==Digital television==\n\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=KOVR|title=RabbitEars.Info|author=|date=|website=www.rabbitears.info|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 13.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=3|[[16:9]] || KOVR-DT || Main KOVR programming / [[CBS]]\n|-\n| 13.2 || rowspan=2|[[480i]] || startTV || [[Start TV]]\n|-\n| 13.3 || DABL || [[Dabl]]\n|}\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nKOVR shut down its analog signal, over [[Very high frequency|VHF]], on June 12, 2009, as part of the [[Digital television transition in the United States|federally mandated transition from analog to digital television]].<ref>[http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf List of Digital Full-Power Stations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |date=2013-08-29 }}</ref> The station's digital signal remained on its pre-transition [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 25,<ref name=\"FCCForm387\">{{cite web|url=https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101233298&formid=387&fac_num=56550|title=CDBS Print|author=|date=|website=licensing.FCC.gov|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref> using [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]] to display KOVR's [[virtual channel]] as 13 on digital television receivers.\n\n==Programming==\nKOVR is the only CBS station in the [[Pacific Time Zone]] that runs its prime time lineup out of pattern from the network's recommended scheduling ([[MyNetworkTV]] affiliate [[KQCA]], channel 58, similarly began carrying that service's schedule one hour behind from 7 to 9 p.m. on September 5, 2006; in 2009, KQCA moved MyNetworkTV programming back to the 8 to 10 p.m. timeslot until 2014). After CBS purchased channel 13, some, including station management, had speculated that KOVR would move the CBS prime time lineup back to its standard 8\u201311 p.m. slot and add ''Guiding Light'' to the schedule, as well as drop ''[[The Jerry Springer Show|Jerry Springer]]''. It was assumed that as an O&O, KOVR would have to carry ''Guiding Light'' (most network-owned stations run the entire network programming schedule, with exceptions only for breaking news coverage or special programming). However, on May 3, 2005, CBS announced that it would make no immediate programming changes, including any addition of ''Guiding Light'' (which remained off the station through its final episode in September 2009).\n\nOn August 11, 2005, CBS announced that KOVR's 7\u201310 p.m. scheduling of the prime time lineup, the 10 p.m. newscast and the 11 p.m. airing of the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' would remain in place due to the success of the early prime schedule. At that point, it also stated that ''Guiding Light'' would not join the KOVR schedule; it is believed that this was based on the logic that a show that had not been available in the market for over 14 years would not receive good ratings, and that there were few requests to run the program. On July 31, 2006, KOVR received approval from CBS to move the weekend prime time lineup back an hour in order to maintain an hour-long 10 p.m. newscast seven days a week, to take effect August 27. ''[[The Late Late Show (CBS TV series)|The Late Late Show]]'' (which had been airing at 1 a.m.) was also pushed one hour earlier, while ''Jerry Springer'' (which aired at 3 p.m. until September 8, 2006) was bumped to a later timeslot before moving to [[KMAX-TV]] in September 2006 (the program moved to [[KQCA]] one year later). KOVR began clearing the entire CBS network schedule in September 2009, after ''Guiding Light'' ended and was temporarily replaced by a secondary run of ''[[The Price Is Right (American game show)|The Price Is Right]]''; ''[[Let's Make a Deal]]'' began airing the following month at 9 a.m. (outside of the show's more common 2 p.m. slot for stations in the Pacific Time Zone).\n\nOn July 30, 2018, KOVR began airing a newscast at 11 p.m., relocating the program from sister station KMAX-TV where it has aired for six years. ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' moved to 11:35 p.m. and ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' moved to 12:37 a.m. The scheduling changes marked the first time KOVR will air an 11 p.m. weeknight newscast since its affiliation switch from ABC to CBS in 1995. It also marked the first time since 1995 the CBS late night lineup on KOVR will be in pattern with the rest of the CBS stations in the Pacific Time Zone.\n\n==News operation==\n{{Refimprove section|date=November 2010}}\nKOVR presently broadcasts 37 hours of locally produced newscasts each week (with 6\u00bd hours each weekday, two hours on Saturdays and 2\u00bd hours on Sundays). KOVR debuted its noon newscast in 1965 as a 15-minute broadcast, which was followed by ''People, Places & Things'' at 12:15&nbsp;p.m. In the 1980s, KOVR aired the ABC soap opera ''[[All My Children]]'' at 11 a.m. (on a day-behind [[broadcast delay|tape delay]]) in order to free the noon slot for the newscast.\n\nWhile under Sinclair ownership, KOVR had worked with a small to medium-sized news staff, unusual considering Sacramento's dramatic growth during the 1980s had made it a top-20 market. It was one of several Sinclair-owned stations that did not participate in Sinclair's controversial ''[[News Central]]'' hybrid news format; this [[Centralcasting|centralized]] operation incorporated national news segments, local [[weather forecasting|weather forecast]] segments, and some sports coverage based out of studios at Sinclair's corporate headquarters on Beaver Dam Road in [[Hunt Valley, Maryland|Hunt Valley]], [[Maryland]] that was supplemented by local content at most of Sinclair's in-house news departments. After CBS purchased KOVR, both it and KMAX-TV's news departments were consolidated at KOVR's West Sacramento facility. On-air staff from both stations periodically appear on their respective newscasts.\n\nMost of KOVR's on-air staffers that were with the station under Sinclair ownership have either been fired or have resigned. Dismissals of former lead anchors Paul Joncich and Jennifer Whitney were sudden and unannounced whereas Marcy Valenzuela and Jennifer Krier were allowed to say farewell to viewers on air. Remaining on-air staff include chief meteorologist [[Dave Bender]] and investigative reporter Kurtis Ming. On February 1, 2006, Pallas Hup\u00e9 and former KCRA anchor Sam Shane became the station's new main anchor team; the evening newscast also instituted a three-anchor format, which began with Shane and Hup\u00e9 anchoring the day's major news stories, deferring to anchor/reporter Christina Anderson (now Janes) for national and international headlines. The unique three-anchor setup remained during the weekend 10 p.m. newscasts with rotating anchors. In July 2006, KOVR debuted an hour-long 4 p.m. newscast on weekdays. In January 2018, KOVR reinstated a sports department, which has been without one since the departure of John Henk in the late 1990s.\n\nIn October 2008, KOVR began broadcasting its local newscasts in [[high-definition television|high-definition]]. Only the in-studio segments are presented in HD; however, for over a year-and-a-half after KTXL upgraded its newscasts to HD, KOVR was the only station in the Sacramento market that still presented its remote field reports in [[pillarbox]]ed [[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|standard-definition]]. Atypical for a duopoly, sister station KMAX-TV did not upgrade its newscasts to HD until summer 2009. KOVR has since begun using HD cameras for its field reports; however, much of the field footage is still downconverted to 16:9 widescreen standard definition in the control room. The station's 10 p.m. newscast won a 2010 Emmy Award for \"Best Evening Newscast\" and was the #1 rated late newscast in Sacramento during the May 2010 ratings period.\n\nKOVR also produces a newscast for sister station KMAX, which air weekdays at 6:30 p.m.. In addition, KOVR provides news updates during [[KMAX-TV|KMAX]]'s morning news program ''Good Day''. The weekend afternoon, evening, and late newscasts are translated into [[Spanish language in the United States|Spanish]] via the station's [[Second audio program|SAP]] feed.\n\n===CBS13.com Rush Limbaugh controversy===\nIn May 2007, KOVR revamped its morning news program with an emphasis on its website. The 5\u20136&nbsp;a.m. hour of the newscast, titled ''CBS13.com'', centered around viewer feedback through the web, viral videos and news found on the Internet. On May 7, 2007, the program reported on a song that conservative radio broadcaster [[Rush Limbaugh]] played heavily on his nationally syndicated program called \"Barack the [[Magic Negro]]\" (to the tune of \"[[Puff the Magic Dragon]]\") that spoofed the then-upcoming [[2008 United States presidential election|election]] of [[Barack Obama]]. The song was a satire of an article called \"Magic Negro Returns\"<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2007/mar/19/opinion/oe-ehrenstein19 `Magic Negro' returns], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', March 19, 2007.</ref> that had appeared in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' claiming that Mr. Obama was \u2013 in many people's minds \u2013 fulfilling a Hollywood film archetype the author called the \"Magic Negro\", who has only positive attributes and exists to improve the lives of the main protagonists, who are white.\n\nThe program ran an online poll asking people whether they thought the song was [[Racism in the United States|racist]]. Limbaugh blasted KOVR, claiming it was a part of the \"liberal media\", and called the anchor team of Chris Burrous, Lisa Gonzales and weather anchor Jeff James \"morons\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509041608/http://www.rushlimbaugh.com/home/daily/site_050707/content/01125108.guest.html|title=KOVR in Sacramento Misreports \"Barack, the Magic Negro\"|author=|date=May 9, 2007|website=web.Archive.org|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref> Throughout that day's newscasts, KOVR covered Limbaugh's remarks against the station, adding with a disclaimer after every story that KOVR never intended to couple Limbaugh with the parody song<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n6WXGWMdAs4|title=YouTube|author=|date=|website=www.youtube.com|access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref> and admitting that the station found the song on [[YouTube]].\n\n===Notable current on-air staff===\n* [[Kristine Hanson]] \u2013 meteorologist (since 2016; previously at KOVR from 2004 to 2005)\n* [[Christina Anderson (journalist)|Christina Janes]] \u2013 anchor\n\n===Notable former on-air staff===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Stan Atkinson]] \u2013 anchor (1994\u20131999; previously with [[KCRA-TV]], now retired running local ads)\n* [[Claudia Cowan]] \u2013 anchor/reporter (later moved to [[KRON-TV]] in [[San Francisco]]; now reporter for [[Fox News]] in [[New York City]])\n* [[Jonathan Elias]] \u2013 investigative reporter (1991\u20131993, now anchor/reporter at [[WJLA-TV]] in [[Washington, D.C.]])\n* [[Lois Hart]] \u2013 anchor (later at KCRA-TV, now retired)\n* [[Bob Hilton]] \u2013 anchor\n* [[Kinsey Schofield]] \u2013 anchor/reporter (2017)\n* [[Steve Somers]] (now at [[sports radio]] station [[WFAN]] in New York City)\n* [[Jim Wieder]] \u2013 reporter/anchor (1989\u20132005; retired from anchoring in 2006)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Out-of-market cable coverage==\n{{Expand section|date = June 2010}}\nKOVR is available on [[cable television|cable]] in the northern parts of the Bay Area, mostly in [[Solano County, California|Solano County]]. KOVR can also be seen in most of the [[Chico, California|Chico]] area.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://sacramento.cbslocal.com/}}\n*{{TVQ|KOVR}}\n*{{BIA|KOVR|TV|TV}}\n\n{{Sacramento TV}}\n{{CBS California}}\n{{CBSTVS}}\n{{Major U.S. TV O-O Stations}}\n\n{{DEFAULT