{"title_page": "Lake W\u0101naka", "text_new": "{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Lake W\u0101naka\n| image = Wanaka from mt roy.jpg\n| caption = View of Lake W\u0101naka from Mt. Roy.\n| image_bathymetry = NZ-L Wanaka.png\n| caption_bathymetry = Location on the [[South Island]]\n| location = [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown-Lakes District]], [[Otago]], [[South Island]]\n| coords = {{coord|44|30|S|169|08|E|region:NZ_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| type = \n| inflow = \n| outflow = [[Clutha River]]\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = New Zealand\n| length = {{convert|42|km|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}}\n| area = {{convert|192|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = approx. {{convert|300|m|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|278|m|abbr=on}}\n| islands = [[Harwich Island]], [[Mou Tapu]], [[Mou Waho]], [[Ruby Island, Lake W\u0101naka|Ruby Island]], [[Stevensons Island]]\n| cities = \n}}\n\n'''Lake W\u0101naka''' (also spelled '''Lake Wanaka''') is New Zealand's [[List of lakes in New Zealand#Largest lakes|fourth largest lake]].<ref>[http://www.newzealand.com/travel/destinations/regions/wanaka/wanaka-home.cfm Lake W\u0101naka] (from the [[Tourism New Zealand]] website)</ref> In the [[Otago]] region, it is 278 meters above sea level,<ref>[https://www.orc.govt.nz/managing-our-environment/water/water-monitoring-and-alerts/upper-clutha/Lake-wanaka Otago Regional Council] (Lake level monitoring)</ref> covers {{convert|192|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/otago-places/page-19|title=19. \u2013 Otago places \u2013 Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|last=Taonga|website=www.teara.govt.nz}}</ref>, and is more than {{convert|300|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep. \n\nThe original [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] name ''Oanaka'' means 'The place of Anaka', a local tribal chief.<ref name=\"TEARA\">[http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/W/WanakaLake/WanakaLake/en Wanaka, Lake] (from [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]], The 1966 New Zealand Encyclopaedia)</ref>\nThe town near the foot of the lake is named [[Wanaka]].\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Geography===\nLake W\u0101naka lies at the heart of the Otago Lakes in the lower South Island of New Zealand. The township, which sits in a glacier-carved basin on the shores of the lake, is the gateway to [[Mount Aspiring National Park|Mt Aspiring National Park]]. [[Lake H\u0101wea]] is a 15-minute drive away, en route to the frontier town of [[Makarora]], the last stop before the West Coast Glacier region. To the south is the historic [[Cardrona Valley]], a popular scenic alpine route to neighbouring [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]].\n\n===Geology===\nAt its greatest extent, which is roughly along a north\u2013south axis, the lake is 42 kilometres long. Its widest point, at the southern end, is 10 kilometres. The lake's western shore is lined with high peaks rising to over 2000 metres above sea level. Along the eastern shore the land is also mountainous, but the peaks are somewhat lower.\n\nLake W\u0101naka lies in a [[u-shaped valley]] formed by [[glacier|glacial]] erosion during the last [[ice age]], more than 10,000 years ago. It is fed by the [[Matukituki River|Matukituki]] and [[Makarora River]]s, and is the source of the [[Clutha River]]. Nearby [[Lake H\u0101wea]] lies in a parallel valley carved by a neighbouring glacier eight kilometres to the east. At their closest point (a rocky ridge called The Neck), the lakes are only 1,000 metres apart.<ref name=\"T2\">[http://www.newzealand.com/travel/sights-activities/scenic-highlights/lakes/sh-lake-wanaka-and-hawea.cfm Lakes: Laka Wanaka and Hawea] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/676ClFFma?url=http://www.newzealand.com/int/article/lakes-wanaka-and-hawea/ |date=2012-04-21 }} (from the [[Tourism New Zealand]] website)</ref>\n\nSmall islands towards the foot of the lake include Ruby Island, [[Stevensons Island]] and Harwich Island. Some host ecological sanctuaries, such as one for [[weka|buff weka]] on Stevensons Island.<ref name=\"TVNZ_710786\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/page/411879/710786 |title=What's Up DOC - Wanaka |work=[[Television New Zealand]] |accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe towns of [[Wanaka]] and [[Albert Town, New Zealand|Albert Town]] are near the lake's outflow into the [[Clutha River]].\n\n===Climate===\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location = Lake W\u0101naka\n| metric first = yes\n| single line = yes\n| Jan high C = 23.9\n| Feb high C = 23.4\n| Mar high C = 20.8\n| Apr high C = 17.3\n| May high C = 12.2\n| Jun high C = 8.4\n| Jul high C = 8.4\n| Aug high C = 11.0\n| Sep high C = 14.4\n| Oct high C = 16.8\n| Nov high C = 19.8\n| Dec high C = 21.9\n| Jan low C = 10.8\n| Feb low C = 10.4\n| Mar low C = 8.4\n| Apr low C = 5.1\n| May low C = 1.6\n| Jun low C = -0.9\n| Jul low C = -1.2\n| Aug low C = -0.2\n| Sep low C = 2.4\n| Oct low C = 5.0\n| Nov low C = 7.3\n| Dec low C = 9.6\n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan precipitation mm = 56.9\n| Feb precipitation mm = 50.2\n| Mar precipitation mm = 60.7\n| Apr precipitation mm = 56.4\n| May precipitation mm = 62.7\n| Jun precipitation mm = 54.5\n| Jul precipitation mm = 52.2\n| Aug precipitation mm = 52.8\n| Sep precipitation mm = 56.4\n| Oct precipitation mm = 63.1\n| Nov precipitation mm = 54.7\n| Dec precipitation mm = 51.9\n| year precipitation mm = 672.5\n| Jan sun = 231.5\n| Feb sun = 201.7\n| Mar sun = 182.6\n| Apr sun = 164.0\n| May sun = 135.5\n| Jun sun = 120.5\n| Jul sun = 126.6\n| Aug sun = 155.8\n| Sep sun = 172.5\n| Oct sun = 193.8\n| Nov sun = 202.2\n| Dec sun = 212.1\n| year sun = 2098.8\n| source = http://www.lakewanaka.co.nz/content/library/Weather_data.pdf\n}}\n\n==Human history==\n\n===Exploration and settlement===\n\nFor [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]], the W\u0101naka area was a natural crossroads. The [[Haast Pass]] gave access to the [[West Coast, New Zealand|West Coast]] and its [[pounamu]]; the Cardrona Valley led to the natural rock bridge \"Whatatorere\", which was the only place that the [[Kawarau River]] and [[Clutha River|Clutha River / Mata-Au]] could be crossed without boats.<ref name=\"DoC\">{{cite book\n|title=Bannockburn Heritage Landscape Study\n|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/Documents/science-and-technical/SfC244b.pdf\n|date=2004\n|author=Janet Stephenson, Heather Bauchop, and Peter Petchey\n|page=29\n}}</ref> Native reeds were used to build boats that enabled a swift return downriver to the east coast.\n\nThe Cromwell basin supported a large population of [[moa]], which were hunted to extinction about 500 years ago.<ref name=\"DoC\"/>\n\nUntil the early nineteenth century, W\u0101naka was visited annually by [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] who sought [[pounamu]] in the mountains above the [[Haast River]] and hunted eels and birds over summer, returning to the east coast by descending the [[Clutha River|Clutha River / Mata-Au]] in reed boats.<ref name=TeAraOtagoMaori>\n{{cite encyclopedia\n  |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/otago-region/page-4 \n| author=Malcolm McKinnon\n| title=Otago region - M\u0101ori history and whaling\n| encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|accessdate=2017-07-11}}</ref>  Ng\u0101i Tahu use of the land was ended by [[History of the Otago Region#Ngati Toa invasions|attacks by North Island tribes]].<ref name=\"DoC\"/> In 1836, the [[Ngati Tama]] chief [[Te Puoho-o-te-rangi|Te Puoho]] led a 100-person war party, armed with muskets, down the West Coast and over the Haast Pass: they fell on the Ng\u0101i Tahu encampment between Lake Wanaka and [[Lake H\u0101wea]], capturing 10 people and killing and eating two children.<ref name=Smith1910>{{cite book\n| title=History and Traditions of the Maoris of the West Coast North Island of New Zealand Prior to 1840\n|author=S Percy Smith\n|date=1910\n|publisher = Polynesian Society\n|location=New Plymouth \n|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-SmiHist-t1-body1-d21-d7.html\n}}</ref> Although Te Puoho was later killed by the southern Ng\u0101i Tahu leader [[Tuhawaiki]],<ref name=AthollAnderson>{{cite encyclopedia\n|author=Atholl Anderson\n|title =Te Puoho-o-te-rangi\n|volume =1\n|year=1990\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand \n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1t59/te-puoho-o-te-rangi\n|accessdate =2017-07-11}}</ref> M\u0101ori seasonal visits to the area ceased.\n\nThe first European to see the lake was Nathaniel Chalmers in 1853.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |author=Jock Phillips\n|title=European exploration - Otago and Southland\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/european-exploration/page-7\n|accessdate=2017-07-11\n}}\n</ref> Guided by Reko and Kaikoura, he walked from Tuturau ([[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]]) to the lake via the [[Kawarau River]]. However he was stricken by dysentery, so his guides returned him down the Clutha in a reed boat.<ref name=\"TeAraNC\">\n{{cite encyclopedia\n|author=Roger Frazer\n|title=Chalmers, Nathanael\n|series=Dictionary of New Zealand Biography \n|volume=1\n|date=1990\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1c11/chalmers-nathanael\n|accessdate=13 July 2017\n}}</ref>\n\nBy 1861, several sheep stations had been established in around the south end of the lake, and in 1862, the lake itself was surveyed in a whaleboat.<ref name=\"TEARA\"/> The early European name was Lake Pembroke.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=OW18890425.2.62&cl=&srpos=0&e=-------10--1----0-all&st=1%7CPASSIM|title=Papers Past - PASSIM NOTES. (Otago Witness, 1889-04-25)|first=National Library of New|last=Zealand|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz}}</ref>\n\n===Current use and tourism===\n[[File:Lake Wanaka.jpg|thumb|244px|right|Lake W\u0101naka on an overcast day.]]\n\nIn addition to ongoing sheep farming, the lake is now a popular resort, and is much used in the summer for [[fishing]], boating and [[human swimming|swimming]]. The nearby mountains and fast-flowing rivers allow for [[Adventure travel|adventure tourism]] year-round, with [[jetboat]]ing and [[skiing]] facilities located nearby.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lakewanaka.co.nz/|title=Wanaka Tourism}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]] airport close by, tourism mirrors that of the surrounding areas.\n\n===Conservation===\nAs one of the few lakes in the South Island with an unmodified shoreline, the lake is protected by special legislation, the Lake Wanaka Preservation Act of 1973. The Act established a 'Guardians of Lake Wanaka' group, appointed by the Minister of Conservation, which advises on measures to protect the lake.<ref>[http://www.doc.govt.nz/about-doc/role/corporate-publications/briefings-to-new-ministers-archive/briefing-to-the-incoming-minister-of-conservation-2011/6-institutional-arrangements/6_1-statutory-bodies/ Briefing to the incoming Minister of Conservation 2011 - containing information about Statutory bodies, including the Guardians] (from the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website, Friday 14 December 2012)</ref>\n\nOxygen weed (''[[Lagarosiphon major]]''), an aquarium plant and [[invasive species]] native to Southern Africa, has been a problem in the lake's ecosystem for some time. Attempts to eradicate the weed have not been successful. Substantial [[dredging|suction dredging]] operations have shown promise, but tend to miss isolated spots which then regrow into larger weed beds.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.linz.govt.nz/docs/crownproperty/biosecurity/lake-wanaka-assessment-2006.pdf |title= Assessment of the 2005/06 ''Lagarosiphon major'' programme in Lake Wanaka |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090920235224/http://www.linz.govt.nz/docs/crownproperty/biosecurity/lake-wanaka-assessment-2006.pdf |archivedate= 2009-09-20 }}&nbsp;{{small|(1.20&nbsp;[[Mebibyte|MiB]])}} ([[National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research|NIWA]] report, June 2006, from the [[Land Information New Zealand]] website)</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Wanaka pan.jpg|600px|View of Lake W\u0101naka, New Zealand}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n\"That Wanaka Tree\" - a [[willow]] growing just inside the lake - is a tourist attraction in its own right, featuring on many tourists' [[Instagram]] feeds.<ref>\n  {{cite news |title=Wanaka's famous Instagram tree attacked with a saw \n     |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/18/wanakas-famous-instagram-tree-attacked-with-a-saw \n     |accessdate=18 April 2020 \n     |publisher=The Guardian\n  }}\n</ref> The tree had its lower branches cut by vandals in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marcus|first=Lilit|url=https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/wanaka-tree-new-zealand-vandalism-intl-hnk/index.html|title=New Zealand's most famous tree, 'That Wanaka Tree,' vandalized|date=20 March 2020|work=CNN Travel|accessdate=18 April 2020|url-status=live|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ThatWanakaTree at Sunrise.jpg|thumb|right|That Wanaka Tree]]\n\nThe lake is referenced in the title of the song ''Lake Wanaka'' by [[Israelis|Israeli]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Keren Peles]].<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =\n | date =\n | title = \u05e7\u05e8\u05df \u05e4\u05dc\u05e1 - \u05dc\u05d9\u05d9\u05e7 \u05d5\u05d5\u05d0\u05e0\u05e7\u05d4 (\u05e7\u05dc\u05d9\u05e4)\n | trans-title = Keren Peles - Lake Wanaka (video music)\n | medium =\n | language = he\n | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g9prCgt9xXM\n | access-date =\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | format =\n | time =\n | location =\n | publisher =\n | id =\n | isbn =\n | oclc =\n | quote =\n | ref =\n}}</ref>\n\n===In film===\n\nThe region has been the setting for many international films, including ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasons.co.nz/wanaka/the-lord-of-the-rings-location-tarras-and-wanaka|title=The Lord of the Rings Location: Tarras & Wanaka}}</ref> ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newzealand.com/ie/feature/the-hobbit-trilogy-filming-locations/|title=The Hobbit Trilogy Filming Locations}}</ref> the ''Legend of S'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/regions/wanaka/chinese-fantasy-filming-wanaka|author=Otago Daily Times|access-date=27 January 2018|title=Chinese fantasy filming in Wanaka|date=2017-05-05}}</ref> and ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/travel/destinations/nz/89336353/witherspoon-winfrey-and-kaling-in-wanaka-and-lake-hawea|title=Witherspoon, Winfrey and Kaling in Wanaka and Lake Hawea}}</ref> Lake W\u0101naka repeatedly featured in the movie ''[[Mission: Impossible III]]'' as a location the lead couple visited and as the answer to [[Tom Cruise]]'s question on the phone to verify the identity of his wife.\n\nThe New Zealand cook and author [[Annabel Langbein]], who owns a small estate at the side of the lake, filmed her series ''The Free Range Cook'' and ''Simple Pleasures'' here.\n\n===As a reported refuge===\nNew Zealand has been reported to be a favoured refuge for the 'super rich' in the event of a cataclysm.<ref>\n  {{cite journal |last1=Osnos |first1=Evan \n    |title=Doomsday Prep for the Super-Rich \n    |journal=The New Yorker |date=23 January 2017 |issue=30 January 2017 \n    |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/01/30/doomsday-prep-for-the-super-rich |accessdate=18 April 2020\n  }}\n</ref> One such [[High-net-worth individual|high net worth individual]] is [[Peter Thiel]], who purchased {{convert|193|hectare|acre}} of lakeside land in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Facebook billionaire Peter Thiel a Kiwi citizen, owns Wanaka estate |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11787741 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |publisher=New Zealand Herald}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lakes of New Zealand]]\n*[[List of lakes in New Zealand]]\n*[[Otago Region#Geography|Otago Geography]]\n*[[Sentinel Peak (New Zealand)]]\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:W\u0101naka, Lake}}\n[[Category:Lakes of Otago]]\n[[Category:Wanaka]]\n[[Category:Clutha River]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Lake W\u0101naka\n| image = Wanaka from mt roy.jpg\n| caption = View of Lake W\u0101naka from Mt. Roy.\n| image_bathymetry = NZ-L Wanaka.png\n| caption_bathymetry = Location on the [[South Island]]\n| location = [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown-Lakes District]], [[Otago]], [[South Island]]\n| coords = {{coord|44|30|S|169|08|E|region:NZ_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| type = \n| inflow = \n| outflow = [[Clutha River]]\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = New Zealand\n| length = {{convert|42|km|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}}\n| area = {{convert|192|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = approx. {{convert|300|m|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|278|m|abbr=on}}\n| islands = [[Harwich Island]], [[Mou Tapu]], [[Mou Waho]], [[Ruby Island, Lake W\u0101naka|Ruby Island]], [[Stevensons Island]]\n| cities = \n}}\n\n'''Lake W\u0101naka''' (also spelled '''Lake Wanaka''') is New Zealand's [[List of lakes in New Zealand#Largest lakes|fourth largest lake]].<ref>[http://www.newzealand.com/travel/destinations/regions/wanaka/wanaka-home.cfm Lake W\u0101naka] (from the [[Tourism New Zealand]] website)</ref> In the [[Otago]] region, it is 278 meters above sea level,<ref>[https://www.orc.govt.nz/managing-our-environment/water/water-monitoring-and-alerts/upper-clutha/Lake-wanaka Otago Regional Council] (Lake level monitoring)</ref> covers {{convert|192|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/otago-places/page-19|title=19. \u2013 Otago places \u2013 Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|last=Taonga|website=www.teara.govt.nz}}</ref>, and is more than {{convert|300|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep. \n\nThe original [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] name ''Oanaka'' means 'The place of Anaka', a local tribal chief.<ref name=\"TEARA\">[http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/W/WanakaLake/WanakaLake/en Wanaka, Lake] (from [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]], The 1966 New Zealand Encyclopaedia)</ref>\nThe town near the foot of the lake is named [[Wanaka]].\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Geography===\nLake W\u0101naka lies at the heart of the Otago Lakes in the lower South Island of New Zealand. The township, which sits in a glacier-carved basin on the shores of the lake, is the gateway to [[Mount Aspiring National Park|Mt Aspiring National Park]]. [[Lake H\u0101wea]] is a 15-minute drive away, en route to the frontier town of [[Makarora]], the last stop before the West Coast Glacier region. To the south is the historic [[Cardrona Valley]], a popular scenic alpine route to neighbouring [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]].\n\n===Geology===\nAt its greatest extent, which is roughly along a north\u2013south axis, the lake is 42 kilometres long. Its widest point, at the southern end, is 10 kilometres. The lake's western shore is lined with high peaks rising to over 2000 metres above sea level. Along the eastern shore the land is also mountainous, but the peaks are somewhat lower.\n\nLake W\u0101naka lies in a [[u-shaped valley]] formed by [[glacier|glacial]] erosion during the last [[ice age]], more than 10,000 years ago. It is fed by the [[Matukituki River|Matukituki]] and [[Makarora River]]s, and is the source of the [[Clutha River]]. Nearby [[Lake H\u0101wea]] lies in a parallel valley carved by a neighbouring glacier eight kilometres to the east. At their closest point (a rocky ridge called The Neck), the lakes are only 1,000 metres apart.<ref name=\"T2\">[http://www.newzealand.com/travel/sights-activities/scenic-highlights/lakes/sh-lake-wanaka-and-hawea.cfm Lakes: Laka Wanaka and Hawea] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/676ClFFma?url=http://www.newzealand.com/int/article/lakes-wanaka-and-hawea/ |date=2012-04-21 }} (from the [[Tourism New Zealand]] website)</ref>\n\nSmall islands towards the foot of the lake include Ruby Island, [[Stevensons Island]] and Harwich Island. Some host ecological sanctuaries, such as one for [[weka|buff weka]] on Stevensons Island.<ref name=\"TVNZ_710786\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/page/411879/710786 |title=What's Up DOC - Wanaka |work=[[Television New Zealand]] |accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe towns of [[Wanaka]] and [[Albert Town, New Zealand|Albert Town]] are near the lake's outflow into the [[Clutha River]].\n\n===Climate===\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location = Lake W\u0101naka\n| metric first = yes\n| single line = yes\n| Jan high C = 23.9\n| Feb high C = 23.4\n| Mar high C = 20.8\n| Apr high C = 17.3\n| May high C = 12.2\n| Jun high C = 8.4\n| Jul high C = 8.4\n| Aug high C = 11.0\n| Sep high C = 14.4\n| Oct high C = 16.8\n| Nov high C = 19.8\n| Dec high C = 21.9\n| Jan low C = 10.8\n| Feb low C = 10.4\n| Mar low C = 8.4\n| Apr low C = 5.1\n| May low C = 1.6\n| Jun low C = -0.9\n| Jul low C = -1.2\n| Aug low C = -0.2\n| Sep low C = 2.4\n| Oct low C = 5.0\n| Nov low C = 7.3\n| Dec low C = 9.6\n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan precipitation mm = 56.9\n| Feb precipitation mm = 50.2\n| Mar precipitation mm = 60.7\n| Apr precipitation mm = 56.4\n| May precipitation mm = 62.7\n| Jun precipitation mm = 54.5\n| Jul precipitation mm = 52.2\n| Aug precipitation mm = 52.8\n| Sep precipitation mm = 56.4\n| Oct precipitation mm = 63.1\n| Nov precipitation mm = 54.7\n| Dec precipitation mm = 51.9\n| year precipitation mm = 672.5\n| Jan sun = 231.5\n| Feb sun = 201.7\n| Mar sun = 182.6\n| Apr sun = 164.0\n| May sun = 135.5\n| Jun sun = 120.5\n| Jul sun = 126.6\n| Aug sun = 155.8\n| Sep sun = 172.5\n| Oct sun = 193.8\n| Nov sun = 202.2\n| Dec sun = 212.1\n| year sun = 2098.8\n| source = http://www.lakewanaka.co.nz/content/library/Weather_data.pdf\n}}\n\n==Human history==\n\n===Exploration and settlement===\n\nFor [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]], the W\u0101naka area was a natural crossroads. The [[Haast Pass]] gave access to the [[West Coast, New Zealand|West Coast]] and its [[pounamu]]; the Cardrona Valley led to the natural rock bridge \"Whatatorere\", which was the only place that the [[Kawarau River]] and [[Clutha River|Clutha River / Mata-Au]] could be crossed without boats.<ref name=\"DoC\">{{cite book\n|title=Bannockburn Heritage Landscape Study\n|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/Documents/science-and-technical/SfC244b.pdf\n|date=2004\n|author=Janet Stephenson, Heather Bauchop, and Peter Petchey\n|page=29\n}}</ref> Native reeds were used to build boats that enabled a swift return downriver to the east coast.\n\nThe Cromwell basin supported a large population of [[moa]], which were hunted to extinction about 500 years ago.<ref name=\"DoC\"/>\n\nUntil the early nineteenth century, W\u0101naka was visited annually by [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] who sought [[pounamu]] in the mountains above the [[Haast River]] and hunted eels and birds over summer, returning to the east coast by descending the [[Clutha River|Clutha River / Mata-Au]] in reed boats.<ref name=TeAraOtagoMaori>\n{{cite encyclopedia\n  |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/otago-region/page-4 \n| author=Malcolm McKinnon\n| title=Otago region - M\u0101ori history and whaling\n| encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|accessdate=2017-07-11}}</ref>  Ng\u0101i Tahu use of the land was ended by [[History of the Otago Region#Ngati Toa invasions|attacks by North Island tribes]].<ref name=\"DoC\"/> In 1836, the [[Ngati Tama]] chief [[Te Puoho-o-te-rangi|Te Puoho]] led a 100-person war party, armed with muskets, down the West Coast and over the Haast Pass: they fell on the Ng\u0101i Tahu encampment between Lake Wanaka and [[Lake H\u0101wea]], capturing 10 people and killing and eating two children.<ref name=Smith1910>{{cite book\n| title=History and Traditions of the Maoris of the West Coast North Island of New Zealand Prior to 1840\n|author=S Percy Smith\n|date=1910\n|publisher = Polynesian Society\n|location=New Plymouth \n|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-SmiHist-t1-body1-d21-d7.html\n}}</ref> Although Te Puoho was later killed by the southern Ng\u0101i Tahu leader [[Tuhawaiki]],<ref name=AthollAnderson>{{cite encyclopedia\n|author=Atholl Anderson\n|title =Te Puoho-o-te-rangi\n|volume =1\n|year=1990\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand \n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1t59/te-puoho-o-te-rangi\n|accessdate =2017-07-11}}</ref> M\u0101ori seasonal visits to the area ceased.\n\nThe first European to see the lake was Nathaniel Chalmers in 1853.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |author=Jock Phillips\n|title=European exploration - Otago and Southland\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/european-exploration/page-7\n|accessdate=2017-07-11\n}}\n</ref> Guided by Reko and Kaikoura, he walked from Tuturau ([[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]]) to the lake via the [[Kawarau River]]. However he was stricken by dysentery, so his guides returned him down the Clutha in a reed boat.<ref name=\"TeAraNC\">\n{{cite encyclopedia\n|author=Roger Frazer\n|title=Chalmers, Nathanael\n|series=Dictionary of New Zealand Biography \n|volume=1\n|date=1990\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1c11/chalmers-nathanael\n|accessdate=13 July 2017\n}}</ref>\n\nBy 1861, several sheep stations had been established in around the south end of the lake, and in 1862, the lake itself was surveyed in a whaleboat.<ref name=\"TEARA\"/> The early European name was Lake Pembroke.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=OW18890425.2.62&cl=&srpos=0&e=-------10--1----0-all&st=1%7CPASSIM|title=Papers Past - PASSIM NOTES. (Otago Witness, 1889-04-25)|first=National Library of New|last=Zealand|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz}}</ref>\n\n===Current use and tourism===\n[[File:Lake Wanaka.jpg|thumb|244px|right|Lake W\u0101naka on an overcast day.]]\n\nIn addition to ongoing sheep farming, the lake is now a popular resort, and is much used in the summer for [[fishing]], boating and [[human swimming|swimming]]. The nearby mountains and fast-flowing rivers allow for [[Adventure travel|adventure tourism]] year-round, with [[jetboat]]ing and [[skiing]] facilities located nearby.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lakewanaka.co.nz/|title=Wanaka Tourism}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]] airport close by, tourism mirrors that of the surrounding areas.\n\n===Conservation===\nAs one of the few lakes in the South Island with an unmodified shoreline, the lake is protected by special legislation, the Lake Wanaka Preservation Act of 1973. The Act established a 'Guardians of Lake Wanaka' group, appointed by the Minister of Conservation, which advises on measures to protect the lake.<ref>[http://www.doc.govt.nz/about-doc/role/corporate-publications/briefings-to-new-ministers-archive/briefing-to-the-incoming-minister-of-conservation-2011/6-institutional-arrangements/6_1-statutory-bodies/ Briefing to the incoming Minister of Conservation 2011 - containing information about Statutory bodies, including the Guardians] (from the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website, Friday 14 December 2012)</ref>\n\nOxygen weed (''[[Lagarosiphon major]]''), an aquarium plant and [[invasive species]] native to Southern Africa, has been a problem in the lake's ecosystem for some time. Attempts to eradicate the weed have not been successful. Substantial [[dredging|suction dredging]] operations have shown promise, but tend to miss isolated spots which then regrow into larger weed beds.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.linz.govt.nz/docs/crownproperty/biosecurity/lake-wanaka-assessment-2006.pdf |title= Assessment of the 2005/06 ''Lagarosiphon major'' programme in Lake Wanaka |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090920235224/http://www.linz.govt.nz/docs/crownproperty/biosecurity/lake-wanaka-assessment-2006.pdf |archivedate= 2009-09-20 }}&nbsp;{{small|(1.20&nbsp;[[Mebibyte|MiB]])}} ([[National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research|NIWA]] report, June 2006, from the [[Land Information New Zealand]] website)</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Wanaka pan.jpg|600px|View of Lake W\u0101naka, New Zealand}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n\"That Wanaka Tree\" - a [[willow]] growing just inside the lake - is a tourist attraction in its own right, featuring on many tourists' [[Instagram]] feeds.<ref>\n  {{cite news |title=Wanaka's famous Instagram tree attacked with a saw \n     |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/18/wanakas-famous-instagram-tree-attacked-with-a-saw \n     |accessdate=18 April 2020 \n     |publisher=The Guardian\n  }}\n</ref> The tree had its lower branches cut by vandals in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marcus|first=Lilit|url=https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/wanaka-tree-new-zealand-vandalism-intl-hnk/index.html|title=New Zealand's most famous tree, 'That Wanaka Tree,' vandalized|date=20 March 2020|work=CNN Travel|accessdate=18 April 2020|url-status=live|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ThatWanakaTree at Sunrise.jpg|thumb|right|That Wanaka Tree]]\n\nThe name of the lake is referenced in the title of the song ''Lake Wanaka'' by [[Israelis|Israeli]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Keren Peles]].<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =\n | date =\n | title = \u05e7\u05e8\u05df \u05e4\u05dc\u05e1 - \u05dc\u05d9\u05d9\u05e7 \u05d5\u05d5\u05d0\u05e0\u05e7\u05d4 (\u05e7\u05dc\u05d9\u05e4)\n | trans-title = Keren Peles - Lake Wanaka (video music)\n | medium =\n | language = he\n | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g9prCgt9xXM\n | access-date =\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | format =\n | time =\n | location =\n | publisher =\n | id =\n | isbn =\n | oclc =\n | quote =\n | ref =\n}}</ref>\n\n===In film===\n\nThe region has been the setting for many international films, including ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasons.co.nz/wanaka/the-lord-of-the-rings-location-tarras-and-wanaka|title=The Lord of the Rings Location: Tarras & Wanaka}}</ref> ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newzealand.com/ie/feature/the-hobbit-trilogy-filming-locations/|title=The Hobbit Trilogy Filming Locations}}</ref> the ''Legend of S'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/regions/wanaka/chinese-fantasy-filming-wanaka|author=Otago Daily Times|access-date=27 January 2018|title=Chinese fantasy filming in Wanaka|date=2017-05-05}}</ref> and ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/travel/destinations/nz/89336353/witherspoon-winfrey-and-kaling-in-wanaka-and-lake-hawea|title=Witherspoon, Winfrey and Kaling in Wanaka and Lake Hawea}}</ref> Lake W\u0101naka repeatedly featured in the movie ''[[Mission: Impossible III]]'' as a location the lead couple visited and as the answer to [[Tom Cruise]]'s question on the phone to verify the identity of his wife.\n\nThe New Zealand cook and author [[Annabel Langbein]], who owns a small estate at the side of the lake, filmed her series ''The Free Range Cook'' and ''Simple Pleasures'' here.\n\n===As a reported refuge===\nNew Zealand has been reported to be a favoured refuge for the 'super rich' in the event of a cataclysm.<ref>\n  {{cite journal |last1=Osnos |first1=Evan \n    |title=Doomsday Prep for the Super-Rich \n    |journal=The New Yorker |date=23 January 2017 |issue=30 January 2017 \n    |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/01/30/doomsday-prep-for-the-super-rich |accessdate=18 April 2020\n  }}\n</ref> One such [[High-net-worth individual|high net worth individual]] is [[Peter Thiel]], who purchased {{convert|193|hectare|acre}} of lakeside land in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Facebook billionaire Peter Thiel a Kiwi citizen, owns Wanaka estate |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11787741 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |publisher=New Zealand Herald}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lakes of New Zealand]]\n*[[List of lakes in New Zealand]]\n*[[Otago Region#Geography|Otago Geography]]\n*[[Sentinel Peak (New Zealand)]]\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:W\u0101naka, Lake}}\n[[Category:Lakes of Otago]]\n[[Category:Wanaka]]\n[[Category:Clutha River]]\n", "name_user": "Rangatira80", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn popular culture:\"The name of the lake is referenced\" -> \"The lake is referenced\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_W%C4%81naka"}
{"title_page": "M. V. Frunze Military Academy", "text_new": "{{short description|Military academy of the Russian Armed Forces}}\n{{Infobox university \n|image          = File:Moscow FrunzeAcademy h46.jpg\n|image_size     = 300px\n|name           = M. V. Frunze Military Academy\n|native_name    = \u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u041c. \u0412. \u0424\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0437\u0435\n|motto          = \n|established    = 1918\n|closed         = 1998\n|type           = [[Military college|Military academy]]\n|chancellor     = \n|head_label     = \n|head           = \n|principal      = \n|city           = [[Moscow]]\n|state          = \n|country        = Russia\n|staff          = \n|students       = \n|campus         = \n|affiliations   = \n|website        = \n|nickname        = \n|coor            = {{coord|55|44|17|N|37|34|40|E|display=inline,title}}\n|telephone       = \n|address         =   4 {{ill|Devichego Polya Drive|ru|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0437\u0434 \u0414\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447\u044c\u0435\u0433\u043e \u041f\u043e\u043b\u044f}}\n|footnotes=\n}}\n\nThe '''M. V. Frunze Military Academy''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u041c. \u0412. \u0424\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0437\u0435}}), or in full the '''Military Order of Lenin and the October Revolution, Red Banner, Order of Suvorov Academy in the name of M. V. Frunze''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u041e\u043a\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044e\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0451\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f, \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0443\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u041c. \u0412. \u0424\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0437\u0435}}), was a [[Military college|military academy]] of the [[Soviet Armed Forces|Soviet]] and later the [[Russian Armed Forces]].\n\nEstablished in 1918 to train officers for the newly-formed [[Red Army]], the academy became one of the most prestigious military educational institutions in the Soviet Union. At first titled the General Staff Academy of the Red Army, taking on a similar role to its pre-revolutionary predecessor, the [[General Staff Academy (Imperial Russia)|Imperial Nicholas Military Academy]], it was renamed the Military Academy in 1921 and then the M. V. Frunze Military Academy in 1925, honouring [[Mikhail Frunze]], who had been a commandant of the academy. It became a higher staff college with the addition of courses for senior command officers in the 1930s, before these were transferred to the newly-formed [[Military Academy of the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Russia|Military Academy of the General Staff]] in 1936. By this time many of the Red Army's most senior commanders were graduates of the academy. During the Second World War large numbers of staff and students were called up to fight. Many won decorations and awards, including 244 [[Hero of the Soviet Union|Heroes of the Soviet Union]], and 18 twice Heroes of the Soviet Union. Training and research at the academy continued throughout the war.\n\nThe academy continued to train senior officers for the Soviet Armed Forces after the war, acting as a stepping stone for those tipped for high command before they attended the Military Academy of the General Staff. It was ranked as the most prestigious of all the Soviet military academies, taking officers ranked captain or above for a three-year course of study to prepare them for higher commands. The academy also offered research and postgraduate degrees in various aspects of military studies. Between 1934 and 1988, 722 graduates of the academy were awarded the title of Hero of the Soviet Union, while the academy itself received the [[Order of Lenin]], the [[Order of Suvorov]] First Class, and the [[Order of the October Revolution]].\n\nThe academy continued to operate after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] in 1991, until being merged with the [[Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy|Malinovsky Military Armoured Forces Academy]] and the [[Vystrel course|Vystrel officer training courses]] in 1998 to form the [[Combined Arms Academy of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mikhail Frunze by Isaak Brodsky (1929).jpg|thumb|right|[[Mikhail Frunze]], a posthumous 1929 portrait by [[Isaak Brodsky]]. Commandant of the academy between 1924 and 1925, and subsequently its namesake.]]\nThe existence of an academy for the training of command and staff officers was an Imperial-era innovation, carried out at the  [[General Staff Academy (Imperial Russia)|Imperial Nicholas Military Academy]]. With the outbreak of the First World War, classes at the academy ceased. Special wartime courses for staff officers were briefly instituted from 30 October 1916 on the initiative of General [[Mikhail Alekseyev]], but closed in late April 1917.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\nThe early experiences of the Red Army during the first stages of the [[Russian Civil War]] demonstrated the inadvisability of entrusting battlefield commands to former workers and soldiers, who had little experience of tactics or of leading men.<ref name=\"Ist\">{{cite web|url=http://ova.mil.ru/info/Istoriya|title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f|work=\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0431\u043d\u043e-\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0421\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \u00ab\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u00bb|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Ministry of Defence]]|language=Russian|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> On 7 October 1918 the [[Revolutionary Military Council]] ordered the foundation of the General Staff Academy of the Red Army, based in Moscow and taking on the functions of the Imperial-era [[General Staff Academy (Imperial Russia)|General Staff Academy]].<ref name=\"Ist\"/> The first intake of students, who joined on 25 November that year, numbered 183, with the official opening of the academy taking place on 8 December 1918.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\nIt was renamed the Military Academy of the Red Army on 5 August 1921, and then the M. V. Frunze Military Academy on 5 November 1925, honouring [[Mikhail Frunze]] who had commanded the academy between 19 April 1924 until his death on 31 October 1925.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Higher courses were added in the 1930s to provide advanced training in military science for earlier graduates.<ref name=\"S&S\">{{cite book|last=Scott & Scott|title=The Armed Forces of the USSR|pages=356\u20137}}</ref> These courses became the basis for the [[Military Academy of the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Russia|Military Academy of the General Staff]], which was split from the Frunze Military Academy in 1936.<ref name=\"S&S\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Shukman|title=Stalin's Generals|page=2}}</ref> On 18 January 1934 the academy was awarded the [[Order of Lenin]], and became known as the Red Banner Order of Lenin Military Academy named after M.V. Frunze.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\nFrom 1922 the academy had occupied a location on {{ill|Prechistenka|ru|\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430|lt=Prechistenka Street}}, in the expropriated {{ill|Dolgorukov Palace|ru|\u0414\u043e\u043c \u0414\u043e\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u043d\u0430 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0435}}.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> A new building was designed by [[Lev Rudnev]], with the academy moving into it in August 1937, and training beginning on 1 September.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> The academy, in common with many other Soviet institutions of military education, suffered during the [[Great Purges]] of the late 1930s, with the commandant and many of the senior department heads and professors being executed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Scott & Scott|title=The Armed Forces of the USSR|page=334}}</ref> By 1941 more than 7,500 personnel had graduated from the academy.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\n===Wartime===\nWith the [[Operation Barbarossa|German invasion of the Soviet Union]] in June 1941, many of the academy's students and teachers were posted to active roles. Between June and July 1941 43 generals and 167 senior officers were dispatched to the front from the academy, many of them taking up high positions in the Soviet defence effort.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Four were appointed regimental commanders, eleven as infantry brigade commanders and chiefs of staff, forty-two as divisional chiefs of staff, twenty-one as division commanders, six as corps commanders and chiefs of staff, twenty-two to army headquarters and forty-four to front headquarters.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Those that remained in the academy were soon occupied in preparing defensive lines and fortifications around Moscow, and in training militia units.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n[[File:\u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0432.jpg|thumb|left|[[Georgy Zhukov]] and [[Ivan Konev]] in 1943, both graduates of the academy]]\nTraining efforts continued during the war, with a shortened programme for command officers to link the regiment and division levels, and from 1944 onwards, for division and corps levels. To meet shortages in personnel, those who had a secondary education and qualified as junior lieutenants were also enrolled.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> As the war progressed, by 1944 training was also provided for combined-arms officers in division and corps units.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Scientific research work continued throughout the war, taking in experience gathered during combat operations and producing summaries of frontline combat activity, manuals on tactics, military geography, and the history of military art.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> On 21 February 1945 the academy was awarded the [[Order of Suvorov]] First Class by the [[Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the USSR]], and became the Red Banner Order of Lenin and Order of Suvorov First Class Military Academy named after M.V. Frunze.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\n===Post war===\nAfter the war the academy continued to train combined-arms officers, establishing a faculty to incorporate tactical and strategic innovations developed during the Second World War, and subsequent advances in science and technology.<ref>{{cite book|last=Scott & Scott|title=The Armed Forces of the USSR|page=38}}</ref> With developments in nuclear weapons, the academy trained officers in the use of tank, motorized rifle units, aviation and artillery in a possible nuclear war.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> In 1978 it was awarded the [[Order of the October Revolution]], becoming the Orders of Lenin and October Revolution, the Red Banner Order of Suvorov Military Academy named after M.V. Frunze.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\nThe academy continued to operate after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] in 1991, training officers for the [[Russian Armed Forces]]. On 29 August 1998, in accordance with government decree No. 1009, the academy was combined with the [[Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy|Malinovsky Military Armoured Forces Academy]] and the [[Vystrel course|Vystrel officer training courses]] to form the [[Combined Arms Academy of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation]].<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:178-\u0439 \u043e\u043c\u0441\u0431 6-\u0439 \u0433\u0432.\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0431\u0440 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435.1981\u0433.JPG|thumb|right|Soviet troops and officers in 1981. By the 1980s many of the higher-ranking officers in the Soviet Ground Forces were graduates of the academy]]\nWith the splitting of the higher strategic courses into the new Military Academy of the General Staff in 1936, the Frunze Military Academy concentrated on preparing officers for combined arms warfare.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> The majority of students were from the [[Soviet Army|Soviet Ground Forces]], though there were those from other services, particularly the [[Soviet Air Forces|Air Forces]] and [[Soviet Air Defence Forces|Air Defence Forces]].<ref name=\"S&S\"/> A late 1970s work recorded that a third of students had graduated from one of the country's [[Suvorov Military School]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Scott & Scott|title=The Armed Forces of the USSR|page=336}}</ref> Students generally entered for a three-year course of study, usually at the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Ist\"/><ref name=\"S&S\"/> By the time they had finished their studies, graduates usually qualified for promotion to the rank of major. In addition to officers from the Soviet Union, students were also drawn from the armed forces of [[Warsaw Pact]] and other associated countries.<ref name=\"S&S\"/>\n\nDuring the Soviet period the academy had departments on operational-tactical disciplines, [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]], the history of the Communist Party and its work, the history of war and military art, foreign languages, and others.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> Studies were supported by a library containing over two million volumes.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> The academy was also an important centre for military scientific research, offering postgraduate and research programmes leading to the award of [[Candidate of Sciences|candidate]] or [[Doktor nauk|doctoral]] degrees.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> By the late 1970s it was considered the most prestigious of the seventeen Soviet military academies.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> Candidates attended the academy after having graduated from one of the higher military training colleges and spent some time on active service. Having graduated from the academy, and subsequently attained the rank of colonel or similar, the most capable candidates were then considered for entry to the General Staff Academy, and so to the highest ranks and echelons of the Soviet military.<ref>{{cite book|last=Suvorov|title=Inside the Soviet Army|page=430}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Schofield|title=Inside the Soviet Army|page=46}}</ref>\n\n==Faculty==\n[[File:Aleksei Antonov 3.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Aleksei Antonov]], one of a number of academy graduates who returned to take up teaching posts]]\nTeaching faculty at the academy often held senior military ranks alongside higher academic qualifications.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> The commandant of the academy usually held a general's rank, and by the late 1970s between twenty-five and fifty general officers were teaching at the academy.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> Among the early military commanders who taught at the academy was [[Aleksei Antonov]], who was a student at the academy between 1928 and 1931, and returned in December 1938 as a lecturer in the general tactics faculty, becoming a senior lecturer in February 1940 and deputy head of the faculty in January 1941.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shukman|title=Stalin's Generals|pages=14\u201316}}</ref>\n\n==Graduates==\nA number of the first academy graduates went on to high ranks, among whom were future [[Marshal of the Soviet Union|marshals of the Soviet Union]] [[Nikolay Voronov]], [[Kirill Meretskov]], [[Vasily Sokolovsky]] and [[Vasily Chapayev]].<ref name=\"Ist\"/> During the Second World War a total of twenty-four academy graduates had commands of either fronts or armies. Among them were marshals [[Georgy Zhukov]], [[Leonid Govorov]], [[Ivan Konev]], [[Rodion Malinovsky]], Kirill Meretskov, [[Fyodor Tolbukhin]], [[Konstantin Rokossovsky]], [[Army General (Soviet rank)|army generals]] [[Andrey Yeryomenko]], [[Ivan Bagramyan]], and generals [[Hamazasp Babadzhanian]], [[Pavel Batitsky]], [[Pavel Alexeyevich Belov|Pavel Belov]], [[Pavel Batov]], [[Afanasy Beloborodov]], [[Alexander Gorbatov]], [[Mikhail Yefremov (military commander)|Mikhail Yefremov]], [[Lev Dovator]], [[Pyotr Koshevoy]], [[David Dragunsky]], [[Alexander Lizyukov]], [[Issa Pliyev]] and [[Vasily Chuikov]], among others.<ref name=\"Ist\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|title=Stalin's General|pages=35\u20136}}</ref> During the Second World War 244 academy graduates received the title of [[Hero of the Soviet Union]], with a further 18 being awarded the title twice.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Between 1934 and 1988, 722 graduates of the academy were awarded the title of Hero of the Soviet Union.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\n==Heads==\nThe first head of the academy was {{ill|Anton Klimovich|ru|\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447, \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}} a major general and division commander, who had served in the [[Russo-Japanese War|Russo-Japanese]] and [[First World War]]s.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*{{ill|Anton Klimovich|ru|\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447, \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1918-1919)<ref name=\"nach1\">{{cite web|url=https://ova.mil.ru/info/Nachalniki-akademii/1/|title=\u041d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0434\u044b|work=\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0431\u043d\u043e-\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0421\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \u00ab\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u00bb|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Ministry of Defence]]|language=Russian|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*{{ill|Andrei Snesarev|ru|\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432, \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1919-1921)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Mikhail Tukhachevsky]] (1921-1922)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Anatoliy Gekker]] (1922)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Pavel Pavlovich Lebedev|Pavel Lebedev]] (1922-1924)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Mikhail Frunze]] (1924-1925)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Roberts Eidemanis]] (1925-1932)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Boris Shaposhnikov]] (1932-1935)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[August Kork]] (1935-1937)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Nikolay Veryovkin-Rakhalsy]] (1937-1939)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Mikhail Khozin]] (1939-1941)<ref name=\"nach2\">{{cite web|url=https://ova.mil.ru/info/Nachalniki-akademii/2/|title=\u041d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0434\u044b|work=\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0431\u043d\u043e-\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0421\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \u00ab\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u00bb|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Ministry of Defence]]|language=Russian|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Nikolay Veryovkin-Rakhalsy]] (1941-1944)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Nikandr Chibisov]] (1944-1948)<ref name=\"nach2\"/>\n*{{ill|Vyacheslav Tsvetayev|ru|\u0426\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0435\u0432, \u0412\u044f\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1948-1950)<ref name=\"nach2\"/>\n*[[Aleksey Semenovich Zhadov|Aleksey Zhadov]] (1950-1954)<ref name=\"nach2\"/>\n*[[Pavel Kurochkin]] (1954-1968)<ref name=\"S&S\"/><ref name=\"nach2\"/>\n*{{ill|Andrei Stuchenko|ru|\u0421\u0442\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e, \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0422\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1968-1969)<ref name=\"S&S\"/><ref name=\"nach2\"/>\n*[[Alexei Radzievsky]] (1969-1978)<ref name=\"S&S\"/><ref name=\"nach2\"/>\n*{{ill|Pavel Vasilyevich Melnikov|ru|\u041c\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432, \u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|lt=Pavel Melnikov}} (1978-1982)<ref name=\"S&S\"/><ref name=\"nach2\"/>\n*[[Gennady Obaturov]] (1982-1985)<ref name=\"nach2\"/>\n*{{ill|Vladimir Konchits|ru|\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0438\u0446, \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1985-1991)<ref name=\"nach2\"/>\n*[[Vladimir Lobov]] (1991)<ref name=\"nach3\">{{cite web|url=https://ova.mil.ru/info/Nachalniki-akademii/3/|title=\u041d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0434\u044b|work=\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0431\u043d\u043e-\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0421\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \u00ab\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u00bb|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Ministry of Defence]]|language=Russian|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*{{ill|Fyodor Kuzmin|ru|\u041a\u0443\u0437\u044c\u043c\u0438\u043d, \u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1992-1997)<ref name=\"nach3\"/>\n*{{ill|Leonid Zolotov|ru|\u0417\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432, \u041b\u0435\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0434 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1997-1998)<ref name=\"nach3\"/>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{cite book|first=Geoffrey|last=Roberts|authorlink=Geoffrey Roberts|title=Stalin's General: The Life of Georgy Zhukov|isbn=978-184831442-9|publisher=[[Icon Books]]|location=London|year=2012}}\n*{{cite book|first=Harriet Fast|last=Scott|first2=William F.|last2=Scott|title=The Armed Forces of the USSR|edition=2|isbn=0-85368-287-9|publisher=[[Arms and Armour Press]]|location=London|year=1981}}\n*{{cite book|editor=[[Harold Shukman]]|title=Stalin's Generals|isbn=9-781842-125137|publisher=[[Weidenfeld & Nicolson|Phoenix Press]]|location=London|year=1993}}\n*{{cite book|first=Carey |last=Schofield|authorlink=Carey Schofield|title=Inside the Soviet Army|isbn=0-7472-0418-7|publisher=[[Headline Publishing Group|Headline Book Publishing]]|location=London|year=1991}}\n*{{cite book|first=Viktor|last=Suvorov|authorlink=Viktor Suvorov|title=Inside the Soviet Army|isbn=0-586-05978-4|publisher=[[Panther Books]]|location=London|year=1984}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1918]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions disestablished in 1998]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1998]]\n[[Category:Military academies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Military academies of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations awarded the Order of the Red Banner]]\n[[Category:Education and training establishments of the Soviet Ground Forces]]\n[[Category:Stalinist architecture]]\n[[Category:Frunze Military Academy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Military academy of the Russian Armed Forces}}\n{{Infobox university \n|image          = File:Moscow FrunzeAcademy h46.jpg\n|image_size     = 300px\n|name           = M. V. Frunze Military Academy\n|native_name    = \u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u041c. \u0412. \u0424\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0437\u0435\n|motto          = \n|established    = 1918\n|closed         = 1998\n|type           = [[Military college|Military academy]]\n|chancellor     = \n|head_label     = \n|head           = \n|principal      = \n|city           = [[Moscow]]\n|state          = \n|country        = Russia\n|staff          = \n|students       = \n|campus         = \n|affiliations   = \n|website        = \n|nickname        = \n|coor            = {{coord|55|44|17|N|37|34|40|E|display=inline,title}}\n|telephone       = \n|address         =   4 {{ill|Devichego Polya Drive|ru|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0437\u0434 \u0414\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447\u044c\u0435\u0433\u043e \u041f\u043e\u043b\u044f}}\n|footnotes=\n}}\n\nThe '''M. V. Frunze Military Academy''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u041c. \u0412. \u0424\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0437\u0435}}), or in full the '''Military Order of Lenin and the October Revolution, Red Banner, Order of Suvorov Academy in the name of M. V. Frunze''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u041e\u043a\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044e\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0451\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f, \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0443\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u041c. \u0412. \u0424\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0437\u0435}}), was a [[Military college|military academy]] of the [[Soviet Armed Forces|Soviet]] and later the [[Russian Armed Forces]].\n\nEstablished in 1918 to train officers for the newly-formed [[Red Army]], the academy became one of the most prestigious military educational institutions in the Soviet Union. At first titled the General Staff Academy of the Red Army, taking on a similar role to its pre-revolutionary predecessor, the [[General Staff Academy (Imperial Russia)|Imperial Nicholas Military Academy]], it was renamed the Military Academy in 1921 and then the M. V. Frunze Military Academy in 1925, honouring [[Mikhail Frunze]], who had been a commandant of the academy. It became a higher staff college with the addition of courses for senior command officers in the 1930s, before these were transferred to the newly-formed [[Military Academy of the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Russia|Military Academy of the General Staff]] in 1936. By this time many of the Red Army's most senior commanders were graduates of the academy. During the Second World War large numbers of staff and students were called up to fight. Many won decorations and awards, including 244 [[Hero of the Soviet Union|Heroes of the Soviet Union]], and 18 twice Heroes of the Soviet Union. Training and research at the academy continued throughout the war.\n\nThe academy continued to train senior officers for the Soviet Armed Forces after the war, acting as a stepping stone for those tipped for high command before they attended the Military Academy of the General Staff. It was ranked as the most prestigious of all the Soviet military academies, taking officers ranked captain or above for a three-year course of study to prepare them for higher commands. The academy also offered research and postgraduate degrees in various aspects of military studies. Between 1934 and 1988, 722 graduates of the academy were awarded the title of Hero of the Soviet Union, while the academy itself received the [[Order of Lenin]], the [[Order of Suvorov]] First Class, and the [[Order of the October Revolution]].\n\nThe academy continued to operate after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] in 1991, until being merged with the [[Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy|Malinovsky Military Armoured Forces Academy]] and the [[Vystrel course|Vystrel officer training courses]] in 1998 to form the [[Combined Arms Academy of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mikhail Frunze by Isaak Brodsky (1929).jpg|thumb|right|[[Mikhail Frunze]], a posthumous 1929 portrait by [[Isaak Brodsky]]. Commandant of the academy between 1924 and 1925, and subsequently its namesake.]]\nThe existence of an academy for the training of command and staff officers was an Imperial-era innovation, carried out at the  [[General Staff Academy (Imperial Russia)|Imperial Nicholas Military Academy]]. With the outbreak of the First World War, classes at the academy ceased. Special wartime courses for staff officers were briefly instituted from 30 October 1916 on the initiative of General [[Mikhail Alekseyev]], but closed in late April 1917.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\nThe early experiences of the Red Army during the first stages of the [[Russian Civil War]] demonstrated the inadvisability of entrusting battlefield commands to former workers and soldiers, who had little experience of tactics or of leading men.<ref name=\"Ist\">{{cite web|url=http://ova.mil.ru/info/Istoriya|title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f|work=\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0431\u043d\u043e-\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0421\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \u00ab\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u00bb|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Ministry of Defence]]|language=Russian|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> On 7 October 1918 the [[Revolutionary Military Council]] ordered the foundation of the General Staff Academy of the Red Army, based in Moscow and taking on the functions of the Imperial-era [[General Staff Academy (Imperial Russia)|General Staff Academy]].<ref name=\"Ist\"/> The first intake of students, who joined on 25 November that year, numbered 183, with the official opening of the academy taking place on 8 December 1918.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\nIt was renamed the Military Academy of the Red Army on 5 August 1921, and then the M. V. Frunze Military Academy on 5 November 1925, honouring [[Mikhail Frunze]] who had commanded the academy between 19 April 1924 until his death on 31 October 1925.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Higher courses were added in the 1930s to provide advanced training in military science for earlier graduates.<ref name=\"S&S\">{{cite book|last=Scott & Scott|title=The Armed Forces of the USSR|pages=356\u20137}}</ref> These courses became the basis for the [[Military Academy of the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Russia|Military Academy of the General Staff]], which was split from the Frunze Military Academy in 1936.<ref name=\"S&S\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Shukman|title=Stalin's Generals|page=2}}</ref> On 18 January 1934 the academy was awarded the [[Order of Lenin]], and became known as the Red Banner Order of Lenin Military Academy named after M.V. Frunze.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\nFrom 1922 the academy had occupied a location on {{ill|Prechistenka|ru|\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430|lt=Prechistenka Street}}, in the expropriated {{ill|Dolgorukov Palace|ru|\u0414\u043e\u043c \u0414\u043e\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u043d\u0430 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0435}}.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> A new building was designed by [[Lev Rudnev]], with the academy moving into it in August 1937, and training beginning on 1 September.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> The academy, in common with many other Soviet institutions of military education, suffered during the [[Great Purges]] of the late 1930s, with the commandant and many of the senior department heads and professors being executed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Scott & Scott|title=The Armed Forces of the USSR|page=334}}</ref> By 1941 more than 7,500 personnel had graduated from the academy.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\n===Wartime===\nWith the [[Operation Barbarossa|Axis invasion of the Soviet Union]] in June 1941, many of the academy's students and teachers were posted to active roles. Between June and July 1941 43 generals and 167 senior officers were dispatched to the front from the academy, many of them taking up high positions in the Soviet defence effort.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Four were appointed regimental commanders, eleven as infantry brigade commanders and chiefs of staff, forty-two as divisional chiefs of staff, twenty-one as division commanders, six as corps commanders and chiefs of staff, twenty-two to army headquarters and forty-four to front headquarters.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Those that remained in the academy were soon occupied in preparing defensive lines and fortifications around Moscow, and in training militia units.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n[[File:\u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0432.jpg|thumb|left|[[Georgy Zhukov]] and [[Ivan Konev]] in 1943, both graduates of the academy]]\nTraining efforts continued during the war, with a shortened programme for command officers to link the regiment and division levels, and from 1944 onwards, for division and corps levels. To meet shortages in personnel, those who had a secondary education and qualified as junior lieutenants were also enrolled.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> As the war progressed, by 1944 training was also provided for combined-arms officers in division and corps units.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Scientific research work continued throughout the war, taking in experience gathered during combat operations and producing summaries of frontline combat activity, manuals on tactics, military geography, and the history of military art.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> On 21 February 1945 the academy was awarded the [[Order of Suvorov]] First Class by the [[Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the USSR]], and became the Red Banner Order of Lenin and Order of Suvorov First Class Military Academy named after M.V. Frunze.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\n===Post war===\nAfter the war the academy continued to train combined-arms officers, establishing a faculty to incorporate tactical and strategic innovations developed during the Second World War, and subsequent advances in science and technology.<ref>{{cite book|last=Scott & Scott|title=The Armed Forces of the USSR|page=38}}</ref> With developments in nuclear weapons, the academy trained officers in the use of tank, motorized rifle units, aviation and artillery in a possible nuclear war.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> In 1978 it was awarded the [[Order of the October Revolution]], becoming the Orders of Lenin and October Revolution, the Red Banner Order of Suvorov Military Academy named after M.V. Frunze.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\nThe academy continued to operate after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] in 1991, training officers for the [[Russian Armed Forces]]. On 29 August 1998, in accordance with government decree No. 1009, the academy was combined with the [[Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy|Malinovsky Military Armoured Forces Academy]] and the [[Vystrel course|Vystrel officer training courses]] to form the [[Combined Arms Academy of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation]].<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:178-\u0439 \u043e\u043c\u0441\u0431 6-\u0439 \u0433\u0432.\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0431\u0440 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435.1981\u0433.JPG|thumb|right|Soviet troops and officers in 1981. By the 1980s many of the higher-ranking officers in the Soviet Ground Forces were graduates of the academy]]\nWith the splitting of the higher strategic courses into the new Military Academy of the General Staff in 1936, the Frunze Military Academy concentrated on preparing officers for combined arms warfare.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> The majority of students were from the [[Soviet Army|Soviet Ground Forces]], though there were those from other services, particularly the [[Soviet Air Forces|Air Forces]] and [[Soviet Air Defence Forces|Air Defence Forces]].<ref name=\"S&S\"/> A late 1970s work recorded that a third of students had graduated from one of the country's [[Suvorov Military School]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Scott & Scott|title=The Armed Forces of the USSR|page=336}}</ref> Students generally entered for a three-year course of study, usually at the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Ist\"/><ref name=\"S&S\"/> By the time they had finished their studies, graduates usually qualified for promotion to the rank of major. In addition to officers from the Soviet Union, students were also drawn from the armed forces of [[Warsaw Pact]] and other associated countries.<ref name=\"S&S\"/>\n\nDuring the Soviet period the academy had departments on operational-tactical disciplines, [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]], the history of the Communist Party and its work, the history of war and military art, foreign languages, and others.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> Studies were supported by a library containing over two million volumes.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> The academy was also an important centre for military scientific research, offering postgraduate and research programmes leading to the award of [[Candidate of Sciences|candidate]] or [[Doktor nauk|doctoral]] degrees.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> By the late 1970s it was considered the most prestigious of the seventeen Soviet military academies.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> Candidates attended the academy after having graduated from one of the higher military training colleges and spent some time on active service. Having graduated from the academy, and subsequently attained the rank of colonel or similar, the most capable candidates were then considered for entry to the General Staff Academy, and so to the highest ranks and echelons of the Soviet military.<ref>{{cite book|last=Suvorov|title=Inside the Soviet Army|page=430}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Schofield|title=Inside the Soviet Army|page=46}}</ref>\n\n==Faculty==\n[[File:Aleksei Antonov 3.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Aleksei Antonov]], one of a number of academy graduates who returned to take up teaching posts]]\nTeaching faculty at the academy often held senior military ranks alongside higher academic qualifications.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> The commandant of the academy usually held a general's rank, and by the late 1970s between twenty-five and fifty general officers were teaching at the academy.<ref name=\"S&S\"/> Among the early military commanders who taught at the academy was [[Aleksei Antonov]], who was a student at the academy between 1928 and 1931, and returned in December 1938 as a lecturer in the general tactics faculty, becoming a senior lecturer in February 1940 and deputy head of the faculty in January 1941.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shukman|title=Stalin's Generals|pages=14\u201316}}</ref>\n\n==Graduates==\nA number of the first academy graduates went on to high ranks, among whom were future [[Marshal of the Soviet Union|marshals of the Soviet Union]] [[Nikolay Voronov]], [[Kirill Meretskov]], [[Vasily Sokolovsky]] and [[Vasily Chapayev]].<ref name=\"Ist\"/> During the Second World War a total of twenty-four academy graduates had commands of either fronts or armies. Among them were marshals [[Georgy Zhukov]], [[Leonid Govorov]], [[Ivan Konev]], [[Rodion Malinovsky]], Kirill Meretskov, [[Fyodor Tolbukhin]], [[Konstantin Rokossovsky]], [[Army General (Soviet rank)|army generals]] [[Andrey Yeryomenko]], [[Ivan Bagramyan]], and generals [[Hamazasp Babadzhanian]], [[Pavel Batitsky]], [[Pavel Alexeyevich Belov|Pavel Belov]], [[Pavel Batov]], [[Afanasy Beloborodov]], [[Alexander Gorbatov]], [[Mikhail Yefremov (military commander)|Mikhail Yefremov]], [[Lev Dovator]], [[Pyotr Koshevoy]], [[David Dragunsky]], [[Alexander Lizyukov]], [[Issa Pliyev]] and [[Vasily Chuikov]], among others.<ref name=\"Ist\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|title=Stalin's General|pages=35\u20136}}</ref> During the Second World War 244 academy graduates received the title of [[Hero of the Soviet Union]], with a further 18 being awarded the title twice.<ref name=\"Ist\"/> Between 1934 and 1988, 722 graduates of the academy were awarded the title of Hero of the Soviet Union.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n\n==Heads==\nThe first head of the academy was {{ill|Anton Klimovich|ru|\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447, \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}} a major general and division commander, who had served in the [[Russo-Japanese War|Russo-Japanese]] and [[First World War]]s.<ref name=\"Ist\"/>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*{{ill|Anton Klimovich|ru|\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447, \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1918-1919)<ref name=\"nach1\">{{cite web|url=https://ova.mil.ru/info/Nachalniki-akademii/1/|title=\u041d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0434\u044b|work=\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0431\u043d\u043e-\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0421\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \u00ab\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u00bb|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Ministry of Defence]]|language=Russian|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*{{ill|Andrei Snesarev|ru|\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432, \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1919-1921)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Mikhail Tukhachevsky]] (1921-1922)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Anatoliy Gekker]] (1922)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Pavel Pavlovich Lebedev|Pavel Lebedev]] (1922-1924)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Mikhail Frunze]] (1924-1925)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Roberts Eidemanis]] (1925-1932)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Boris Shaposhnikov]] (1932-1935)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[August Kork]] (1935-1937)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Nikolay Veryovkin-Rakhalsy]] (1937-1939)<ref name=\"nach1\"/>\n*[[Mikhail Khozin]] (1939-1941)<ref name=\"nach2\">{{cite web|url=https://ova.mil.ru/